target_text: and he took and sent messes unto them from before him: but benjamin's mess was five times so much as any of theirs. and they drank, and were merry with him.

source_text: sa vakaroti ira na veiqaravi ena nona vale ka tukuna, "vakatawana na kakana ena nodra taga na tamata, na kena levu ga e rawa ni ra kauta, me biu tale na nodra i lavo ena gusu ni nodra taga.
target_text: and he commanded the steward of his house, saying, fill the men's sacks with food, as much as they can carry, and put every man's money in his sack's mouth.

source_text: "me biu na noqu bilo siliva ena gusu ni nona taga o koya e gone duadua kei na nona i lavo talega ni sila. " sa caka me vaka na vosa sa tukuna o joseva.
target_text: and put my cup, the silver cup, in the sack's mouth of the youngest, and his corn money. and he did according to the word that joseph had spoken.

source_text: ni sa kida na mataka, era sa vakatalai yani na tamata kei na nodra asa.
target_text: as soon as the morning was light, the men were sent away, they and their asses.

source_text: ni ra sa lako tani yani mai na koro, ka e se bera sara na nodra lako yani vakayawa, sa tukuna o joseva vua na dauveiqaravi "tu cake, cici muri ira na tamata, ni o sa toboki ira, tukuna vaka oqo, 'na cava dou sa caka ca kina ena vuku ni vinaka?
target_text: and when they were gone out of the city, and not yet far off, joseph said unto his steward, up, follow after the men; and when thou dost overtake them, say unto them, wherefore have ye rewarded evil for good?

source_text: 'sa sega beka ni oqo na nona ka ni gunu na noqu turaga “oqo talega sa dau caka i sausau kina o koya, dou sa caka ca sara ena vuku ni ka oqo. '"
target_text: is not this it in which my lord drinketh, and whereby indeed he divineth? ye have done evil in so doing.

source_text: sa toboki ira sara ka cavuta na veivosa oqori.
target_text: and he overtook them, and he spake unto them these same words.

source_text: era sa tukuna vua, "na cava na vuna sa cavuta kina na vosa oqori na noqu turaga? me kua sara vei keimami na nomuni tamata na cakava na veika oqori.
target_text: and they said unto him, wherefore saith my lord these words? god forbid that thy servants should do according to this thing:

source_text: "raica keimami sa kauta lesu tale mai, mai na vanua o kenani nai lavo sa kune ena neimami taga, kila rawa vakacava me keimami butakoca na siliva se koula mai na vale ni neimami turaga?
target_text: behold, the money, which we found in our sacks' mouths, we brought again unto thee out of the land of canaan: how then should we steal out of thy lord's house silver or gold?

source_text: "vei koya ena kune vua, me na vakamatei, ka keimami na wili me nona bobula na noqu turaga. "
target_text: with whomsoever of thy servants it be found, both let him die, and we also will be my lord's bondmen.

source_text: sa tukuna na tamata, "sa na yaco me vaka na nomudou vosa, o koya sa na kune vua, ena noqu bobula, o kemudou dou na sega ni beitaki. "
target_text: and he said, now also let it be according unto your words: he with whom it is found shall be my servant; and ye shall be blameless.

source_text: era sa vakatotolo sara ka biuta kece ki ra na nodra dui usausa, ka dolava na nodra dui taga.
target_text: then they speedily took down every man his sack to the ground, and opened every man his sack.

source_text: sa tekivu mai vua sa qase ki vua sara sa gone: na bilo sa kune ena taga nei penijamini.
target_text: and he searched, and began at the eldest, and left at the youngest: and the cup was found in benjamin's sack.

source_text: era sa basuraka na nodra i sulu, ka era sa vakavodoka tale na nodra dui asa ka lesu ki na koro.
target_text: then they rent their clothes, and laded every man his ass, and returned to the city.

source_text: o juta kei ira na tacina, era sa lako mai ki na vale nei joseva, (ni se tiko ga e vale) era sa cuva vua ki na qele.
target_text: and judah and his brethren came to joseph's house; for he was yet there: and they fell before him on the ground.

source_text: sa tukuna vei ira o joseva. "na cava dou sa cakava oqo? dou sa sega beka ni kila ni tamata vakataki au, sa dau caka i sausau? "
target_text: and joseph said unto them, what deed is this that ye have done? wot ye not that such a man as i can certainly divine?

source_text: sa tukuna yani o juta, "na cava me keitou tukuna vua na neitou turaga? na vosa cava? se me keitou vakagalalataki keitou vakacava? na kalou sa raica na neitou cala, sai keitou oqo “keitou sa nona bobula na noqu turaga, oi keitou kei koya talega sa kune vua na bilo nei koya na noqu turaga. "
target_text: and judah said, what shall we say unto my lord? what shall we speak? or how shall we clear ourselves? god hath found out the iniquity of thy servants: behold, we are my lord's servants, both we, and he also with whom the cup is found.

source_text: sa tukuna mai o joseva: "me kua sara vei au oqori, me'u cakava na ka vaka oqori, o koya ga sa kune vua na bilo, ena noqu bobula “vei kemudou, dou lako ena vakacegu vei tamamudou. "
target_text: and he said, god forbid that i should do so: but the man in whose hand the cup is found, he shall be my servant; and as for you, get you up in peace unto your father.

source_text: sa toso voleka o juta vei joseva ka tukuna, "noqu turaga, me'u vosa mada ka mo ni vakarorogo, me kua ni katakata na nomuni cudru vua na nomuni tamata; ni kemuni sa vakataki fero ga.
target_text: then judah came near unto him, and said, oh my lord, let thy servant, i pray thee, speak a word in my lord's ears, and let not thine anger burn against thy servant: for thou art even as pharaoh.

source_text: "na noqu turaga sa taroga na nomuni tamata ka vaka, 'edua tiko na tamamudou, e dua tiko na tacimudou? '
target_text: my lord asked his servants, saying, have ye a father, or a brother?

source_text: "keitou sa sauma vua na turaga, 'sa tiko na tamai keitou ka sa qase sara, sa tiko talega na taci keitou, e luvei tamai keitou ni sa qase sara, e gone sara, sa mate o tacina, o koya ga na luvei tinana ka sa rui lomani koya vakalevu o tamana. '
target_text: and we said unto my lord, we have a father, an old man, and a child of his old age, a little one; and his brother is dead, and he alone is left of his mother, and his father loveth him.

source_text: "o ni sa tukuna vei ira na nomuni tamata, 'me kau sobu mai me raici koya na matamuni. '
target_text: and thou saidst unto thy servants, bring him down unto me, that i may set mine eyes upon him.

source_text: "keimami sa tukuna vua na neimami turaga, 'na gone sa sega ni rawa ni biuti tamana, ena mate o tamana kevaka sa biuti koya na gone. '
target_text: and we said unto my lord, the lad cannot leave his father: for if he should leave his father, his father would die.

source_text: "o ni sa tukuna vei ira na nomuni tamata, 'kevaka sa sega ni lako mai na gone, keimami na sega ni raici kemuni. '
target_text: and thou saidst unto thy servants, except your youngest brother come down with you, ye shall see my face no more.

source_text: "ni keimami sa lako vei tamai keimami, keimami sa tukuna vua na vosa nei koya na neimami turaga.
target_text: and it came to pass when we came up unto thy servant my father, we told him the words of my lord.

source_text: "sa tukuna o tamai keimami, 'me keimami mai volia tale mada vakalailai na kakana. '
target_text: and our father said, go again, and buy us a little food.

source_text: "keimami sa tukuna, 'keimami na sega ni lako na sobu, vakavo kevaka sa lako vata kei keimami na gone. '
target_text: and we said, we cannot go down: if our youngest brother be with us, then will we go down: for we may not see the man's face, except our youngest brother be with us.

source_text: "na tamadra na nomuni tamata sa tukuna, 'dou sa kila, na watiqu sa vakasucuma vei au e rua na luvequ tagane;
target_text: and thy servant my father said unto us, ye know that my wife bare me two sons:

source_text: 'o koya sa lako tani mai vei au, "sa dina sara, sa basubasuki vakalalai"“au sa sega ni raici koya tale mai na siga o ya.
target_text: and the one went out from me, and i said, surely he is torn in pieces; and i saw him not since:

source_text: 'kevaka dou sa kauti koya tale oqo, ka yacovi koya na leqa, dou sa kauta sobu na ulu sika oqo ki nai bulubulu. '
target_text: and if ye take this also from me, and mischief befall him, ye shall bring down my gray hairs with sorrow to the grave.

source_text: "o koya oqo, ni'u na lako vua na nomuni tamata na tamaqu, ka sa sega ni tiko vata kei keitou na gone, na nona bula sa vesuki vata tiko kei na nona bula na gone,
target_text: now therefore when i come to thy servant my father, and the lad be not with us; seeing that his life is bound up in the lad's life;

source_text: "ena yaco ni sa raica sa sega vei keitou na gone, ena mate o koya. o keitou sa na beitaki ni kauta sobu ki nai bulubulu ena rarawa na ulu sika “na tamai keitou.
target_text: it shall come to pass, when he seeth that the lad is not with us, that he will die: and thy servants shall bring down the gray hairs of thy servant our father with sorrow to the grave.

source_text: "o au, na nomuni tamata, sa yalayala mei vakadei me baleta na gone vei tamana. 'kevaka, au na sega ni kauta lesu mai na gone “sa na noqu na kena bili me sega ni mudu. '
target_text: for thy servant became surety for the lad unto my father, saying, if i bring him not unto thee, then i shall bear the blame to my father for ever.

source_text: "o koya oqo, me'u tiko o au na nomuni tamata ka me lako na gone, me'u nona bobula na noqu turaga “me lako ga yani na gone vata kei ira na tacina.
target_text: now therefore, i pray thee, let thy servant abide instead of the lad a bondman to my lord; and let the lad go up with his brethren.

source_text: "me'u lako rawa vaka-cava vei tamaqu kevaka sa sega na gone, de, au na qai raica na rarawa levu ena lako mai vei tamaqu? "
target_text: for how shall i go up to my father, and the lad be not with me? lest peradventure i see the evil that shall come on my father.

source_text: sa sega ni rawa ni vosoti koya tiko o joseva e matadra sa tu vata kei koya, ka sa kaci yani, "mera lako kece i tuba na tamata mai vei au! " sa sega e tu vata kei koya ni sa tukuni koya tiko vei ira na tacina.
target_text: then joseph could not refrain himself before all them that stood by him; and he cried, cause every man to go out from me. and there stood no man with him, while joseph made himself known unto his brethren.

source_text: sa tagi vakadomoi levu o koya, o ira na ijipita kei ira na vuvale nei fero, era sa rogoca.
target_text: and he wept aloud: and the egyptians and the house of pharaoh heard.

source_text: sa tukuna o joseva vei ira na tacina, "o au o joseva, e se bula tiko o tamaqu? " era sa sega ni sauma rawa na tacina, ni ra sa kidacala e matana.
target_text: and joseph said unto his brethren, i am joseph; doth my father yet live? and his brethren could not answer him; for they were troubled at his presence.

source_text: sa tukuna o joseva vei ira na tacina, "dou toso voleka mai vei au. " sa qai tukuna tale, "o au o joseva na tacimudou, o koya dou a volitaka mai ki ijipita.
target_text: and joseph said unto his brethren, come near to me, i pray you. and they came near. and he said, i am joseph your brother, whom ye sold into egypt.

source_text: "dou kua ni rarawa se cudruvi kemudou kina ni dou volitaki au mai ki ke; na kalou sa talai au mai e liu vei kemudou, me maroroi kina na bula.
target_text: now therefore be not grieved, nor angry with yourselves, that ye sold me hither: for god did send me before you to preserve life.

source_text: "ena rua na yabaki oqo sa sega kina na kakana ena vanua, ka sa tiko tale oqo e lima na yabaki ena sega kina na cukicuki se na tatamusuki.
target_text: for these two years hath the famine been in the land: and yet there are five years, in the which there shall neither be earing nor harvest.

source_text: "na kalou sa talai mai liu vei kemudou me maroroi na sautu ena vuravura, ka me vakabulai kemudou ena veisereki levu.
target_text: and god sent me before you to preserve you a posterity in the earth, and to save your lives by a great deliverance.

source_text: "ia, oqo sa sega ni oi kemudou sa talai au mai, na kalou ga, o koya sa cakava me'u tama vei fero, ka turaga ena nona vale taucoko ka lewa ena vanua taucoko o ijipita.
target_text: so now it was not you that sent me hither, but god: and he hath made me a father to pharaoh, and lord of all his house, and a ruler throughout all the land of egypt.

source_text: "dou totolo ka lako cake vei tamaqu ka tukuna vua, 'sa tukuna vaka oqo o joseva na luvemu: "na kalou sa cakava me'u turaga levu duadua e ijipita taucoko, lako sobu mai vakatotolo “kua ni wawa tale.
target_text: haste ye, and go up to my father, and say unto him, thus saith thy son joseph, god hath made me lord of all egypt: come down unto me, tarry not:

source_text: "dou na mai tiko ena vanua o koseni, dou na mai tiko volekati au, o kemudou kei ira na luvemudou kei ira na luvena na luvemudou, na nomudou manumanu kei na ka kecega sa nomudou.
target_text: and thou shalt dwell in the land of goshen, and thou shalt be near unto me, thou, and thy children, and thy children's children, and thy flocks, and thy herds, and all that thou hast:

source_text: "mai kea au na vakarautaka vei kemudou, de o ni na qai dravudravua o kemuni kei na nomuni vuvale kece, ni se vo tiko oqo e lima na yabaki ni dausiga. "'
target_text: and there will i nourish thee; for yet there are five years of famine; lest thou, and thy household, and all that thou hast, come to poverty.

source_text: "mo dou kila, na matamudou kei na matai penijamini na taciqu, sa raica na gusuqu ni sa vosa tiko.
target_text: and, behold, your eyes see, and the eyes of my brother benjamin, that it is my mouth that speaketh unto you.

source_text: "dou tukuna vei tamaqu na noqu cecere e ijipita kei na veika kecega dou sa raica; mo dou vakatotolo kina ka kauta sobu mai na tamaqu e ke. "
target_text: and ye shall tell my father of all my glory in egypt, and of all that ye have seen; and ye shall haste and bring down my father hither.

source_text: rau sa veimokomokoti kei penijamini na tacina ka veitagicaki.
target_text: and he fell upon his brother benjamin's neck, and wept; and benjamin wept upon his neck.

source_text: sa reguci iratou kece na tacina ka veitagici, ni sa oti o ya, era sa veivosaki.
target_text: moreover he kissed all his brethren, and wept upon them: and after that his brethren talked with him.

source_text: nai rogorogo ni veika oqo sa yaco sara ki na loma ni vale nei fero ka vaka: "o ira na taci joseva, era sa lako mai. " sa taleitaka o fero kei ira na nona tamata na ka oqo.
target_text: and the fame thereof was heard in pharaoh's house, saying, joseph's brethren are come: and it pleased pharaoh well, and his servants.

source_text: sa tukuna o fero vei joseva, "tukuna vei ira na tacimu, 'dou vakatawana nai lakolako, ka lako ki kenani.
target_text: and pharaoh said unto joseph, say unto thy brethren, this do ye; lade your beasts, and go, get you unto the land of canaan;

source_text: 'dou kauti tamamudou mai kei na nomudou vuvale ka lako mai vei au; au na soli vei kemuni na tikina vinaka duadua ena vanua o ijipita, o ni na kania na uro ni vanua.
target_text: and take your father and your households, and come unto me: and i will give you the good of the land of egypt, and ye shall eat the fat of the land.

source_text: 'o ni sa vakaroti mo ni cakava oqo o mo ni kauta na qiqi vakavale me ra kau mai kina na gone kei tinadra ka mo ni kauti tamamuni talega mai.
target_text: now thou art commanded, this do ye; take you wagons out of the land of egypt for your little ones, and for your wives, and bring your father, and come.

source_text: 'mo ni kua ni leqataka na veika e nomuni, baleta, ni na soli vei kemuni na vanua vinaka duadua e ijipita me nomuni. '"
target_text: also regard not your stuff; for the good of all the land of egypt is yours.

source_text: o ira na luvei isireli era sa cakava oqo, me vaka sa tukuni vei ira, sa soli vei ira na qiqi vakavale me vaka nai vakaro i fero, sa soli talega vei ira na i vaqa ni lakolako.
target_text: and the children of israel did so: and joseph gave them wagons, according to the commandment of pharaoh, and gave them provision for the way.

source_text: sa solia vei ira kece, vei ira vakayadua na veisau ni nodra i sulu; vei penijamini ga sa solia kina e tolu na drau na tiki ni siliva kei na lima nai sulu ni veisau.
target_text: to all of them he gave each man changes of raiment; but to benjamin he gave three hundred pieces of silver, and five changes of raiment.

source_text: sa vakauta vei tamana na veika oqo, e tina na asa sa vakavodoki kina na veika vivinaka e ijipita, e tini na asa yalewa sa vakavodoki kina na sila, na madrai, kei na veikakana ni lakolako mai.
target_text: and to his father he sent after this manner; ten asses laden with the good things of egypt, and ten she asses laden with corn and bread and meat for his father by the way.

source_text: sa vakatalai ira yani na tacina, ka era sa lako yani, ka sa tukuna vei ira, "dou raica me kua na leqa ena sala. "
target_text: so he sent his brethren away, and they departed: and he said unto them, see that ye fall not out by the way.

source_text: era sa lako cake tani yani mai ijipita ka lako mai kina vanua o kenani vei jekope na tamadra.
target_text: and they went up out of egypt, and came into the land of canaan unto jacob their father,

source_text: era sa tukuna vua, "o joseva e se bula tiko, e sa lewa tiko ena vanua taucoko o ijipita. " sa kidacala o jekope baleta ni sa sega ni vakabauti ira.
target_text: and told him, saying, joseph is yet alive, and he is governor over all the land of egypt. and jacob's heart fainted, for he believed them not.

source_text: ia, ni ra sa tukuna vua na vosa kece i joseva, ka sa raica talega na qiqi vakavale sa soli mai me mai vodo kina, sa vakabulabulataki tale na yaloi jekope na tamadra.
target_text: and they told him all the words of joseph, which he had said unto them: and when he saw the wagons which joseph had sent to carry him, the spirit of jacob their father revived:

source_text: sa qai tukuna o isireli, "sa rauta, e se bula tiko o joseva na luvequ. au na lako ka raici koya ni bera ni'u mate. "
target_text: and israel said, it is enough; joseph my son is yet alive: i will go and see him before i die.

source_text: sa kauta o isireli na nona veika kece ena nona i lakolako ka sa lako mai ki perisepa ka vakacabora nai soro vua na kalou i aisake na tamana.
target_text: and israel took his journey with all that he had, and came to beersheba, and offered sacrifices unto the god of his father isaac.

source_text: na kalou sa qai vosa vei isireli ena raivotu ena bogi ka tukuna: "jekope, jekope, " sa sauma mai o jekope, "sai au oqo. "
target_text: and god spake unto israel in the visions of the night, and said, jacob, jacob. and he said, here am i.

source_text: sa tukuna mai, "oi au na kalou, na kalou i tamamu, kua ni rere ni lako sobu i ijipita, au na vakayacora mo matanitu levu mai kea.
target_text: and he said, i am god, the god of thy father: fear not to go down into egypt; for i will there make of thee a great nation:

source_text: "au na lako sobu vata kei iko ki ijipita, au na kauti iko lesu tale mai vakaidina. o joseva ena biuta na ligana e mataqu. "
target_text: i will go down with thee into egypt; and i will also surely bring thee up again: and joseph shall put his hand upon thine eyes.

source_text: sa tucake o jekope mai perisepa, o ira na luvei isireli era sa kauti jekope, ira na nodra lalai, kei ira na watidra ena qiqi vakavale ea solia mai o fero me ra mai vodo kina.
target_text: and jacob rose up from beersheba: and the sons of israel carried jacob their father, and their little ones, and their wives, in the wagons which pharaoh had sent to carry him.

source_text: era sa kauta na nodra manumanu kei na nodra i yaya, era sa rawata ena vanua o kenani, ka lako sobu ki ijipita, o jekope kei ira kecega na nona kawa.
target_text: and they took their cattle, and their goods, which they had gotten in the land of canaan, and came into egypt, jacob, and all his seed with him:

source_text: o ira na luvena tagane kei na luvedra tagane na luvena, na luvedra yalewa kei na luvedra yalewa na luvena tagane, kei ira kece na nona kawa, sa kauti ira kece ki ijipita.
target_text: his sons, and his sons' sons with him, his daughters, and his sons' daughters, and all his seed brought he with him into egypt.

source_text: sai ira oqo na yacadra na luvei isireli, jekope kei na luvena tagane, o ira sa lako sobu ki ijipita. o rupeni na ulumatua nei jekope.
target_text: and these are the names of the children of israel, which came into egypt, jacob and his sons: reuben, jacob's firstborn.

source_text: o ira na luvei rupeni tagane, o anoki, o palu, o esironi kei kami.
target_text: and the sons of reuben; hanoch, and phallu, and hezron, and carmi.

source_text: o ira na luvei simione tagane: o jemueli, o jamini, o qada, o jakini, o soara, o saula na luveni dua na yalewa ni kenani.
target_text: and the sons of simeon; jemuel, and jamin, and ohad, and jachin, and zohar, and shaul the son of a canaanitish woman.

source_text: o ira na luvei livai tagane: o kerisoni, o koata, kei merari.
target_text: and the sons of levi; gershon, kohath, and merari.

source_text: o ira na luvei juta tagane: o eri, o onani, o sela, o veresi, kei sera. (o eri kei onani e rau sa mate ena vanua o kenani). na luvei veresi o esironi kei amulu.
target_text: and the sons of judah; er, and onan, and shelah, and pharez, and zerah: but er and onan died in the land of canaan. and the sons of pharez were hezron and hamul.

source_text: o ira na luvei isakari tagane: o tola, o pura, o jope, o simironi.
target_text: and the sons of issachar; tola, and phuvah, and job, and shimron.

source_text: o ira na luvei sevuloni tagane: o sareti, o eloni, kei jaelieli.
target_text: and the sons of zebulun; sered, and elon, and jahleel.

source_text: sai ira oqori na luvei lia tagane, sa vakasucuma vei jekope mai padani-erami kei taina na luvena yalewa. o ira kece oqo sa lewe tolusagavulu ka tolu na tamata.
target_text: these be the sons of leah, which she bare unto jacob in padanaram, with his daughter dinah: all the souls of his sons and his daughters were thirty and three.

source_text: o ira na luvei kata tagane: o sifioni, o aqi, o suni, o esiboni, o eri, o arodi, kei areli.
target_text: and the sons of gad; ziphion, and haggi, shuni, and ezbon, eri, and arodi, and areli.

source_text: o ira na luvei aseri tagane: o jimina, o isua, o beria kei sera na luvena yalewa. o ira na luvei beria tagane, o eba kei malikieli.
target_text: and the sons of asher; jimnah, and ishuah, and isui, and beriah, and serah their sister: and the sons of beriah; heber, and malchiel.

source_text: sai ira oqori na luvei siliva na dauveiqaravi nei lia. o ira kece oqo sa tinikaono na tamata.
target_text: these are the sons of zilpah, whom laban gave to leah his daughter, and these she bare unto jacob, even sixteen souls.

source_text: na luvei raijeli tagane na wati jekope: o joseva kei penijamini.
target_text: the sons of rachel jacob's wife; joseph, and benjamin.

source_text: vei joseva ena vanua o ijipita sa sucu kina o manasa kei ifereimi, e rau sa vakasucumi mai vei vasemaca na luvei poti-fera na bete.
target_text: and unto joseph in the land of egypt were born manasseh and ephraim, which asenath the daughter of potipherah priest of on bare unto him.

source_text: o ira na luvei penijamini tagane: o bela, o bikeri, o asiveli, o qera, o nemani, o ei, o rosi, o mupimi, o upimi kei areti.
target_text: and the sons of benjamin were belah, and becher, and ashbel, gera, and naaman, ehi, and rosh, muppim, and huppim, and ard.

source_text: o ira oqori na luvei raijeli tagane, sa vakasucuma vei jekope e tinikava na tamata.
target_text: these are the sons of rachel, which were born to jacob: all the souls were fourteen.
and the sons of dan; hushim.

source_text: o ira na luvei navitalai: o jasili, o qani, o jasa kei silemi.
target_text: and the sons of naphtali; jahzeel, and guni, and jezer, and shillem.

source_text: o ira oqori na luvei bila na dauveiqaravi nei raijeli. sa vakasucuma vei jekope e vitu na tamata.
target_text: these are the sons of bilhah, which laban gave unto rachel his daughter, and she bare these unto jacob: all the souls were seven.

source_text: o ira kece na tamata era sa lako vata kei jekope ki ijipita “o ira kece sa lako mai ena yagona, sa onosagavulu ka ono na tamata.
target_text: all the souls that came with jacob into egypt, which came out of his loins, besides jacob's sons' wives, all the souls were threescore and six;

source_text: oi rau na luvei joseva sa sucu mai na vanua o ijipita, sa lewe rua. o ira kece na vuvale i jekope sa lako sobu ki ijipita sa vitusagavulu na tamata.
target_text: and the sons of joseph, which were born him in egypt, were two souls: all the souls of the house of jacob, which came into egypt, were threescore and ten.

source_text: sa vakatalai juta yani e liu o jekope vei joseva, me dusimaka vei ira na sala ki koseni. era sa lako mai ki na vanua o koseni.
target_text: and he sent judah before him unto joseph, to direct his face unto goshen; and they came into the land of goshen.

source_text: sa vakarautaka o joseva na nona qiqi vakavale ka lako cake ki koseni me sota kei isireli na tamana; sa mokoti tamana yani ka rau sa veitagicaki.
target_text: and joseph made ready his chariot, and went up to meet israel his father, to goshen, and presented himself unto him; and he fell on his neck, and wept on his neck a good while.

source_text: o isireli sa tukuna vei joseva, "mo laivi au me'u mate, ni'u sa raica tale na matamu, baleta ni o se bula tiko. "
target_text: and israel said unto joseph, now let me die, since i have seen thy face, because thou art yet alive.

source_text: o joseva sa tukuna vei ira na tacina kei ira kece na vuvale nei tamana, "au na lako cake vei fero ka tukuna vua, 'ni o ira kece na taciqu kei na vuvale kece nei tamaqu era sa tiko mai na vanua o kenani, era sa lako mai oqo ki vei au.
target_text: and joseph said unto his brethren, and unto his father's house, i will go up, and shew pharaoh, and say unto him, my brethren, and my father's house, which were in the land of canaan, are come unto me;

source_text: 'era sa dau vakatawana na sipi, me vaka ga ni nodra cakacaka na vakania na sipi; era sa kauta talega mai na nodra manumanu kece. '
target_text: and the men are shepherds, for their trade hath been to feed cattle; and they have brought their flocks, and their herds, and all that they have.

source_text: "ni sa lako mai o fero me tarogi kemuni, 'se cava na nomuni cakacaka? '
target_text: and it shall come to pass, when pharaoh shall call you, and shall say, what is your occupation?

source_text: "mo ni qai tukuna, 'na nodra cakacaka na nomuni tamata sa tu vata ga kei ira na manumanu, mai na neimami gone ka yacova na siga oqo, oi keimami kei ira talega na tamai keimami: ' mo ni tiko kina ena vanua o koseni “o ira kece na vakatawa ni manumanu era sa ka vakasisila vei ira na kai ijipita. "
target_text: that ye shall say, thy servants' trade hath been about cattle from our youth even until now, both we, and also our fathers: that ye may dwell in the land of goshen; for every shepherd is an abomination unto the egyptians.

source_text: sa lako o joseva ka tukuna vei fero, "o tamaqu kei ira na taciqu, na nodra manumanu kei na veika kece era taukena “era sa lako mai na vanua o kenani, ka era sa tiko ena vanua o koseni. "
target_text: then joseph came and told pharaoh, and said, my father and my brethren, and their flocks, and their herds, and all that they have, are come out of the land of canaan; and, behold, they are in the land of goshen.

source_text: sa kauta mai e lima, mai vei ira na tacina ka vakaraitaki ira vei fero.
target_text: and he took some of his brethren, even five men, and presented them unto pharaoh.

source_text: sa tarogi iratou na tacina o fero, "na cava na nomudou cakacaka? " e ratou sauma vei fero, "o ira na nomuni tamata sa dau vakatawa sipi, o keimami kei ira talega na neimami qase. "
target_text: and pharaoh said unto his brethren, what is your occupation? and they said unto pharaoh, thy servants are shepherds, both we, and also our fathers.

source_text: era sa tukuna talega vei fero, "keimami sa lako curuma mai na vanua, ni sa sega na kakana me kedra na manumanu baleta ni sa rui levu na dausiga e kenani. me ra tiko mada na nomuni tamata ena vanua o koseni. "
target_text: they said moreover unto pharaoh, for to sojourn in the land are we come; for thy servants have no pasture for their flocks; for the famine is sore in the land of canaan: now therefore, we pray thee, let thy servants dwell in the land of goshen.

source_text: sa vosa o fero vei joseva ka vaka: "eera sa lako mai na tamamu kei na tacimu vei iko.
target_text: and pharaoh spake unto joseph, saying, thy father and thy brethren are come unto thee:

source_text: "sa tu e matamu na vanua o ijipita. me ra tiko na tamamu kei na tacimu ena vanua vinaka duadua e ijipita, me ra tiko e koseni. kevaka, talega o sa raica e dua na tamata vinaka vei ira, me mai qarava na noqu manumanu. "
target_text: the land of egypt is before thee; in the best of the land make thy father and brethren to dwell; in the land of goshen let them dwell: and if thou knowest any men of activity among them, then make them rulers over my cattle.

source_text: o joseva sa kauti jekope mai na tamana vei fero, ka me tu ena matai fero. sa vakalouvinakataki fero o jekope.
target_text: and joseph brought in jacob his father, and set him before pharaoh: and jacob blessed pharaoh.

source_text: sa tarogi jekope o fero ka vaka: "o sa yabaki vica? "
target_text: and pharaoh said unto jacob, how old art thou?

source_text: sa sauma o jekope, "na veisiga ni noqu bula sa dua na drau ka mani tolusagavulu na yabaki, sa lailai ka ca na veisiga ni noqu bula, sa sega ni vaka na nodra veisiga ni bula na noqu qase. "
target_text: and jacob said unto pharaoh, the days of the years of my pilgrimage are an hundred and thirty years: few and evil have the days of the years of my life been, and have not attained unto the days of the years of the life of my fathers in the days of their pilgrimage.

source_text: sa vakalouvinakataki fero o jekope ka lako tani mai matana.
target_text: and jacob blessed pharaoh, and went out from before pharaoh.

source_text: o joseva sa vakatikori ira na tamana kei na tacina ena vanua o ijipita, na tikina vinaka duadua ena vanua e ramisese, me vaka sa vakarota o fero.
target_text: and joseph placed his father and his brethren, and gave them a possession in the land of egypt, in the best of the land, in the land of rameses, as pharaoh had commanded.

source_text: o joseva sa vakani tamana kei ira na tacina, kei na nodra veivuvale me vaka na kedra i wiliwili.
target_text: and joseph nourished his father, and his brethren, and all his father's household, with bread, according to their families.

source_text: sa sega na madrai ena vanua taucoko, ni sa rui dede sara na dausiga, na vanua o ijipita kei kenani sa sega sara ga kina na ka baleta na balavu ni dausiga.
target_text: and there was no bread in all the land; for the famine was very sore, so that the land of egypt and all the land of canaan fainted by reason of the famine.

source_text: o joseva sa kumuna kece nai lavo ena vanua o ijipita kei na vanua o kenani, ena vuku ni sila era sa mai volia. sa kauta kece mai na i lavo ki na lololo nei fero.
target_text: and joseph gathered up all the money that was found in the land of egypt, and in the land of canaan, for the corn which they bought: and joseph brought the money into pharaoh's house.

source_text: ni sa oti kece nai lavo e ijipita kei kenani, era sa lako kece mai na ijipita vei joseva ka tukuna, "solia mai na kakana, me keimami mate beka e matamuni? ni sa oti nai lavo. "
target_text: and when money failed in the land of egypt, and in the land of canaan, all the egyptians came unto joseph, and said, give us bread: for why should we die in thy presence? for the money faileth.

target_text: and they brought their cattle unto joseph: and joseph gave them bread in exchange for horses, and for the flocks, and for the cattle of the herds, and for the asses: and he fed them with bread for all their cattle for that year.

source_text: ni sa oti na yabaki o ya, era sa lako tale mai ena yabaki ka tarava, ka tukuna vua, "keimami na sega ni vunitaka ni sa sega vei keimami nai lavo, na neimami turaga talega sa taura na neimami manumanu. sa sega tale na ka e vo “na yagoi keimami ga kei na neimami vanua.
target_text: when that year was ended, they came unto him the second year, and said unto him, we will not hide it from my lord, how that our money is spent; my lord also hath our herds of cattle; there is not ought left in the sight of my lord, but our bodies, and our lands:

source_text: "na cava me keimami mate kina ena matamuni, oi keimami kei na neimami qele? mo ni voli keimami kei na neimami vanua ena madrai. oi keimami kei na neimami vanua keimami na bobula vei fero; solia vei keimami nai tei. me keimami bula ka sega ni mate, me kua ni lala na vanua. "
target_text: wherefore shall we die before thine eyes, both we and our land? buy us and our land for bread, and we and our land will be servants unto pharaoh: and give us seed, that we may live, and not die, that the land be not desolate.

source_text: o joseva sa volia na vanua taucoko o ijipita vei fero, ni tamata kecega e ijipita sa volitaka na nona vanua, baleta ni sa rui sivia sara ga na dausiga. sa yaco me nei fero kece na vanua.
target_text: and joseph bought all the land of egypt for pharaoh; for the egyptians sold every man his field, because the famine prevailed over them: so the land became pharaoh's.

target_text: only the land of the priests bought he not; for the priests had a portion assigned them of pharaoh, and did eat their portion which pharaoh gave them: wherefore they sold not their lands.

source_text: sa qai tukuna o joseva vei ira na tamata, "raica au sa voli kemuni kei na vanua vei fero. oqo nai tei, mo ni tea na vanua.

target_text: and it shall come to pass in the increase, that ye shall give the fifth part unto pharaoh, and four parts shall be your own, for seed of the field, and for your food, and for them of your households, and for food for your little ones.

source_text: the members of parliament shall be chosen by secret ballot in free and fair elections administered by the electoral commission, in accordance with this constitution and any written law governing elections. proportional representation system .—() the election of members of parliament is by a multi-member open list system of proportional representation, under which each voter has one vote, with each vote being of equal value, in a single national electoral roll comprising all the registered voters. ----------------------- page -----------------------

target_text: we, the people of fiji, recognising the indigenous people or the itaukei, their ownership of itaukei lands, their unique culture, customs, traditions and language; recognising the indigenous people or the rotuman from the island of rotuma, their ownership of rotuman lands, their unique culture, customs, traditions and language; recognising the descendants of the indentured labourers from british india and the pacific islands, their culture, customs, traditions and language; and recognising the descendants of the settlers and immigrants to fiji, their culture, customs, traditions and language, declare that we are all fijians united by common and equal citizenry; recognise the constitution as the supreme law of our country that provides the framework for the conduct of government and all fijians; commit ourselves to the recognition and protection of human rights, and respect for human dignity; declare our commitment to justice, national sovereignty and security, social and economic wellbeing, and safeguarding our environment, hereby establish this constitution for the republic of fiji. ----------------------- page ----------------------- the republic of fiji

source_text: na lewenipalimedi mera digitaki ena veidigidigi vuni ka vakayacori ena savasava ka vakamatau ka solia vua na veimatavakaturi kei na veimatapolitiki mera cakacaka ena galala, kei na kena vakau na itukutuku me vakayacori ena galala, kei na mataveilewai me soli vua na galala ni vakatulewa ka qarava na cakacaka ni veidigidigi na matabose ni veidigidigi, me vaka e virikotori ena yavunivakavulewa qo se dua na lawa tabaki e kovuta na kena ivakarau ni kena vakayacori na veidigidigi. iwalewale ni veidigidigi veiraurau .—() na lewenipalimedi era na digitaki ena iwiliwili ni mata dola raraba. ena iwalewale ni veidigidigi qo, na levu na dabedabe e winitaka e dua na matapolitiki se ilawalawa ni matavakaturi, ena veiraurau kei na levu ni digidigi e rawata na matapolitiki se ilawalawa ni matavakaturi. ena iwalewale ni veidigidigi qo na tamata taucoko e veidigidigi me dua na nona idigidigi, qo e kena ibalebale ni digidigi ni lewenivanua yadua e wiliki vakatautauvata ka na tu tale ga e dua na ivola ni veidigidigi vakamatanitu e tabaki kina o ira na lewenivanua taucoko era volayaca ni veidigidigi.
target_text: the members of parliament shall be chosen by secret ballot in free and fair elections administered by the electoral commission, in accordance with this constitution and any written law governing elections. proportional representation system .—() the election of members of parliament is by a multi-member open list system of proportional representation, under which each voter has one vote, with each vote being of equal value, in a single national electoral roll comprising all the registered voters. ----------------------- page -----------------------

target_text: the writ for a general election must be issued within days from the expiry of parliament or from the proclamation of its dissolution by the president.

source_text: ia ena veika e vakamacalataki ena wasetiki (), ena vuku ni tikina qo, na “valenivolavola ni lewenivanua” e sega ni okati kina na valenivolavola ni paraiminisita, valenivolavola ni minisita, valenivolavola ni ivukevuke ni sipika, valenivolavola ni iliuliu ni itoniveisaqa se dua na valenivolavola ni minisita se o ira era digitaki mera minisita. gauna ni palimedi .—() ena vuku ni tikina qo, na palimedi me na tomani me na yabaki mai na imatai ni bose ni oti na kena digitaki e dua na lewenipalimedi, vakavo ke sa bokoci totolo ena yavunivakavulewa qo.

foreword (to a book).
lady, as a form of address, usually followed by a first name. adi is sometimes sounded as yadi

influence of lau. when followed by a name, adi may be heard abbreviated informally as di, as in di lala for adi lalabalavu, and this short version is not disrespectful. like the man ’s chiefly title ratu, this form of address was limited to the eastern coast of viti levu but has become commonly adopted by chiefly women throughout fiji. the origin may come from the ra word yadi (also used in parts of tailevu), meaning to take, as a chief takes up a woman when he takes her as a wife. but that is idle speculation.

senitoa n. hibiscus festival usually held annually in august in suva with parade and floats. a “queen”, adi senitoa, is selected. a great deal of rain usually falls during this week , giving the local
“hibiscus weather”. senitoa hibiscus rosasinensis, malvaceae, the introduced, ornamental hibiscus flower.
(or) yagelo (eng., rom. cath.) n. angel.
(or) agilosi (eng., prot.) n. angel. idiom: agilosi flattering reference to a beautifully natured girl.
(eng.) ireland.
(eng.) n. ice. aisi boloko ice block.
(or) aisikirimi (eng.) n. ice cream, that fij ians usually spell as one word.
(eng. angl. church) n. archbishop. syn.(rom. cath.) aravikavo, arekavikavo.
(eng.) n. account (bank). ala, alaca (cakau) v. to remove wood from fire, to reduce or extinguish the flame; usually one hears
na buka or me ala na buka. (buka firewood). the word may be written, less often heard, as yala, yalaca . abbrev. of tala, talaca.
. n. millipede; three harmless types, one small and brown, one small and black, one large and black , which leaves a yellow stain when its belly is touched, the yellow fluid irritating to human skin.
. (bible) alpha, used in the expression aliva kei na omeka from beginning to the end, lit., from alpha and omega, first and last letters of the greek alphabet.

(eng. acronym) n. agricultural landowners and tenants act, which has governed the leasing of native land. “alto” (or) alato (eng.) alto singing voice. syn. (lau) kanokano. “ambar” (hindi) n. white-fleshed turmeric, used fresh for pickles, especially by gujerati indians, or raw

(eng.) n. anthurium, a genus of plants of south american origin. these attractive durable flowers, usually bright red, are grown commercially by some fij ian women who sell to hotels. very few local people know that this plant is quite toxic. “apei” (rotuma) n. very fine white mat woven by rotumans from pandanus leaf, a principal item used
(eng.) n. apple (imported from australia, new zealand).
(bible) apostle. araneke! (interj ection) cheat ! (usually at card games). syn. ereneke!
(bible) n . ass (the animal). none in fij i.
(eng.) n. aspirin. due to successful marketing, aspirin these days is largely displaced by the omnipresent, more expensive panadol, much used by urban fij ians.

i (or) me. pronoun, st person singular. as the subj ect of the sentence it can become oi au or o yau. preceded by a vowel it may become yau: raica e dua vei keirau, o seru se o yau. see one of us (two, exc. the one being talked to), either seru or me. following the particles me or ni it becomes abbreviated as meu and niu, sometimes seen as me ’u and ni ’u. syn. (tonga) au. (colo east, namosi) ’u.
(eng.) n. hour. also spelled auwa. ena veiaua kece at all hours. ena veimama na aua in half an hour.
(eng) n. haversack.
(slang) n. lazy person who shirks work. this is a man ’s name but how it has come to take on a lazy implication is an elusive story.
b. this letter b does not exist in the local language of drekeniwai, near nasavusavu, vanua levu island.
. n. edible stalk of taro, considered a delicacy, steamed with the skin removed. lemon and chili
as a modern touch, not traditional. it is also a special ceremonial gift-food
. (rewa) n. taro, colocasia esculentum, an edible root-crop, staple food. syn. dalo. idiom: ba rewa! "hi beautiful !" (or) "hi handsome !" young fijians are much given to jocular
amongst their own people or related people. and most everybody is related in one way or another. this expression rather dated.
. n. as in ba-ni-ika, fish fence, usually made of reeds. fish are caught by the movement of the tide or coastal currents.
. n. game, contention, riddle. veiba quarrel, dispute.
. n. guess, bet, belief. noqu iba o seru. my bet is on seru.
. n. (archaic) trolling lure, often made of shell, as a samoan and later, tongan artefact. binding

done with inner bark of roga (pipturus argentus). trolling was unknown to fijians who fished almost exclusively within the lagoon. ba, bataka v. to deny, argue. veiba, veibataka v. to argue, to argue about (something). veibataki disputed.
. n. slope, hill. veibaba hilly slopes. see baba siga.
. n. ceremonial food taken to a new mother and baby, usually the skinned stems of taro, as a vegetable delicacy. see ba.
n. cheek (of the face), side, as of the body.
v., n. to block (as a fallen tree might block a road), to impede, hold back, prevent. also, to move sideways.
n. wall of wooden house, also a fried pastry turnover eaten at breakfast.
n. dolphin, a mammal. this word is not commonly known. dolphins are not referred to in any of the well known myths or legends.
(west) n. species of freshwater eel, gymnothorax sp . syn. dadarikai.
n. popular nickname for macuata province where, as the name implies, there are sunny slopes.

n. worm, bait, as in fishing, or by extension, an enticement that has duplicitous intention. as a verb, baca, bacana to put our bait, as on a hook. baca ni qele earthworm. idiom: baca kuita a special enticement, very likely to succeed, a "hooker" that will win over the
being enticed. (kuita octopus). o iko baca cava ? what bait (enticement) are you using? na baca kuita . something special, that will succeed.

(kadavu, lau) sick , illness, injury. syn. tauvimate. baci . a rather formal word, difficult to translate; it approximates “thus”, or “then” or “again”, implying a repetition. the word may be used to indicate a result or consequence of something that is stated earlier. e rawa meu baci cakava tale. i could or would do it again . au baci raica tale mada. i wish i

again . sa baci voleka tale tiko na gauna ni balolo. once again the time of balolo is close by. sega ni dede, sa baci lesu mai. before long, he/she will return. baci . (vanua levu) penis, male sexual organs. syn. boci (uncircumcised). see qala-na, uti-na.
n. a common swamp eel in fresh or brackish water. it is reddish brown in colour with a

belly. slow-moving, it is often caught by hand. the presence of algae called de ni duna ("eel excrement") indicate its presence, and one can see the air holes in the mud. relative to other eels they are slow-moving. the flesh is a little brownish and slightly oily when cooked, usually grilled with the skin on, after gutting, or cooked in a leaf-wrapped package in the earth-oven.
after all, therefore, thus, then (in the preceding senses), as a matter of course, as an affirmation. this is a rather formal word used by the older generation.
(lau, kadavu) n. tooth. syn. bati.
(eng.) v. to hit, "bang", smash it/him (marbles as a game), a word said by some children but not in general usage.
n. fence, stockade. vakabai fenced. viribai-taka to fence, set up fences. viribai can refer to stockades, ancient war defenses, and is often used figuratively to mean prepare for imminent war or,
stone enclosure, stone wall. bainivuaka pig-pen, pig stye. syn. ba ni ika, bavatu, etc.

(hindi) n. eggplant, an introduced food in areas of indian influence. idiom: e sega ni dua na nomu baigani. it is none of your business. “baini” (hindi “sister”) n. form of address speaking to a mature indian woman. “baiya” (hindi “brother”) n. form of address to an indian man.
n. very large native tree, ficus obliqua, with drooping branches and hanging roots. growth can start
an epiphyte, and smother the mother tree. believed formerly to be associated with spirits. they are

by the queens road near navua. inner bark formerly used for cloth when masi not available. white latex has been used to entrap birds. fruits are a fig, maturing to yellow orange, then red, throughout the year. often confused with f. prolix, an introduced, similar, sacred tree of india,
has fruits that turn black while f . obliqua fruits turn yellow, orange and red, and f. obliqua

all year round. there is confusion as to which species is referred to by the fijian names baka ni viti and baka ni valagi. confused also is f. tinctoria. syn. (west) yayawa. idiom: vunibaka ga sa tevoro. beware the power of a big man ; he may appear magnificent but he can be dangerous, literally , the baka tree (banyan tree) has its own devil. idiom: sa kamusu na baka. a great chief has died.
n. a type of branched coral.
adj ., n. crazy, silly person. reference is to st. giles hospital, a mental hospital in suva,
(which in fact does not enclose the place).
n. remora, pilot fish that attaches itself to sharks. edible but not tasty, echeneis naucrates.
. adj . bitter, astringent in taste, such as the taste of immature bananas.

. n. foreskin of a penis, excised in ceremony of circumcision. by extension baku may refer to the penis of people who are not circumcised. idiom: baku! insult, usually joking, of someone who is thought ineffectual. syn. sometimes used for indo-fijians kulina, literally “skin”.
n. hydra, according to neyret, one of the cnidarians (j ellyfish, sea anenomes, polyps, and including hydra), tiny, with tiny tentacles. gov ’t dictionary has this listed as ophiolep sis superba.

n. male sea turtle (green turtle), chelonia mydas. bala! interj ection, implying surprise or disappointment. bala, balata v. push into water (person, anchor, other things), or shove into some place, put into (prison):
ikelekele! drop the anchor ! bala ki na vale ni veivesu put into prison. the word implied shoving, pushing. there is a new year ’s eve custom of heaving people into the water.

n. tree fern, cyathea lunulata and other species. splinters from tree ferns cause dangerous and lingering pain and are a common injury in the bush , especially to bare feet. tree fern wood is useful as
a long time; it burns very slowly. the firm spongy pith in the stem of mature

n. tree fern, cyathea affinis, tall and very thin but solid, very hard trunk, and thus much more durable wood. it is distinguished by a lighter leaf-stem colour, finer leaflets and less branching of the leaves.
n. edible surgeon fish around the reef, acanthurus sp .
n. a palm useful for its very thin , straight and hard stem, formerly used for spears, balaka species.
v. to stick through (spear, nail, knife) without gripping.
adj ., n. long, tall. (fij ians use the same word for both concepts.) length, height. na kena balavu

height (or length). babalavu plural, one of the very few adjectives that takes a plural form. see cere, cecere, height applied to high places, hills, mountains. see also dede, for length of time. idiom: vuaka balavu lit. “long pig” or “tall pig”, meaning a human body intended for eating.

n. pandanus fruit, and by extension, the introduced pineapple due to similarity in appearance of the fruit. in the viti levu highlands, balawa usually refers to an edible bush pineapple with very small fruits, now growing wild. (cultivated pineapple is re-planted every two years with suckers because the
much smaller after the first two years.) pineapples originated in central america. well
commercial variety is the ripley queen, small, very thorny, very juicy and sweet. the

(sydney) varieties are types of smooth cayenne, much larger and with only small thorns at the tips of leaves. vatu ni balawa whale-tooth (tabua) formerly placed in a grave; certain coastal fij ians (not highlanders) believed that a dead man ’s spirit would throw the tabua at a certain pandanus palm to gain entry to the afterworld.
viriki (archaic) after the mid-s, when whale-teeth were introduced to fij i and became symbolic, a legendary custom developed: the notion that after dying, a man ’s spirit would pass udu
(mua-i-udu) where there was supposed to be a pandanus tree and he should throw a whale tooth at it. if successful, he could pass on to the other world. viriki thrown at.
v . to die (of a person) polite, honorific term, especially for chiefs. bale drokadroka v. to die young
adj . noble, honorific term used only in the combination na turaga bale the noble chief, na

the noble lady. bale, baleta v., adj . to be the cause of, often meaning to be at fault, to blame. sa bale vei koya. he/she is to blame. he/she was responsible. sa baleti iko. it is because of you. bale, baleca v. to fall from upright position (onto), usually of something tall, a person or a tree.

(nait.) v. to go. e bale ivei o koya ? where is he/she going? taubale to walk . bale, bale-taka v. to go on, pass by, cross over, usually on foot. taubale to walk, go on foot. bale dodo to follow the “stretch” (path, road, river, but perhaps especially, the continuing ridge of a hill).

is that many hands make light work. working alone is slow and arduous. this is a very important, useful custom in fij ian villages.

black, or blackish, usually of skin colour. fijians can be colour-conscious and will sometimes remark on how dark or light a person ’s skin is. traditionally, many of the blacker, “true” fijians of the highlands have felt disadvantaged. they have in several places accepted as chiefs immigrant tongans,
fair skins, as for the noemalu, and at the nadroga coast. on a few occasions, fijians have
europeans as incoming chiefs (clan naulucavu, for example, at nakorosule, and also the
sawakasa, tailevu). fijian mothers are often proud to have a light-skinned child. skin
(whiteners) are advertised in the fijian language newspapers, as are hair-straighteners. this
is a sensitive one, and a complicated one. black warriors of the fiji highlands have had a great
as mercenaries in tonga and also in the tui kaba conquest of lakeba island accomplished
sulu n. bolt of cloth, lobi, lobia to fold. e va na balobi sulu four bolts of cloth. bolts of cotton

are important gift items at some modern fij ian ceremonies. (in coastal areas, barkcloth has been used, especially in areas of polynesian influence.) the long stretch of cloth is strung out on display,
forward by a procession of women , showing it off. highlanders never had the mulberry barkcloth, and never had such grand ceremonial displays.
n. an edible sea-worm, the annelid eunice viridis (formerly palolo viridis), found only in certain places, but not at viti levu. balolo appears once or twice a year at only about coastal locations in
at any one place it may not recur annually, or may occur only once (as at lakeba). elsewhere,
of the usual places, fij ians may never have seen it or tasted it, but they have all heard of it.
in the morning the annelids rise in a spiral from coral sand, brown male sperm sacs and green
egg sacs in the form of worms that intertwine and fertilise, squirming to the surface. by the
the sun becomes strong, around eight o’clock, they will disappear. the transparent eggs become

and the thin coloured skins seem to evaporate to nothing. the balolo also exists in samoa, tonga, and the islands off japan . qoliva na balolo fish for the balolo. tagava na balolo net the balolo. collection may involve many village people. when quantities are great, much will be given away. it is contrary to custom that balolo be sold, but lautoka market now does have some, cooked, for sale.

locations are in lomaiviti (tokou, ovalau, wakaya), yasawa (mamanuca, waya), lau (lakeba, naidi, susui, avea, udu at kabara, vanuavatu, vatoa), around the south coast of kadavu (village muani and according to geraghty, from nabukelevu to galoa, and soso to vacalea), and off the south coast of vatulele island.

in abundance only once a year. village tubou has the true balolo. nukunuku has the fish nuqa. waciwaci has the red land crab lairo in late november to december, and the salala fish in april. vakano has the unicorn fish ta, and a type of bill fish saku. saqalau has the shark qio damu. drano has

november-early december, when the major season may occur, according to the phase of the moon and the weather, and other factors unknown. rising of balolo usually occurs to days after the full moon, from midnight to am, on the falling tide, lasting into the early daylight hours. the rising is often preceded a day or two by the appearance
early morning, until about am, the annelids are sieved up in tins, fine-mesh nets, and cloth ,
they spiral in thick streams to the surface from the sandy bottom. (i have observed them and swum
them as a diver.) males are brownish and the females are green but otherwise they look similar. when exposed to the sun, they appear to dissolve, leaving only a few drops of water which
evaporate. the segment of the animal that rises is composed almost entirely of tiny transparent
or sperm covered by an extremely thin, fragile coloured skin that itself becomes virtually invisible when burst open.
are eaten raw, living and writhing, or cooked in the earth oven, all with some joyous ceremony. they can be frozen, and they can be fried. there is a tradition of first presentation (isevu)
the sea scum remnant of the balolo. syn. (kadavu) baya . idiom : e kua gona ni balolo, me na kua sara. “now or never”, if this opportunity is not grasped, the

n. cheek (part of the face). idiom: balu bilo the vulgar trick of some men, say, who try to force a mouthful of yaqona beverage
the mouth of a young woman, as might be done if their peoples are tauvu dredre, kin-groups,
related in a very hard joking relationship with the people playing tricks on one another. the
people of matuku island in lau are related this way with waimaro people of the eastern
of viti levu. when the two peoples meet, great liberties are taken that can be humiliating and very frightening to youngsters. real injury is never done.

(eng.) n. barmaid (who serves drinks). “banana-face” (youthful slang) adj . “freckle-face”, a taunt directed against white kids or part-fijians.
. (eng.) n. bun (as from a bakery). modernly, a fijian breakfast is a fried or boiled bani for which
are many local names. in urban areas on good friday a primitive fiji version of hot cross buns
imperative, and replaces virtually all other breads. these are very simple, virtually tasteless buns,
by the dozen, each one marked crudely with a red cross painted on with food-dye. it is a
ritual, not at all a gastronomic occasion, rather like the concept of a birthday cake, which modern urban fij ians also insist on. the cross must be red colour.

n. fish fence to catch fish, usually made of upright reeds fastened together with strip s of walai vine. some are erected seasonally to catch seasonal runs of fish such as the ki. ba kele permanent fish fence, usually made of stones. depth is usually four to six feet at high tide and virtually empty or very shallow at low tide. an inner collection area is known as the malevu and there may be as many as three of these. a stone fish fence is known as moka.
n. caterpillar, general term. banuve has been a name of a vunivalu chief on bau island.syn. (lau) nuve.

(or) bausi n. (slang, eng. “purse”) . purse. . a small gift, or action, usually to attract the affections of someone of opposite sex. in mild, good-humoured reproach, one might say kua ni bausi! don ’t try try flattery ! baovi, baovi-taka v. to cook a food (usually fish) wrapped in leaves, grilled on hot coals of the fire. syn. tavusala, tavusalutaka.
n. any leaves used to wrap a cooked food.
(eng.) n. bank.

of the american denomination assemblies of god may be referred to as brother. some

in coconut cream. symbolic gift, uncooked, brought by relatives to mothers of newborn babies. (sei split). syn. baba, dolodolo.

(eng.) n . bus. waraka na basi. wait for the bus. vodo e na basi. get on the bus. calata na basi. miss the bus. na ikelekele ni basi the bus-stop. basiteni n. bus stand, often referring to a central bus stand in town. idiom: “tailevu no leqa, no basi, paidar”. this is a proud exclamation, vaunting the qualities of tailevu. a curious tri-lingual saying (english, fijian, hindi), lit. there ’s no problem in tailevu. if there is no bus we can walk. the notion is that tailevu is a relatively flat province. if there is no bus one can walk almost anywhere. idiom: qarauna o na sega ni “vodoka na basi ni lokia! an apocryphal, legendary rumour has it that ro lala exclaimed this to her husband ratu kamisese mara, lit. “be careful or you won ’t climb on the
bus!” implication is that he should be more considerate of her or he would not succeed in

in sexual union. village lokia is a junction point where, after crossing the rewa river, rewa people can take a bus to suva, and ro lala of course, was a lady of rewa. basi, basia v. to spread open with fingers, e.g. of coconut-shell partly opened but not completely separated. idiom: vakabasibasi to sit or lie down suggestively exposing one’s private parts (with or without underwear). basika . v . to put through, as thread through a needle.

n. warrior caste, usually referring to a traditionally specialised clan serving a chief. these days the
are only ceremonial, for example at funerals or installation of chiefs. veibatiki serving as

warriors who are a first line of defence, fighting away from the chief’s home. bati leka
who are a last line of defense for the chief, household warriors, and may have the duty of

a dead chief ’s body. two tribes that are veibatiki have food prohibitions in each other’s presence. warriors may not eat pork or sometimes, plantain; the others may not eat seafood or coconut products. historically, such warriors were not always loyal; they could trade their favours with different chiefs.
as a prefix, indicating a taste preference supposedly common to a certain region of fiji, said mockingly, as a joke or competitive j ibe by people of another region. these jibes formerly came

said of the kainakelo, by the people of tokatoka, implying they eat a lot of balei. balei is a regional word for snake, mostly heard in naitasiri and namosi.

people of macuata. kawai type of cultivated yam.
people of vuda, sabeto, or vatukarasa (nadroga). kulu breadfruit.
people of gau island. lumi an edible seaweed.

korocau people by their tauvu of kocoma. niu coconut.

lovoni people, by those of bureta, referring to seeds of dawa fruit.

as a prefix, indicating some characteristic of the person. (bati tooth).
choosy eater (digi-taka choose).
gobbles food fast, usually said of children but may apply to gluttony of an adult.

such wild men existed, social deviants, psychologically disturbed people, outcasts who did not

s. i fed him and kept him and he followed me around like a pet. he was mentally deficient, and escaped from his own family who treated him like a slave and beat him. the police
me to return him to his family who ultimately beat him excessively, and he died. he had never hurt anyone and never tried to defend himself.

n. species of swimming crab that has black claws (batiloa) bati madramadra n. medicinal herb, bidens pilosa, compositae, common weed, macerated in coconut oil and applied externally in massage for painful muscles, bruises. bati ni kete-na n. stomach just below rib cage on each side of person's body.
ni lovo (lau) n. extended family, intimately related, lit. “edge of the earth-oven”, implying the sharing of food. syn. tokatoka.
n. fish-hook, formerly made of wood or shell. wa ni siwa fishing line. line fishing was not customary in most parts of fiji. tongans and samoans introduced the concept.
ni toro n. razor blade. toro, toroya to shave. itoro razor. fijians formerly used a piece of glass
n. mangrove (tiri) swamp at edge of sea or river. a recurring place-name. very useful breeding ground for fish and other marine life.
n., adj . valencia-type oranges grown at batiri, macuata. this has been a failed plantation programme sponsored by the fij i government. mis-management continued for years.

(idiom) adj ., n. person who prefers green fruit rather than fruit that is fully mature. this is fairly common in fij i. by extension, a person who is attracted to younger people of the opposite sex, usually said of men who are attracted to younger women. vou new.
. a word that can have several meanings: just (or) indeed. a modifier that adds decisiveness or
in a very polite form by softening a statement or request. au sa bau lako. i'll just go; e

n. a fijian sickness, believed caused by spirits or witchcraft; generally failing health, weakness, confused thoughts. baubau happens to be a name associated with the mother of cakobau, the name of her house-site on bau island. it is also an old place-name in the tailevu mainland. see drimi.

n. tree, palaqium spp. and burckella sp., sapotaceae, timber often used to make punts.

n., adj . (eng. “bloody fool”) dopey, bavulu levu really dopey. bauan doce. this expression is by now perhaps somewhat archaic.and also a rather low-class expression.
n. spathe (unopened flower shoot) of coconut palm, also the dried calyx, the outer sheath of the spathe, used as torch in walking outdoors at night. (viti levu highlanders, having no coconuts, more
torches at night.) gilbertese but not fijians have known the art of making alcohol, a type of arrack, from unopened spathes. it is shaved thinly at the tip each day and the juice

small container. a plant rich in tannin may be used to arrest fermentation. a “wine” can be produced, or a strong alcohol. idiom: basu bawara of a person, to break free, break out from contraints such as discipline at home, village, or military. a spathe bursts open as it dries and matures, and reveals its flowers. be adj ., n. stubborn self-will and judgmental nature. dau be stubbornly negative.

apparently agreeable but in fact uncooperative.

n . surname of thomas baker, methodist missionary killed in interior viti levu . he is referred to as m isi beika. a main hall is named baker hall, beika olo at the methodist school, davuilevu. m isi peka may be a preferred spelling.
perhaps, maybe. vakabeka-taka v. to doubt (something).
. n. may refer to small insect-eating bats but more usually to the large, very visible flying fox,

species, mainly the polynesian flying fox. it is eaten especially by hill tribes, caught by prickly vine nets, or by stoning, or by shaking a tree where one hangs. when the tree is shaken, the bat falls to
(tavu) over a fire. fruit bats can become very friendly pets, and can be stroked on the neck and on the nose. they may

let to fly free and the males especially, will return to a person who has fed them. they eat fruit of bananas, papaya, the sa tree, kavika tree, and flower shoots of the yaqoyaqona. they have excellent vision, and sense of smell but cannot echo-locate, as the smaller, insectiverous bats do, who live
caves. they scout around dusk, flying alone, in pairs, and sometimes in a pair of couples. in
at certain times they may appear as a great cloud of thousands; this is thought to be a sign of impending bad weather with the bats looking for food in advance. settling into a tree at night,
may fill the tree. against a torchlight their eyes may gleam like a thousand little lights, a

sight. the beka dina sleep s more in daytime. the beka lulu is active in daytime, and has much lighter colour fur. syn. (tonga) p eka. (west) bekwa. (kadavu) doli. idiom: beka ni bogi (slang) person who is active only at night. idiom: lako vakabeka to take one’s own food when going somewhere, find one ’s own food, not depending on others. syn. vuka vakabeka. idiom: samusamu beka to stand around doing nothing (usually when others are working). idiom: tuvani vaka bati ni beka very neatly arranged (like the teeth of a bat). beka . n. by ext., a boil in the armpit, very painful, causing a person to hold up the arm, like a bat-wing.
common among fij ians. syn. kirikiribeka.
v., n. pet, pamper (person, animal).
n. eyelash(es). dakudaku ni mata-na eyelids.
n. fenced area containing dairy cattle.
. n. edible leafy vegetable shrub, abelmoschus manihot, malvaceae, often grown at edge of garden, as implied by the name. (the name also means “to sprout”, of young leaves for the edible parts picked
over a fire and then placed on boils. also juice extracted to ease menstruation or childbirth.
from various parts of eastern melanesia. it was indigenous to southeast asia, still widely
in malesia. available all year but mainly december, january. bele damudamu is hardier, more durable, less susceptible to rot, smaller somewhat tougher leaves; bele vulavula and regular green
are two other cultivars. bele sukau (or) sukau refers to the edible young leaves of the small tree
gnemon, gnetaceae. sani, sanita pluck, harvest, leaves such as bele. na sani bele the harvesting of bele leaves.
gunu wai ni bele to be humiliated, reprimanded, lit. to drink the (inferred, distasteful) water from cooking bele-leaf.
. v. to sprout (of tree-leaf shoots). sa bele mai na vu-ni-kau the soft leaf-shoots of the tree are
(implying impending fruiting), esp . of forest trees and fruit-trees. belebele v. implies a multiplicity of sprouting.
. n. edge, hem (garden , cloth, etc.). . crest of a wave, bele-ni-ua. . cock ’s comb.
. (eng.) n. belt.
. (eng.) “belt”, ribbon fish, trichiurus haumela, silver colour, edible. syn. tovisi, tovici.

n. freshwater fish , gobi, inches, edible though head is discarded. as a kind of “whitebait” (a n.z . term), beli are born in the sea, move up to freshwater, where they are known variously as cigani or cinani or, around navua, namosi province, ta-nene. syn. siri-beli. beli are strictly seasonal.

n. reef heron, egretta sacra, mottled, grey or white colour. often seen around rivers. may nest fairly far inland. syn. (suva) sako. idiom: domo ni belo person who has only tea for lunch or dinner. idiom: sa suru na belo. work is done for the day; the job is finished. lit. the heron has sneezed. (time to go home.) belu, beluka v. to bend, of something strong but soft, such as tin . see lobi, lobia for bending or folding soft flat things such as mats, cloth. bena, bena v. to treat hair with dye (usually black, sometimes orange), lime, or ashes. ibena n. hair dye.
women usually like to have lustrous black hair and must dye it to have that colour. formerly
v. to overuse something, to use excessively. bena na yaqona to overuse yaqona.
(eng.) n. "benzine ", the local english for petrol, gasoline. the somewhat different white benzine for coleman lamps is referred to as benisini vulavula.
n. garbage. biuta na benu throw out the rubbish, garbage. na wai benuci the polluted water. ibenubenu n. place for throwing garbage. kava ni benu garbage tin.
v. to discard rubbish indiscriminately.
vakaca v. n. to litter. this is a modernism, of course. virtually everything a fijian used was organic plant material that decomposed naturally.

(eng.) n., adj . bankruptcy, bankrupt. bera . not yet. sa bera not yet. sa bera ni lako not yet gone. bera . late. keitou sa bera mai. we (several) are late in coming. keitou sa bera sara . we are too late. bera! bera! you are late ! (school, job). cakacaka bera (ang.) v. to work late. vakabera v. to delay , to cause to be late (person, work). bera . before, in ni bera ni . . . : ni bera ni o lako before you go. ni bera ni ’u lako . . before i go . . .
as in: ni bera na nona siga ni sucu before his birthday.
quick as lightning. beranaliva the phantom (comic book character).
slow (vehicle, boat, horse, person). keitou sa berabera. we (several) are slow. vakaberabera to slow it down.

v. to miss, to be late for. berata na basi miss the bus. bese, besetaka v. to refuse (it). au sa bese ni cakava i refuse to do it. bese! no ! i/we refuse what your are asking. (only youngsters would talk so bluntly , among themselves.)
v. to strike (of workers).
(eng.) n. basin.
in full bloom (of a plant).

(nait.) n. an ornamental plant coleus sp., red or yellow, variegated, often grown next to houses. in bauan, lata. fij ian women drink an infusion of the leaves of the red variety believing it will prompt menstruation because of the red colour.
. n. priest, traditional fij ian, or roman catholic or anglican. in eastern fiji the bete were in many
associated with a specific local clan (mataqali). among people speaking western dialects there
no special clan of priests. priests were consulted mainly prior to war, though chiefs were
always convinced of the authenticity of their powers. priests also functioned in many cases in handling the body of a dead chief. bete . v . to snap off (branchlet).
n. usefulness, purpose. e sega na betena. it is of no use.
(eng.) n. battery . syn. bateri. beti, betia v. to pluck (fruit, flower), usually with a twisting motion. betibeti (or) betia vakalevu pick
(applies to small fruit).
(colo west) n. lit. mens’ house, but referring to the basic kin-group of colo west where the now standardised types of units called yavusa and mataqali were unknown. among highlanders, adult men

in such a men ’s house, one for each extended family. wives and children lived separately. syn. (west) bito. (colo east) bure. bevu, bevuya v. to thatch (old-style fij ian house). ibevui n. thatch. leaves of the swamp plant misimisi are probably the most durable thatch. this word might not be known by fijians living in towns.
n. ceiling beam of house.
. (archaic) n. fence at the shore to enclose live captured sea turtles. the same word applies to a collection of ten turtles to be presented at some very important traditional ceremony.
. adv., adj . heavily, heavy (only for special uses). sa tau bi na uca it is raining heavily. this is a
used to express heaviness or importance. (see the following words and expressions.) ena
in a deep voice. ucu bi stuffed nose.

v. to place weight on, move the centre of gravity to another place by shifting the weight, as in a sailing boat, to shift the weight to one side or another to stay on a more even keel. ivakabi . n. paperweight, or any obj ect used to weigh down and hold something in place.
. n. stress or emphasis on a syllable (a modern term). usually in fijian pronounciation stress is on the second-to-last syllable of a word.
(eng.) n. beer.
(polyn.) n. wave(s). ena dela ni biau on top of the wave. wasawasa vakabiau very rough sea.
adj ., n. heavy, weighty, serious or important (problems, talk), severe (as in sa rui bibi na itotogi the
is too severe), weight (as in e vica na kena bibi? how much does it weigh? ); loloma bibi
(a common way of ending informal letters), or written more fully loloma bibi tu yani. tiko
of a woman , pregnant, lit. heavy (with child). na nona tiko bibi her pregnancy. e na yalo
in greatest sorrow.
especially, most importantly (in enumerating thoughts). gadreva vakabibi especially desire, seriously desire. vakabibi vei ira especially for (to, or among) them.
adj . overcome with sorrow. bici n. a bird, banded rail, gallirallus philippensis, now extinct on the main islands, due to the introduced
and also feral cats but common on small islands where those animals are ab sent. often

or scampers rather than flying. can become charmingly cheeky and rather unafraid when accustomed to people. syn. (nadro.) kuma. (kadavu, lau) bisi. idiom: ketekete ni bici na lomalagi fair clear sky with light strip s of cloud, like the breast of the bici. idiom: e lauta na bici na kena ikolo. he/she gets what is deserved (usually a just punishment). the punishment fits the crime. bika, bika . v. to press down. bika, bika . v. to refuse a favour that is asked in a presentation ceremony (usually a gift of whale-tooth)

source_text: by a return-gift of a similarly valuable thing
target_text: (another whale-tooth). see dirika.

v., n. a funeral ceremony where women sit on pile of mats on which coffin will be placed. they keep vigil, attend to the coffin and grieve for the dead. this is a traditional function of certain women only but modernly, others may also attend.
v. (rare) achieve by careful planning, manipulation. bikini . (eng.) beacon, as for sailors. bikini . (eng.) bikini bathing suit of women. (p ikini n. diaper for baby.)

n. a form of fij ian "bread" madrai ni viti, dense and chewy, made of fermented but unleavened starchy root-crop, usually cassava these days but formerly, traditionally, from ivi, polynesian chestnut.
coconut and sugar is sometimes used in the preparation. wrapping is with leaves, usually of
(= vasili= qau), cordylene terminalis. village naila, tailevu, has a reputation for making famously good bila. it is sold in the suva market as a snack food.
is a somewhat similar food. idiom: na kena bila refers to one’s specialty, a special skill or talent that a person has.

v. to crack something using a stone. na bila niu the cracking open of coconuts with a stone. bili, bilia v. to set out (wasea) portions of food (ibilibili) to be shared formally at a magiti feast, usually
of others. recipients attending the ceremony will feel offended if they are not alloted a fair share, and they are watching closely. idiom: ibilibili o tuirara excessively large share selfishly kept
n. outskirts of village.
. n. raft, usually of bamboo, made in colo east, wainibuka, and namosi to descend the river
to the coast. the wainimala and wainibuka rivers, and then the waidina river all flow into
(rewa river), that leads south to the suva area. propulsion is by the current, and by
and pushing, as implied by the word. fijians may live on the raft for three days or more.
advisable for bananas, not to get soaked, but not necessary for taro which withstands the
well. bananas were grown in the highlands, but also taro and yaqona, and then transported
to the coast, to sell around suva or nausori. the rafts never make the return journey and thus
be referred to as “hms no come back”. in some cases they have been sold cheaply for use in building in the lowlands, where bamboo is more scarce. bilibili are still reasonably common, because it

expensive to rent punts with outboard motors, or trucks for the roads that now penetrate the highlands of viti levu. ibilibili . n. portion of feast food shared out. it is placed out, often pushed there (as implied by the word),
n. cup. bilo iloilo glass (for drinking). bilo kava tin cup, bilo yaqona cup of yaqona, bilo ni yaqona
for yaqona, a smoothed half-shell of a mature coconut. cups did not exist in any form in olden times. water and even yaqona was normally lapped up. sometimes a temporary cup was improvised

a leaf but that was used only for carrying a little water a short distance. it was then lapped up or poured into someone’s mouth. idiom: bilo cicila undependable, cannot be relied on (person), lit. like a leaky cup. idiom: bilo vata words that might be said in humour, suggestively, by a man to a woman, as in daru
bilo vata, kedaru. we, we two share the same cup, have much in common, and should have an intimate relationship.
has a cup, is supplied with a cup. as an idiom, a person can be said to be vakabilo, meaning bewitched, having magical powers derived from pouring a cup of yaqona to an evil spirit. once a

a “devil” (tevoro) in this way to carry out his (usually evil) wishes, he must regularly continue to pour cups of yaqona to his devil, or great misfortune will befall him. in effect, in faustian fashion, he has made a pact from the devil and cannot withdraw from it. in a very different context, vakabilo may refer to someone of chiefly rank, as if they have been installed by having been given the official cup to drink, i.e. they have been vagunuvi.
(or) pini (eng.) n. peas, cooked, dried and salted, sold in the street as a snack. the same word may
to green beans, mostly the very long beans grown by indians, eaten as a vegetable. p ini may also refer to clothes-pins, or paper-clip s used in an office.
n. kneecap. bini, binia v. to pile up.
n. pile, heap.
v. to attach (as brooch to a dress, etc), stick up (as with thumbtack, something on the wall, etc.),
(poster on the wall). vakabira na sitaba e na mata ni waqa ni ivola. stick a postage stamp on the front of the envelope.

adj . bulging, of body veins, muscles, usually from exertion. biri, biria, birika v. to set, prop up, of a snare to catch birds, pigs; set open, of umbrella, mosquito net. birika implies more force. b irika na nomu taunamu. open up your mosquito net. bisa, bisa . v. to complete something difficult. bisa, bisa . v. to fall suddenly, to pour down, of rain usually but could apply to mud in a landslide, or anything that flows. bisa to rain on something. bisa, bisa . v. to arrive, come or occur suddenly (not a common expression). au bisa ga yani na nona lako tiko. i just arrived as he was going.
(eng.) n. biscuit, usually referring to the local breakfast biscuits, such as lee's brand or punj a brand. fijians often dunk tonia biscuits in tea and slurp them, especially those with poor teeth.
