(eng.) amen. syn. ameni.

(or) e na in, or in the, or during, as in ena vula sa oti during last month. ena rua na siga in two days. preferred spelling by official grammarian is ena though many educators disagree very strongly.
tomorrow.

(or) evereli (eng.) n. april. the p is more common in lau, cakaudrove. the v is used more often in tailevu, naitasiri, ra. eqe v. to walk in a lop-sided way, with unequal balance between the two legs. may be due to one or more
they (many) or he/she (of high chief).

(or) ira below, as opposed to e cake, above. this applies to relative height but ira may refer to the west, downwind of the speaker’s location. similarly e cake may refer to an upwind direction or uphill direction.
(or) e ratou they (few), properly eratou.
(interj ection) declining to answer, i am not sure, do not know.
(eng.) ace, as in a deck of cards.
(eng.) n. escort, usually as a guard for people of great importance. esikote-taka to escort, accompany, a dignitary on official mission.
(eng., methodist) formal estimate of financial needs of a local church for the coming year.
and planning is then given as to how these funds can be sourced and what the congregation should be asked to contribute.
(or) e so some, as in mai na veivanua e so, in some countries. used at the beginning of an expression it is perhaps more customary to separate the spelling, as e so na tamata some people.
(eng.) n. extreme unction as last rites for a dying roman catholic.

(eng.) aide-de-camp, formerly serving the governor. may be heard as tikoqe. eu! interjection of pain, or of rej ection, disgust, especially in response to something said, or something offered. as with most expressions, this may be said in j est. one sometimes hears u!
(or) e vei where (as a question).
(eng.) n . april. syn. ep ereli.
v. to grow big, espec. of the body.
n. a seaside tree, hernandia peltata or h . nymphaeifolia, hernandiaceae, the inner bark often used as an abortifacient. (scientific tests on rats indicate no such effect - r.g.)
is no letter f in mainland fijian languages. it is the polynesian equivalent of the fij ian v in

and has been introduced by tongans on the smaller islands, especially in lau. some english or tongan words with f are now sometimes pronounced with that letter. the letter v is sometimes used in place of an f, except for distinctly lauan words or for some adaptions of english words.
(eng.) father, form of address for roman catholic priest.

(lau) treat the hair with lime (lase) as conditioning. “faiba” or “fibre” (eng.) n. fibreglass boat, usually open-topped, operated by an outboard engine. in some places this has replaced the wooden punt and and small cutters used for short trips.

(or) ifaele (eng.) n. file. f ailetaka v. to file, fijians' way of sharpening knives. bush knives (cane knives) are made of soft steel that can be sharpened readily by frequent filing. knife-filing justifies resting between bouts of hard work cutting weeds, grass.
(eng.) n. final (in sports), referring to the last championship game. semi-f ainala semi-finals. can be used as a verb as well as noun.
(lau) v. to sit cross-legged, as done by men.
(lau, from togan f aiva) n. expertise, special skill from experience.
(lau) n. spokesman-protocol officer for lauan chief. the equiv. of matanivanua among mainland fijians. sometimes pronounced vaka.

(tonga) n. spontaneous giving of gifts during dances, or functions of two different groups of people, often a man ’s shirt. may include money slipped into the clothes of dancers, flour sprinkled on their head. syn. tibivuru.
(lau) v. to do, to make, bauan cakava.
. (eng.) n. flour. along with rice and cassava, this is now a main staple starch foods of fij ians,
it is much less nutritious. these introduced starches have been cheaper than traditional root crops and are less perishable. flour is used for many fried breakfast foods.
. (eng., lau) a starch food treated as kakana dina, “true food”, such as taro or yam, cooked in
at meals with a garnish (icoi), or at breakfast with tea. because of the shortage of
starch-foods in the smaller islands of lau, store-bought flour is mixed with grated cassava and coconut as a basic food.

(lau) n. house. traditional lauan houses follow tongan style with rounded ends, rather than appearing strictly rectangular. syn. vale. (west) were, sue. “fale fisi” (tonga) n. the clan ha’a fale fisi, of the tongan royal family, as founded by tapu ’osi, the

lakeba, a waciwaci chief who married sinaitakala i langileka, tu ’i tonga fefine, daughter of th tele’a, tu ’i tonga. the narewadamu are true kailakeba, early chiefs of lakeba, replaced ultimately by the vuanirewa people of the tui nayau who retain a separate but similar affiliation with
a royal wife from the sacred, royal island of tungua in tonga. tui naosara settled on nayau and his two sons were the first vuanirewa.
(eng., lau) n. family.
(eng.) n. funnel. faqa! (interj ection) cheat ! (in playing, usually marbles).
(bib.) n . pharisee.
(lau) n. lauan chiefly serving-bowl especially for kava, the rim inlaid with pearl shell, and
twelve legs instead the the four legs that are more common elsewhere in fij i. the artefact is tongan in concept. vakaf atu (or) vakavatu as an anglicism, may also refer to a very wealthy person.

(rotuma) n . traditional sweet pudding with thick coconut cream, sometimes sold in the public market. the starch basis has been mostly taro, sometimes yam. (yams rarely used in fij ian sweet puddings).
(or) veverueri (eng.) february. fika . (eng., lau) adj . to be smart, clever, adept.

(lau): meca i a f ika ga, or meca qo na f ika ga. literally , “the thing is to think it through”, more figuratively, “(things will be done) by hook or by crook”. fika . (eng.) v . to calculate. fika . (eng.) n . arithmetic, figure.
(eng.) v. to calculate a total (isoqoni) in arithmetic.
subtraction na musumusu. musu e rua sa tolu. five minus two is three.
addition sosoqoni. kei na rua sa vitu. five plus two is seven.
multiplication na vakalevutaki. vakarua sa tini. five times two is ten.

division na wasewase. wase rua sa lima. ten divided by two is five. “fire!” (slang) pron. “faiya!”, go ahead ! begin ! let’s go ! "fifty cents " (eng, slang) a very vulgar taunt, meaning "coward", implying a loose rectum as large as a fifty-cents coin.

(eng.) n. movie film or photographic film. fiu . (lau, tongan “fihu”) n. a type of very fine white woven sleeping mat. fiu . (lau, tongan “fiu”) tired, worn out, done in, fed up. syn. oca. “fix”-taka v. to arrange, to set up, to iron out (a problem), to fix. “fix”, “fix”-taka v. to try to win over a woman, with a desire to make love, arrange intercourse with or for someone. au na qai f ixtaka a dua na nomu. i will get you a partner for making love.
(eng.) n . fox, and may refer to someone cunning like a fox. slang: yalewa f okisi prostitute.
(eng.) v. to assemble in a formal group, “fall in”, of soldiers, or children assembled at school.
(eng.) n. foreman .
. (eng.) n. form (to be filled out). vakalewena na f omu. fill out the form.
. (eng.) n. form, as a class of secondary school that in fiji can extend through form seven, in preparation for possible tertiary education.
(tonga) sinnet fly whisk as used by chieftains.
(eng.) floor. syn. buturara.

source_text: the letter g is pronounced as
target_text: a soft ng, as in going, fling. it is not pronounced like the ng in anger. in western viti levu, gwa may replace the ga, as in gwata for gata (snake), or tagwane for tagane (man) in eastern fij i.

. n. duck. ga ni vatu peregrine falcon, rather rare in fiji. ga loa (or) ga ni viti pacific black duck, common wild duck at rivers and coastal shores. syn. (lau) p ato. idiom: sili vaka ga lit., bathe like a duck, said to a child who takes a quick, superficial bath, not bathing properly. idiom: tamata daku ni ga person who cannot listen or follow instructions. words flow off as water from a duck ’s back, an anglicism. ga . only, just, a particle used with some words to limit them: wale ga only. wale ga oqo just now. o
only you. tiko ga forever, always. in written fijian this particle is often joined to the word that follows it. the expression o iko ga! can have romantic implications.
. v. mouth open, agape, stare, usually with a blank look. ga cake! open your mouth ! (as a dentist

request). dalaga! open your mouth wide (as mother to child, giving medicine). ga balavu remain gaping, doing nothing with a blank stare into space. kakua ni ga balavu! don't gape ! don ’t stare ! (to child). mata gaga face agape. ga calucalu to be at a loose end, idle with nothing much on the mind. igaga n. spout, as of teapot.
. n. guts, intestines. . by extension, equipment, spare parts for motors, engines. syn. iwawa intestines. idiom: ivola gacagaca document, manual.
v. to walk at ease, usually for pleasure, take a pleasure trip. au na gagade tu mai kea. i will be
around over there. vale ni igagade holiday cottage. ilakolako vakagade pleasure trip.
ni igagade ni saravanua tourist spot. gade siga tolu take a three-day trip. syn. gadi. (colo east) gadea.
. (archaic) n. a type of fij ian fighting club.
. brother of one’s mother or husband of father’s sister. see below. syn. momo. gadigadi . n. object of romantic love. igadigadi . n. place to relax and pass the time peacefully .

and gadi n. a type of family relative, man , mother's brother or the husband of one's father's sister. bauans use the term vugo-na. gadre, gadreva v. to desire, want, wish for (anything). au bau gadreva tu meu lako i just wish i could go. na gagadre the desire.
n. palate, extending to the gums. mate ni gadro gum disease. gadro lala toothless.
adj . prickly, thorny (as of some trees, citrus, sago palm, some liana vines. wa gadrogadro a prickly vine, a wild raspberry, rubus moluccanus. gadro, gadrota v. to prickle.
v. to pierce, as by a needle or thorn. syn. qarota.
(lau) n. finely woven soft cummerbund of pandanus matting made by tongan procedures,
intended for formal occasions including church services. it is customary to use worn or

torn matting, to give a sense of humility. this is not worn in the moala region (yasayasa moala), part of lau province, and not in some parts of northern lau province that are more closely related to cakaudrove than to the more tongan culture of lau.
n. spout, as in small, clay pot for water to be drunk. ga refers to mouth agape, since fijians poured
the mouth, the pot being held several inches above. lip s never touched the drinking vessel and there were not cups. by ext., igaga might modernly apply to the spout on a teapot.
. adj . bitter, overly concentated, distasteful, "hot" (of chili). sa rui gaga na kari. the curry is very “hot”. sa gaga na wainimate. the medicine tastes bad.

. adj ., n. poison, poisonous, toxic, polluted. vakagaga na wai to pollute the water. vakagagai polluted. wainimate gaga ni veivaka-mateni-taki intoxicating drugs (mateni intoxicated). e na rawa ni ko ni gaga kina. it is possible that you could be poisoned by it. e rawa ni vagagai ko ira na dau kania. people who usually eat it could be poisoned. in ancient times fij ians used at least three species of plant as poisons to be consumed by their enemies.
kalou, pittosporum sp., pittosporaceae, was pounded and mixed in yaqona (capell, p. ); lobau, brugsmansia suaveolens (formerly datura candida), also mixed in yaqona in colo east as i
recorded in oral histories; and mavu ni toga, antiaris toxicaria, moraceae, for which i have
information on how it was used. antiaris spp. have long been used in asia as a poison to
humans. apparently fij ians did not usually use poison on their arrows or spears. used as an
were colourful (bright red and stark black) seeds of diridamu, abrus precatorius, but its

cyanide often killed the mother as well as the foetus. formerly, diridamu were used in necklaces, now forbidden due to the dangerous poison. so small and quick-acting, diridamu has been used in food for assassinations.
adj . to be sitting idly, not knowing what needs to be done.

n. wish, desire. a cava na nomu gagadre? what is your desire? what would you like? gagano, gaganotaka v. to desire secretly someone, usually sexually. somewhat more moderately, gano, ganova. garo, garova v. applies to lust for a person, or some thing very greatly desired.
n. deep-seated desire (usually sexual, usually futile). “gagaj” (rotuma) n. chief in one of the seven districts of rotuma. may be used as a title. there is no
chief on the island though one eccentric character has claimed to be “king”. the letter “g” is pronounced with a soft “ng”, as it is in fijian.
v. to have an excessively strong scent.
n. tetanus.
n., adj . very sharp, as of a knife or spear. syn. momoto, as applied to spears, pencils. gata sharp (and also, as a noun, for `snake).
v. desire deeply.
adj . ineffectual, useless, of a person in any endeavor. a lack of motivation or ability is implied.
. n. pet pig, or affectionate name for pigs, used to call out to pigs to come and be fed. it has been a
custom to adopt very young pet pigs, a custom discontinued in fij i. formerly, women sometimes nursed them at the breast. syn. geti.
. (vanua levu) v. do not want. au gai ni la ’o. i don ’t want to go.
(or) gaigaiya . n., adj . a colour, light or soft yellowish (can have brownish or dusky tone) usually referring to wilted vegetation or to faded, sullied cloth , not usually to human skin.
adj . free, independent, available. sa tu vagalala o seru seru is living (and farming) alone,
of the village and legally free of usual traditional obligations. na tu-galala nei viti the independence of fiji. o galala ? are you available (free)? me galala na nomu vakasama. free
mind (do not worry). by extension, may indicate that some item of clothing is too large, too
about the body. sa galala tu na nomu tarusese. your pants are loose (too big). colonial
established a system whereby a fijian individual or nuclear family could be released from
and clan responsibilites to be independent (galala). although ratu sukuna himself lived

any clan or village responsibilities, he discouraged that system for fij ians generally, believing they were not ready for it. the system failed partly because independent fijians usually lived close to their village, and villagers by custom would not release them from traditional obligations. vagalala, vagalalataka v. to make free, available, to clear off or out or away. vagalalataka na teveli clear off the table. vagalalataka na vale clear out the house (make it free, available). me vagalala na
to vacate the room. vagalalataki iko mai vei iratou stay away from them.

. have one ’s head tilted to one side and/or supported with a hand, usually indicating lack of interest, attention, relaxed sa vagalegale tu ga o seru seru has his head to one side of his shoulder (can be with head in hand). gale . n.,v . to eat, something to eat, idiom from galegale j aw. a cava na ka ni gale? what is to eat? what are we having for food? galegale-na n. molar(s), side teeth, side of the j aw.

v., adv. to be relaxed, even when doing something. e a taubale vagalegale sobu mai. he walked down here relaxedly. gale, vagaleta . v. to need, care about. au sega ni galeti iko i do not need you. au sega ni vagaleta

i do not care for beer. gale, galeta, galeleta . v. to care for, desire, to be motivated with interest. kevaka e sega ni galeleta na yalomu na cauravou oqori, kakua ni gole vua. if your heart does not strongly care for that young man, do not go to him. syn. galele.
adj . lonely.
adj . of child who is curious, independent, picking up things and leaving them somewhere else; of adult who sees things and picks them up without asking. a loner who is not properly socialised.

(colo) n. night. ma lutu mai na galo. the night is falling. vakagalo afternoon. vakagalo have dinner. galu, galuva v., adj . to be silent (of person) speechless, dumb. galu! shut up ! fijians are taught not to speak in the presence of their elders. galuva to be silent in relation to someone or something. see tiko lo.
adj . quiet, silent (person), rarely speaking.

adj . silent, as in sa dua na bogi vagagalu. it is a silent night. galu, galuva, galuvaka v. to be silent, speechless, dumb, to be silent in relation to someone, or some people, galuva . e galuvi au na ganequ. my sister may not speak with me (man speaking). galuvaka v. to be silent about it, deliberately, to clam up. vagaluya na gone to quiet down the child. na vakagalu ni gusumu! this will shut you up ! galu! be silent ! galu na gusumu! shut your mouth !
mada! quiet down ! vagagalu to make someone be silent. in the face of direct questions, a
may assume the right to remain silent. (silence, or non-response may often mean “no” to a request.) see tiko lo!.
v. to remain deliberately silent through self-interest, to avoid getting involved or found out, to avoid revealing something. e so na ka eda dau vakagaluya. some things we do not talk about.
n. silence (no people talking). may refer, for example, to the prohibition of speech between father and daughter-in-law. also, formerly, a brother and sister might not converse.

v. do something a second time to do it better. na kena igalui the second try, which will complete it. could apply to burning off garden again, or to an additional ceremony that will satisfy people that it has been done properly.

n. sibling of the opposite sex, sister (of male), brother (of female). e rau sa veiganeni. they (two) are brother and sister. na gane i siteri esther's brother. this has been a tabu relationship, no talking, looking, or any contact, unless the sister is older, acting in motherly role. na veiganeni the brother and sister. ganei n. father's sister, abbrev. from gane i tamaqu; now often further abbreviated as nei.
v. to be suitable, appropriate, match (of clothes). sa veiganiti vinaka na nona vosa. his/her
apt, appropriate. erau veiganiti na nomu vava kei na nomu vinivo. your shoes and your dress match nicely. e ganiti iko na sote oqori. that shirt really suits you. na ka o ganita! that's
you deserve ! na itotogi e veiganiti kei na cala. the punishment fits the crime. e sega ni veiganiti me kaburaki ena walesi. it is not appropriate to broadcast on the radio.

ni vatu n. peregrine falcon. syn. (northern lau) tuitui. black head, breast, flank and thighs striped black on cream. staple diet is flying fox fruit bat, finches, pigeons, some sea birds. eyrie on cliffs, - white eggs with brown blotches. watling says the long pointed wings and long tail are distinctive. gano, ganova v. to gape or stare with desire, to lust after. gara, garata v. to snarl wildly, angrily, snort. ucu gara makes a wild angry face (or, simply) have large
a flat nose. kua ni garata na gone. don't snarl at the kid(s). e garati au mai o
he shouted snarlingly at me just now. kua ni gara. don't shout angrily . syn. kara .
v. to like to eat immature fruit, as in pregnancy. syn. bati vou. garo, garova v. to have a strong desire for (a food or drink), or lust after (a person, sex).
adj . having rabid desire (a food, drink), or lustful (with sexual desire). see vorivori.

v. to want something that will never give satisfaction. na ka o gasa! that's what you yourself wanted ! (often said sarcastically). idiom: dau gasa yawa always wants the inaccessible. often said of a person who stays away from home, feeling more comfortable elsewhere.
adj . tasty, delicious, nicely sweet. mata gasagasa cute, sexually attractive (of person).
v. to make a food or beverage tasty or sweet, as in adding a condiment. igasagasa n. sweetener, condiment, such as salt.
n. reed, arrow. gasau kuro n. bomb. gasau nunu torpedo. gasau ni dakai bullet.
kinds of reeds are gasau saisai (= gasau lailai) used for multi-pronged fishing spears and
for arrows, gasau dina used for house-walls, fish-fences. reeds also served commonly as
the innovation of newspapers. (see roth, fij ian way of lif e, p. ). flowering of reeds, miscanthus floridulus, occurs around february-march , signaling a time of flies, and a time of

(cika). in western viti levu, reeds were commonly used for the walls and roofs of native houses. syn. (west) sina. (nadro) hina. idiom: daru qai laki sota ki na gasau leka . we are not likely to meet again, lit. we will meet next at

source_text: the place where the short reed grows
target_text: (at bua, supposedly the jumping-off place to the next world, after death).
n. bomb. na vakalutu gasaukuro. the bombing.
(archaic) n. cannon balls.
v. (vanua levu) to refuse.
adj . sharp. vagata. to sharpen (knife, axe). rui gata very sharp .
n. snake, the pacific boa, candoia bibroni, a harmless, nocturnal tree-climber that gives live birth
meter but the boa can grow to two meters. locally, the boa has its colour variations which led
to think there were several species, and the personality can become a quite snappy in some places, kabara, for example. males have tiny vestigial claspers or spurs around the cloaca. formerly,

source_text: necklaces were sometimes made of the snake’s
target_text: back-bones. modernly, fijians might generally refer to all or any snakes as gata. in fij i there are no venemous land snakes that ever bite people. the small, to inch bolo, ogmodon vitiensis, is deadly poisonous but is shy, very rarely seen, and has never been
to bite anyone. the boa was eaten in taveuni, ovalau, namosi, and kadavu and in the
of viti levu (namosi and colo east) and probably other places. tavuki people of taveuni

snakes for the tui cakau to eat. in some places the snake is sacred, and may be a totem. at village somosomo on taveuni island it has had ritual significance. similarly on kadavu island, village naikorokoro, sanima district, tribe suesue, there has been great ritual significance to the snake; they kept a bai ni gata, snake pit in a pile of rocks, and practised ceremonies that revitalised the people.
for the snake brings up a connection between the vusaratu people of nacula island
or muddy water. nacula’s vusaratu people opted to become tribe drola (sic) which again refers to murky waters (from algae) of the bay where they arrived and settled.
more is known of their old relationship. it is well known that the ancestral god degei takes
a cave explain any thunder that is heard but he is quite inoffensive, little interested in
affairs, if at all. degei was the name of a legendary immigrant chief, later deified. some oral history refers to degei i and degei ii. syn. (colo east, namosi) balei.
. n. glottal stop that in pronunciation replaces the t in parts of ra and western vanua levu, and
the k in eastern vanua levu. gatotaka na t. put a glottal stop in place of the letter t. sa gatotaki na k mai bua. the letter k is replaced with a glottal stop in bua. in some vanua levu areas

the t and the k are replaced by glottal stops; this is referred to as gato rua, another term newly invented by school teachers. gato . adj . able to speak a local dialect as if from that area. gato, gatova v. to peer, peek, usually secretly or without disturbing.

(lau) n. large barkcloth used in presentation ceremonies. there are two kinds, gatu vakatoga and gatu vakaviti. the tongan type used freely hand-painted design, mostly with tan colour, and often has writing relevant to the occasion. the fijian type has more formal geometric design using stencils and often, darker colouring.

n. major or principal section or part of something, mid-section, suggesting large size. gaunisala roadway, path . gau ni vosa main body of a speech . gau ni kau chunk of wood. gau levu big bodied, stocky (person, animal). syn. tolo-na. idiom: gau kau beat someone with a stick. in jocular j ibing with a person from gau island, one

the term gau kau that calls to mind the supposedly great power of the gau people. in fact, that power has been more imaginary than real. the expression usually raises a smile. idiom: silima na gau ni dali to intrude in a conversation, lit. dive for the middle (rather than the end) of a rope fallen in the water.

(onam.) meaow, the cry of a cat. gauna n. time. ena gauna vou in modern times. ena so na gauna sometimes. ena gauna kece ga at all times. ena gauna oya at that time. ena veigauna eso sometimes, occasionally. ena veigauna
in colonial times. e veiveigauna at various times. na gauna ni liliwa (katakata) the

of cold (hot) season. gauna ni vuata fruit season (tree-fruit : bananas, citrus, etc.) ena veigauna sa bera mai. in times to come, in the future. vagauna sometimes, occasional, occasionally. e vagauna ga na kena vua. the fruit is only seasonal. vagaunataka na veitau cici to time the running race. vakagauna occasional, occasionally (more commonly vagauna.)
n. “new era”, a name adopted by apolosi r. nawai (ca. -) renegade political dissident, to express the importance of his indigenous movement. he first formed an association called
vou. his commercial enterprise viti kabani “fiji company” collap sed and he was

by government authorities at the instance of ratu sukuna who had him deported to new zealand, and then exiled, first to yacata island, later to die at yanuca island (just off qamea island). he had led a flamboyant personal life and had a large following as a sort of indigenous prophet. some
is still occasionally used by fijians for some new venture, more mundane than nawai ’s vision. gauniliga-na n. forearm (human).
. n. road. see sala path.

. n. by ext., means, ways. me taurivaki eso na gaunisala me cakava. use some means of doing it. idiom: mo muria na nomu gaunisala. you are to follow proper protocol, as in the formalities of entering a village, or approaching a chief. formal communications were supposed to follow traditional paths.
n. calf (of the human leg).
adj . off-condition, pale, weak, worn out, dirty, of people or materials such as clothes, matting, barkcloth. gavugavu cowardly.
adj . useless to others, ineffectual (of a person), uncooperative, listless and lazy, implicitly dirty. in ra this word can be slang for “naughty”. syn. gavu-sa.

adj . mentally vacant, of unfocussed mind, droopy headed, inattentive to present surroundings. may imply sleepy headed. gede, gedea v. to rock back and forth , to shake, or bob up and down (as in mixing a cocktail). gedea na
lailai rock the baby. vagedegedea na lori rock the truck (to move it). gedea na tavaya ni
shake the milk bottle. gedea na niu shake the coconut (to check for presence of internal liquid).
toss about, as a small boat in rough seas. see gude, gudea. syn. kurea.
rocking about, rumbling (thunder), bobbing up and down (fishing float in the water). see vude to bob up and down.
v. to classify , set a standard or set an example.
n. class, classification, standard, example (that demonstrates a standard), relative quality . na ivakatagedegede ni qito. the standard of playing (sports).
v. to open up the ripe ivi nut (polynesian chestnut), or open the kai (mussel).
v. wobble, as something not firmly in place.
adj . proud of bearing.
adj ., v. lame, to limp . yava gera game leg. vageregere, vageregerea v. to have rhythmic fluctuation, as in the throbbing of a drum (fij ian lali). na vageregerea ni lali.
v . to crash, usually of something heavy falling.
n . pet pig. syn. gai.

v., n. buzz, as of mosquitos. gi, givaka v. to squeak (bat), squeal (pig), yelp (dog, person), buzz (mosquito). na cava e givaka na vuaka ? what's the pig squealing about? children make the sound gi in teasing and reproaching each other. it goes with a facial expression and sometimes pinching. in former times, warriors were said to make this sound in attacking.
n. friendly ground dove, gallicolumba stairii, actually quite timid, brown colour, it “coos” the way
tu. godro v. and n. to grunt, groan, grumble sa godro tiko na ketequ. my stomach is rumbling. such use of
gogo mai niu sa qase. i have become weak with age. sa vakagogotaki au na noqu tauvimate
illness has weakened me. ka kua ni dau gogo nomu itovo. don't let your behaviour deteriorate
(lack of resolve). gogo . n. bird species, black noddy, anous tenuirostris, grey colour with white cap, often seen with the
common brown booby, sula leucogaster, gutulei or toro or tero, but is smaller in size. or may

to common noddy, anous stolidus, gogo or rosawa which also has distinctive white cap. syn. drelo. gole, goleva v. to proceed, turn away or turn toward. igolegole n. turn-off, turning off point, turning

(in a new direction). lako yani ekea qai gole ki na bati ni wai. go over there and then turn off toward the river bank. sa goleva vakalevu na yaloqu. my mind keep s turning back to that. qai gole yani vale! come over to my house ! au sa gole mada. i beg to take my leave. idiom: gole ki (na dua na vanua) allied with (some more important territory), referring usually to
ties between two territories, usually a minor one and a major one. this is an alliance, not a

relationship . there was an advantage of mutual protection in this traditional type of relationship. vagole, vagolea v. to direct (boat, car) toward (some place). gole, golea v. to push back and forth (tree stump to test if it can be removed, digging stick to plant crops, garden fork in digging planting-mounds, gearshift of car to change gears).
v. to shake back and forth sharply or forcibly. goletaka na uluna shake the head sharply from side to side, as in certain dance motions.
thus, therefore, aforementioned, because of that, referring to something previously said or understood. idiom: koya gona! that's it ! (that's what i've been trying to tell you, that's what i meant).
. n. child, youngest one (of family); gone tagane boy. gone yalewa girl. vagonegonea childish. vagone child-like. gone yaga helpful child. gonevuli pupil, student (inc. university).

biu vuli school-leaver. gone tubutubu adolescent child. gone dramidrami baby at nursing stage. na itabagone the young generation (children). gone ni toko pampered, favoured child. idiom: tamata vagone person who has a devil (tevoro) who is served (as in pouring yaqona in tribute) in return for favours that are usually evil. conceptually , looking after the devil is as looking after a child, requiring attentive care but it is dangerous if duties are neglected. syn. vakatevoro. idiom: gone turaga (or) gone marama respectful reference to a chief, male turaga or female marama.
. adj . young. na itei gone the young plant(s). tamata gone young person. na itaba gone the youthful generation. gone vei au younger than me. oi au gone sara. i am the youngest.
n. traditional type of kin-group serving a paramount chief as fishermen (usually of turtle), or

collecting human bodies for chiefly consumption (as in the case of the lasakau on bau island). these were sailors of tongan origin. their language has some differences from other versions of the fij ian languages.
n. fisherman.
n. chiefly title, centred in ra province in the area of nakorotubu. there is confusion and
as to the origin and lineage associated with this title. there is no tradition of a formal
ceremony. close connection to super-tribe dewala and the early history of bau island.
a very close relationship with bau. curiously, this title has no extensive territory and no
tribe. n. l. c. official report lists the title as na sau. (tribe dewala itself has become fragmented and dispersed widely.)
n. first-born baby of a mother. see ulumatua.
(or) gone ni vuli n. school child(ren), young student.
n. motivation, physical energy. tovolea ena nomu gu taucoko. try with all your might. e malumalumu na nodratou gu. their (several) motivation is weak.

n. force of effort with powerful motivation. e kaukauwa na nodratou igu. their powerful force is strong. nomu igu! give all your effort ! (yelled at athletes). gudea vakaigu to shake it vigorously, energetically. igu matua diligent, diligence. vinaka na igu matua . thanks for trying hard. vagugu, vagugutaka v. to hum, as of a melody, usually when the words have been forgotten. gu, guta, gutaka, guraka v. to apply effort. gu vakaukauwa to try hard. guta vakaukauwa to try hard for it. guraka! really go for it ! idiom: lai guguraki v. go to the toilet (to defecate). this is socially polite usage, more common in the

than the bauan term veka. perhaps the most frequently used polite term is the verb valelailai, referring to the physical toilet itself. (no such facility in earlier days. faeces were concealed to avoid black magic.) idiom: gu vaka tina-ni-gone to try very hard, like a woman giving birth. idiom: vagugu v. to rush wildly. rau sa vagugu yani me rau yacova rawa made ga na gusu ni qara.
(two) rushed over to reach the mouth of the cave.
adj . lacking motivation, energy, lazy . gu-ca-taka v. to fail to apply oneself at something. syn. gu ce.

adj ., adv. hasty, forceful, slipshod, of a person, or some work or action. guce, guce-taka v. to fail by lack or motivation or energy, not to be interested or motivated, to give up the effort. ira sa guce ena vaqarai iratou. they (many) failed in the search for them (few). gude, gudea, guderaka . v. to cradle in the arms and gently rock, as with a baby. gude, gudea . v. to shake. gudea na vunikau me lutu na vuana shake the tree so the fruit will fall. gude! shake it ! supportive cry to dancers (taralala, tamure or disco dance, not meke). gudea na "cocktail" shake the cocktail. syn. gede, gedea . gudu, guduva . v. (colo east) to pull out, off with the hands. (electric plug, vines off a fruit-tree). syn. gutu, gutuva. gudu, guduva . v. to cut off. igudu piece of something that has been cut off. syn. gutu, gutuva.
n. (archaic) type of sharp-edged, oar-shape warclub, much less wide than the kinikini. guileca, guilecava v. to forget. see leca. guiguileca adj . forgetful. na guiguileca n. the loss of memory.

hard-to-forget, unforgettable. syn. lecava. see liaca. gule, gulea v. to press or push back and forth, to test the firmness, as of a tooth possibly loose, of a newly placed house-post in the ground to test its solidarity. gunu, gunuva v. to drink, drink it. me gunu di na bilo yaqona drink dry the cup of yaqona. gunuva
drink it dry. vagunuva na ose water the horse (give water to drink). sa gunu vinaka. that
(of beverage). syn. (kadavu) somi, somica. idiom: dau vagunu person who dispenses herbal medicines.
sevusevu v. to drink water from cupped hands, a relatively modern custom outdoors. more traditionally, fij ians drank directly from streams, putting their face to the water, or from water vessels,
the mouth, with the vessel several inches from the face. cups as such never

source_text: existed before the introduction of coconut cups
target_text: (bilo) for drinking kava and no other liquid. originally, bilo referred just to human knee-caps.

n. installation of a chief (by having him drink the ceremonial cup of kava offered), a custom of most but not all fij ian tribes. for some territories it is said that no installation ceremony is necessary

as to the rightful successor.) some christian sects now forbid their members to drink kava. vagunuvi installed, of a chief, having drunk the installation cup of yaqona. igunugunu . n. flavour, taste of a drink (or melon, orange, ice cream). igunugunu . n. source for drinking water for a village or community.
n. colourful damsel fish of the reef, various species in various colours, but of the same shape,
algae, often fearless of people. unaffected by poison cells of anemone. with tough prickly
and tough skin, guru is usually grilled on a fire and then skinned. dorsal spines make the fish
to handle. this fish has special significance to waimaro highlanders of serea and their distant kinfolk who migrated to the shores of southern viti levu, centred around village muaivuso. there it is

. n. mouth. gusuniwai river-mouth. gusu coci harelip, cleft lip. gusu bona bad breath, halitosis. gusu kaukauwa "big mouth ", outspoken, rough mannered. gusu ca or gusugusu ca backbiter, gossip, uses rough language. gusugaga spiteful, hurtful, nasty. gusu tete broad-lipped (tete lit. spread-out). gusu kabasu cannot keep a secret. gusu macala clear speaker. gusu macamaca voluble, never at a loss for words. gusu wa or gusa tabu wawa to talk on and on, incessant talker.
ni vosa spokesman. gusu-sika one who cannot keep a secret. gusu totolo n. rapid talker, a
many fijians, especially in broadcasting; fij ian speech in general is much faster than virtually all polynesian speech .
. n.,v. spokesperson, spokesman, with a possessive pronoun suffix; as a verbal form, to speak
(several) of us fijians who are in new zealand.
adj . verbal or oral (not written).
(anglicism) n. microphone; spokesperson.
ineffectual talk just for the sake of appearances.
as in na wili gusutaki the reading aloud, reciting, mouthing the words.

adj . loquacious with futile talk, babbler. guta v. refers to a strong feeling of missing someone, or longing to be with someone. e guta na lomaqu meu raici kemuni. i long to see you. guta v. (vanua levu) to take it all, using force if necessary, not leaving anything. gutu, gutuva, gutulaka v. to snap off (twig, string) or pull out and off with the hands (electric plug,
off a fruit-tree), sever, cut off (rope, cloth from a bolt of cloth), separate off. gutugutu,
snap off in pieces (string, vine). syn. gudu, guduva. using an axe or heavy knife on sticks of wood, this word implies chopping across the grain. may be used figuratively as in tagutuvi mai na
vanua dina of a people, cut off, separated from their own true land. this has been said of
people, expelled from ovalau by cakobau. ragutu or cagutu snapped off, severed, without that being deliberately done.
n. seabird, sula spp., brown booby or masked booby (never nest in trees) or red-footed booby (nests in trees), sula sp., both very common. syn. toro, vava-biau.
v. to run for one's life, to flee. gutuwa-taka desperately run off with it.
city. quite a few noun-forms begin with the letter i when the noun-form is adapted from a verbal root-form.

"the knife" na isele is adapted from the verb “to cut” sele, seleva. by cabinet dictum in march , that i should be attached as part of the noun-form. nonetheless, in much common writing in fiji, the word can often still be seen as nai sele or na isele. in this dictionary that word would appear
the letter s, first letter of the root-word sele. in ordinary, fast speech, one might not always hear the letter i that precedes many nouns.
. of, an abbreviation of ni as in: tama i seru father of seru .
. to (or) to the, an abbrev. of ki or ki na. siro sobu ki matasawa go down to the beachfront.

. alternative, regional pronounciation for the prefix “e” in word combinations helping to indicate direction. i ra, ira or e ra below (or downwind). i cake (or) e cake above (or upwind) . those words sometimes used as a suffix to a place-name, as in nananu-ira island.

. an attached prefix that indicates a noun adapted from a verbal root-form : isele knife (from the verb “cut” sele); idabedabe seat, chair, saddle (from the verb “to sit” dabe). some fijians prefer to see that “i” float alone, unattached to the noun.
. v. to go. ia mai! come here ! ia i suva go to suva. syn. lako. (vanua levu) la ’o.
. word that stands alone, indicating a pause, meaning “well, . . .” ia ! . said rather forcefully, this can be the equivalent of “hey, you !”, catching a person ’s attention.

. (or) ia ka but, used as a conjunction (isema) in a sentence. au via lako ia sa sega ni rawa. i want to go but it is not possible. ia, iataka . v. to take place, occur, to be performed or done. sa ia tiko na bose the meeting is taking place. iataka na meke to perform the exhibition-dance. iauwe! emotional interj ection, when a person is surprised, amazed, fatigued, suddenly sorrowful. syn. oiauwe.
n. mat. ibe ni moce sleeping mat. ibe ni kana mat for serving meals, of cotton cloth or woven

leaves. ibe vulavula woven mat with no coloured fringe of wool (kula) and no blacking (somo) from dyed pandanus leaves. ibe vakula mat fringed with colourful wool (formerly red feathers (kula). ibe kilukilu course-woven floor mat (kilu refers to the plain finishing edge with no fringe).
a type of mat unique to udu, macuata province, having no fringe but a very strong, straight edge. ibe vakabati mat with several layers of wool fringe for covering a bed. bati ni vasua mat with
saw-tooth edges. ibe pap ua decorative mat with intricately interwoven black geometric design,
island (and some overseas melanesian places). ibe vakavutuvutu mat with finely sliced
fringe. ibe kuta (or) ibe sasa mat made from sedge, a specialty of bua; it is softer but less durable; traces years old have been found at sigatoka sand dunes. ibe ni tonga round mat used

dining tables. tabu kaisi refers to a very high quality , fine mat made at ono island, southern lau. most mats are made with leaves of voivoi, pandanus sp., about leaves needed for one sleeping mat, some four feet wide and seven feet long, but as many as may be used. a floor mat is referred to as icoco. ibe ni valagi rug or carpet. syn. for mat (west, vanua levu) loga. (lau) yaba.
n. edible type of worm, often found buried in sand, eaten raw or used as bait, siphonosoma australe. syn. bou. idi . (eng.) n. inch. e lima na idi. five inches. idi . (eng.) n. hinge.
n. india, indian person, people. kaiidia indian (person), more politely , turaga ni idia or marama ni
indian gentleman or indian lady.
(eng.) n. engine. idini cavu outboard motor. punts with outboard engines have replaced the sailing
so common at mid-century. idini dabe refers to a boat engine that is installed, not readily removable. idini ni cina generator to produce electricity.
(eng.) n. engineer, mechanic.
(eng.) england. bolatagane is an older term, more honorific. peretania great britain .
(eng.) egypt.

(polyn.) n. fish. ika vuka flying fish. ika bau sp. of river fish, eliotris melanosoma or ophieleotris aporos, syn. (kadavu) vorina, (west) miqa. ika ni wai droka fresh water fish. ika droka raw fish,

ikadroka flagtail, kuhlia rupestris. ika ni laca sailfish , istiophorus sp., ika toa lion fish (see below), ika vavi oven-cooked fish. ika tavu grilled fish. ika vakalolo fish cooked in coconut cream. tobo, toboka na ika catch the fish. syn. (eastern macuata) koli. (western macuata) qoli, (colo east) ilava. (tonga) ika. idiom: tobo ika ena vanua mamaca. lit. catch fish on dry land, i.e., attempt the impossible.
n. sea turtle, any kind. may also refer to a live fish.

n. a kind of mullet, cestraeus sp., a significant source of food from rivers. viti levu highlanders caught these in community efforts with large nets, using stone sinkers, and divers to guide the net and
the fish. these stone sinkers (vatu-kata-i-lawa) were the only stone implements ever used by highlanders.
n. sailfish , long-beaked with a huge dorsal fin, the usually migratory istiophorus sp., rarely if
caught by early fijians but now available as people now fish outside the reefs. the flesh is not preferred, partly because of the frequently found holes in the flesh caused by parasitical worms.
darkish coloured, sailfish skin sparkles with colour and glistening silver when the fish is excited. they travel in small groups but can come together in large groups, male and female together,

toa . (or) ikatotoa (or) tokalou lion fish, butterfly fish, lactoria cornuta, formerly listed as pterois volitans. beautiful, floating fins with very long dorsal and pectoral fins equipped with poisonous spines, unfrightened of visitors, confident in its armament. ika toa . box fish, square in cross-section, very tough body and skin but with a delicious, tender slab of meat on its back that resembles a chicken breast.
(or) iike n. wooden pounder to beat bark-cloth.
a dance motion, to turn sharply the body to face left or right. ta iki turned in this way (here the
suggests a cutting motion).
you (singular, as obj ect). vukei iko help you. au na qai solia vei iko. i will then give it to you. ocei? o iko (or) ko iko. who? you.

n. mirror, glass. mata iloilo spectacles, glasses. vaka-rai-ta-iloilo n. imagination. vaka-rai-tailoilo-taka v. to imagine it. the only kind of mirror known in fiji was a reflection in clear pool of water. such a mirror gives rise to the name of ratu sir joseva iloilo (he told me) from his mother ’s use of such a natural mirror on taveuni.

v. look at, through something transparent (glasses, diving goggles, translucent or reflective like a mirror). by ext. have an x-ray image taken, usually of some part of the human body. see tirova. also see irova v. to peep. inisua, inisuataka (eng.) v. to insure (in a commercial sense).
yes. traditionally, fij ians answered questions with strict logic, as in “aren ’t you going to town?”
with a “yes”, meaning “yes, i am not going to town .” today usage is confusing. only
village fij ians can be relied upon to retain the correct fij ian logic. often, instead of
a verbal answer “yes”, fij ians will raise their brow slightly (deguvacu), or they may simply
agreement. instead of saying “no” in declining a request, a fijian may remain silent. in effect, a silent response means “no”. it might be considered impolite to say “no”. a negative
may be indicated by a slight sideways movement of the head. vaka-io v. to say “yes”, to approve, to agree. syn. (tonga) ’io.
(eng.) ink.
pronoun: them (many). o ira kece all of them. ira na tamata the people. idiom: ira vata they are all the same.
them (few).

n. fan. iri ni buka fan for fanning fire. iri livaliva (or) iri ni cagi electric fan . iri batabata air conditioner. iri buli hand-held traditional fan of woven pandanus leaf, notably from daku, tailevu.
ni meke hand-held fans used in exhibition dances meke. l iga i iri were warriors who carried a

fan in battle confrontations as an indication of fearlessness and display of confidence. (ligairi has also become a distinguished family name from village nabalebale, wailevu, vanua levu.) iri, iriva, irivaka v. mo irivi au mada please fan me. me irivi na kakana. fan the food (usually to disperse flies). irivaka na buka fan the fire. dau ni iri trad. person who fans the chief. iro, irova v. to peer, peep, take a look at (or) vakairoiro to keep peering, usually quietly, even secretly .

"peeping tom", syn. tokalulu, (macuata) va ’alalagi. isa! (or) isalei! cry of regret, sorrow. isalei is the name of fij i's popular song of farewell. that melody and original words were actually tongan and not at all ancient but has become an icon of fijian culture with words adapted into a fij ian context. i’saka! formal form of address, used at the beginning of a letter, respectfully to draw the attention of the reader. the equiv. of “dear sir” or “dear madame”. may also be used in speech, similarly, respectfully to draw the attention of a listener. saka sir (or) madam.

(eng.) n. yeast. early fijians had no leavened bakery products and no baking flour. isi, isia n. tear off, as of twig, flower, piece of bread, newspaper, piece of cloth, to split pandanus leaf for weaving.
eng. israel. this is also used as a man ’s name sireli.
n., adj . east. colo isiti colo east, a former province in the eastern highlands of viti levu island. there is a very proud tradition to this area and its people.
n. very near miss, as with something thrown. syn. oisou.
(archaic, eng.) agent, commercial agent.
. n. polynesian chestnut, inocarpus edulis (or) i. fagiferus, caesalpinaceae. the fruit is a cooked, nutty
eaten in some areas, notably on beqa island, and sold at the public markets. tiny white fragrant flowers, fruits heavily around april, may, june, nuts eaten boiled, grilled, or made into a form
after grating. the heavily buttressed tree grows rapidly in damp areas and can reach giant size. the thin buttresses formerly served as an improvised drum for communicating at a distance. ivi

grated ivi. mainly a coastal tree, widely known, often by similar names, throughout the south pacific. there are many different varieties. excellent firewood. various puddings of ivi include sikovoro, koko, soloi, bila. tender leaves are also edible. syn. (polyn.) if i, ihi, i ’i. idiom: vakaruku ni ivi. shelter under an ivi tree, i.e., having sheltered where the rain leaks through. ivi . n . kidney. ivi qaqa. padlock. the letter j does not occur in mainland fij ian speech except in adaptions of english words, or in words
and kadavu where tongan influence is strong. it often replaces the standard letter
as in ij itoko for ititoko, walking stick. in a person ’s name such as jemesa, for james, the intitial j may

way to an s as in semesa. the letter j appears in some speech of the navosa highlands that were penetrated by early tongans; the tongan ‘ikai for no or not becomes j ikai. . . . j a single letter, and thus a sound, appended to any or all fijian words or names by youngsters
to carry on a strange, childish language that they think is cute. it can be difficult to understand their speech. it is even harder to speak it. one might presume this silly fad will pass.
n. (eng.) “jumper”, as in isulu and j aba, formal cotton dress of fijian women. the isulu extends
ankles. the j aba is a sort of bodice on upper body, from the neck down to the thighs, or to the knees, or further down, outside the sulu. this form of dress was imposed by missionaries.
(eng.) champion, usually in sports.
n., adj . immigrants from tonga, specialised boat-builders who settled mostly at fulaga. they built the famous drua named ratu finau, its hull (kata) . meters long, -.

as in lotu jaj i (or) lotu tiati anglican church , church of england. jaj i is a fijian rendition of “george” though there are various spellings of that name. many colonial officials were anglicans and
. jaji, jajitaka (eng.) v. to charge (battery) or charge some expenditure to an account.
(eng.) j acket.
n. (lau) charles. syn. salesi.
(eng.) germany. kaijamani german person or people.
(eng.) chairman. syn. j iemeni, j emeni.
(eng.) january.
. (eng.) cheque. u .s. check, for transfer of funds.
. (eng.) “jack” in the royal suite of playing cards. j oka joker.
(eng.) general (military). metia jenereli major general, usually referring to sitiveni rabuka who arranged to be given this title after his military coup in .
(bible) jerusalem. idiom: tekivu mai jerusalemi, . . begin at home before worrying about other places. this has been an excuse for nepotism.
(kadavu) local chiefly title that precedes a place name such as ji wailevu. jia, jiataka (eng) v. to cheer, to cheer for . . . j iataka na timi to cheer for the team.
n. (eng. “china”) banana, formerly classified as musa chinensis. banana may be distinguished
susceptible to disease than is plantain. early native immigrants brought several varieties of
but no bananas which are much sweeter and do not require cooking. the species has tiny,
seeds. propagation is only vegetative, by suckers, and movement is only by man. plant are variable in phenotype, being genetically very motile. syn. j aina. see tiaina for more details.
(or) jaina china, or chinese person(s).
(eng.) gardenia, “charley” (= tiale), the national flower of tahiti, gardenia taitensis, native to

but aboriginal introduction to polynesia. a now more common species is g. augusta (formerly g. j asminoides), introduced from the orient. there are eight other gardenia species, including g. vitiensis as named by seemann.
(eng.) chairman. vukevuke j iemani assistant chairman. syn. j ameni.
(western highlands, navosa, from tonga) no, not. syn. hikai, sega, warai, wara, mino. (eastern macuata) maka, (western macuata) maqa. these variations are all familiar to most fijians.
(or) tili (tonga) n. hand-net thrown from the shoulder to catch small schooling fish close to shore with the man standing in shallow water. this is polynesian custom, not fij ian .
(eng) n. cheese.
(bible) jesus.
(lau) n. walking stick (= ititoko ), sometimes used to refer to one final bowl of kava, “one for the road”, before departure of a guest.
(eng.) july. syn. julai.
(eng.) june. syn. june.
. (eng.) “joker” in a deck of playing cards.
. (eng. joker) person who is showing off, acting important, powerful.
(slang) v., adj . to act in a manner of exaggerated self-importance, aggression or power, as in swaggering, “collar up” as is said in fijian english.
(eng.) n. chalk ; also jug. j oke ni wai water-jug.
(eng.) n. chocolate.

source_text: some words may begin with either k or q
target_text: such as kasivi, qasivi, depending on regional dialect. the k
to be used by "true" fijians of viti levu, while the q is more common among the island people of lau, kadavu or vanualevu-icake or vanualevu-ira, where there is a substantial tongan influence.

(go). but when an introduced foreign word has a k sound, the k sound is usually retained. in bua, the k is often replaced by an h. the fruit (morinda citrifolia) kura becomes hura. in parts of vanua levu,

source_text: k may be omitted at the beginning of
target_text: a word. in fiji as well as many other pacific languages, it is vowels rather than consonants that serve to anchor the meaning of words.
. and, a conjunction joining verb-forms. raica ka rogoca see it and hear it. ka . that, as in na ilavo ka sa kumuni the money that was collected.

. n. thing. na ka oqo this thing; na ka oya that thing. na ka levu (locally na kwa levu) lit. “the big one” high chief of the coastal region of nadroga province. ena veika kece in all things. m inisita

minister for fijian affairs idiom: sa dua na ka! that’s really something ! (remarkable). ka lo secret. idiom: ka ni tagane or ka vakatagane n. male genitals, a polite term. idiom: ka ni yalewa n. female genitals, a polite term.
. prefix to a numeral, indicating "nth " as in a sequence: na ikatolu the third. ikaciwa the ninth.

? raises the question as to which ranking. kadua usually means "other " as is na yasana kadua the other side. taura na kadua take the other one. na ikarua the second (after the first), but karua refers to a certain family relative of same sex.

. prefix of adj ective or past participle indicating force, strong action. kasura smashed. kabasu broken. ka! . (slang, affectionate) hey you ! that greeting is sometimes associated with male homosexuals. ko

or ka oya. "what's-his-name ". ka oya can also mean “that one”. kaba, kabata, kabataka . v. climb up. kabata na vunikau climb the tree. kabataka na itukituki climb up with the hammer. may also refer to climbing a hill. idiom: ivakaba ni sau dramatic act to assert a demand for rightful title to some authority, such as chiefly position, lit. a means of climbing to power. idiom: kabawaqa v., n. girls of easy morals who board ships (waqa) in harbour, often accepting money for their services. this is a common insult, equiv. of saqamua fornicator, prostitute.

(vulgar slang): kaba to have sexual intercourse, though for animals this is not a vulgar word. this is the normal way of referring to a male animal mounting a female. ikabakaba n. ladder, steps, staircase. ikabakaba ni sere (or) ikabakaba sof a musical scale, staff notation in music. idiom: ikabakaba vou new habit, new skill, new way of doing things. kaba, kaba, kabata . v. to attack, fight. kabata na koro or kabakoro v. to attack the village.
n. conquest (in war). kabani . (eng.) n. commercial company, corporation, military company. kabani . (eng.) n. darling, partner, good friend, companion.

(eng.) n. compass. fijians had no compass and no concept of regularly spaced directions like nesw. their directions were the directions of the various winds of fiji. fij ians have adapted readily to the european compass directions mata ni kabasi. the term kabasi applies also to a compass as used
meant only downwind, which is in a westerly direction. the common tradewind comes
southern hemisphere and from the northeast in the northern hemisphere of the
ocean, with the doldrums in between . noca isi northeast. noca wesi northwest. and so on.

is, however, fijian sailors now most often simply use the english word for compass directions without modifying the pronounciation. kabasu v. to burst, bust (box, door kicked in, clothing from stress, book with broken binding), broken. see basu, basuka v. to break.

n. sea bream, edible reef fish, thumbprint emperor, lethrinus harak, resembles the snapper sabutu, whitish body, reddish lips, tends to fight the fishing line. the body adopts the camouflage colour of the background adapting to the immediate background in the area nearest the eyes, according to the late rob wright.

n. a type of strong string for tying things. a thin string is sliced from the top of the midrib of a coconut-palm leaf. this is often used to sew up a sack after it is filled with copra. kabe, kabea (archaic) v. to flourish and threaten with a raised weapon, club or spear.
v. of a person or people, speak badly of them, spreading bad stories. veivakabekabei n. the action of doing this.
adj . bent out of shape (corrugated iron, basket). syn. (lau) kap elu.
adj . chipped (plate, tooth , blade of axe or knife). kabi, kabita v. to cling onto, adhere onto, to stick. kabikabi sticky (can apply to a farmer's soil).
stick it to the wall. na itavuteke sega ni kabi the non-stick frying pan. idiom: wai ni diva, sega ni kabita. tears of longing for what can never be.

v. to bring alongside, or dock (as of a boat), usually at a wharf. ikabi n. (archaic) wooden club formerly used to knock down, burn, and clear away bush before planting crops. stone axes did not exist in the highlands among the very early indigenous fijians who immigrated from vanuatu or the solomon islands.

adj . dented, bent out of shape (car in accident, kitchen pot). may refer to sheets of corrugated iron. see kabelu. kabo, kabota v. to take hold of something hot with the hand(s) protected from the heat by leaves, a cloth, gloves, that protection being called ikakabo.

n. edible saltwater fish , saluridae sp. catfish. plotosidae, usually plotusus arab . sharp serrated spine in each pectoral fin and in dorsal fin. young, they stay in schools of a few hundred, often staying burrowed in mud or sand in shallow water, a danger to waders, the pain of a sting lasting several hours.
. n. yellow-breasted musk parrot of viti levu, prospeia personata. it cannot be taught to speak
at all. flies about in the morning and afternoon. swooping, jerky flight. sometimes in pairs.
to feed around cassava patches. often a friendly bird, even loving, especially the female. syn. kaka. kabote . v. to burst. sa kabote na vaivo. the pipe burst. see bote, botea.
n. morning mist, fog. kabukabu (or) kabukabua heavy fog, misty (weather), fogged over, covered

(as a mountain might be). kabu, kabuya, kaburaka v. to scatter (seeds), sprinkle (water). kabuacara, kabuacarataka v. to put or keep in careless disorder one’s personal possessions, tools, equipment, supplies, scattered about.
limited visibility, usually due to weather conditions and distance. syn. kobua see buawa.
v. to seep out, as liquid from a package, as happens sometimes to leaf-parcels of food cooked in an earth-oven. bura, buraca to ooze.
. v. to scatter (as in broadcasting seeds) forcefully.
. v. to broadcast. vale ni kakaburaki broadcasting house.
(or) kabuacara v. to spread out at random, scattered here, there and everywhere, spread out,

source_text: scattered about in careless or sloppy manner
target_text: (clothes, shoes in a room, tools in a workshop etc.). syn. kabuacara.
v. to sprinkle, usually something like a powder, or ashes. ashes may be used in treatment of hair
adj . cracked, split (mirror, stone, skin, leather, wooden or cardboard box). vakaca v. to crack it.
(anglicism) break of dawn .

split open (coconut, breadfruit, bamboo). kacabote v. to explode, burst, detonate. vakacabote-taka v. to explode deliberately. idiom: veitalia na kacabote! no matter what the consequences! let’s just do it ! (a saying attributed to the frog ra boto who puffs up his chest in a story for children).
v. to burst (of a boil, or a fallen fruit). syn. kasabura. see bura.

. n. small, pelagic, non-migratory bird, quite common , collared petrel, or white-throated shearwater, pterodroma leucoptera brevipes. feeds largely on squid. grey upperparts, grey breast but white underneath . syn. (lau , all petrels) laf u. (kadavu) lagio.
. n. macgillivray ’s petrel, pterodroma macgillivrayi. in the south pacific there are some five
of that genus, some of them quite widespread. but this one is known only at gau. it was discovered by t. m . raynor, medical officer of the h .m.s. herald, in october, . he named it for
about the nesting habits, probably with the help of new zealand’s sniffing dogs. all this is
important in terms of biodiversity. even the district council has been persuaded to take an interest.

v. to crack with sharp sound. syn. kavida, heard as avida in major parts of vanua levu. kaci, kaciva v. to call using some form of address (attracting someone’s attention), invite (person, animal). but kaci may refer to a village headman calling out some announcement in the village. idiom: (vulgar) o kacivi ga, o sa vude cake. when alerted, the penis rises to the occasion. lit. when you are called, you rise to the occasion.
v. to call out to someone from a distance without concern for disturbance to people in between.
n. large edible fish, long-nosed emperor, lethrinella xanthocheila, reddish belly (as implied in
(or) ikacivi n. name or title by which a person is addressed, the name they are called when
to them, or the name used in referring to them. traditionally this has almost never been the
name, which was considered impolite. a man whose name is seru, and who has a
called manasa may be addressed as tama i manasa, and referred to as such. similarly, formerly,
often referred to a place indirectly by some reference other than its proper name. these words may apply to a group of people, the name by which one refers to them.
idiom: to die far from home, usually overseas, as an example of fijian indirect manner of speech. kacimuri, kacimuria v. to call after (someone).
v. to announce, to call out publicly, as done by village administrator turaga ni koro, in making announcements. kacivaka yani vei koya announce it to him, shout it out to him. kacivaka na
announce the marriage. kada, kadava v. (lau, vanua levu) to run, run for it (bau : cici, ciciva). kada vakina run with it. ada, adava could be heard in vanua levu.
n. reed or other support for food-crop cultivated vines, yams. me vakada na uvi put up the yamvine support.
n., adj . medium stage of maturity of coconut when there is flesh and refreshing liquid. syn. drokai.
n. aggressive black biting ant, odontomachus sp., that nests around rotting vegetation. kadi vuka

ant. batikadi formerly, a potentially dangerous lone wild person living in the bush, now guerilla fighter, commando, resistance fighter (world war ii), bandit. idiom: vakaseuta na bure ni kadi lit., scratch into an ant ’s nest, i.e., inadvertantly stir up trouble.
adj . old but still edible, of yams, or overly mature sweet potato that may be split.

. n. river prawn , also found in brackish water, macrobrachium equideus. the “true prawn” ura dina is m. lar, in freshwater, the totem of some tribes. m . rosenbergii is the introduced malaysian freshwater prawn with no special fijian name.
. spying gossip .
(med.) “pins and needles” sensation, prickly feeling.
adj . changed to bright red, of cooked prawns, crab, dyed clothes, a healing wound.
adj . chipped, cracked, usually of something like crockery. see dirika.
forced open (door, box). see dola to open.
broken off with force (branch, banana from stem, pencil broken in two). see doloka .
. (eng.) n. candle.
. (eng.) n. roman candle tree, candelabra plant, cassia alata, a common, introduced garden

with yellow, candle-like flowers. juice from the macerated leaves are used medicinally , applied to ringworm. kadrala . (eng.) n. cassava root when it has the undesirable eating characteristics of a hard, waxy texture and heavy core-fibres that resemble a candle wick. kadre, kadre v. to sprout up. modernly , the word may be used figuratively, as with ideas, thoughts.
n. vegetative shoot or sprout. sa kadre mai na soredra. their seeds are sprouting out. vula i kadrekadre. sprouting season (yams).

torn, of something still hanging there. see dresu, dresuka. kadru, kadruva, kadruma, kadruta v. to scratch, usually with the nails, or forcefully, a cat with claws. - ma, -ta both imply scratching with force. wa kadrukadru barbed wire. sa kadruvi au na vusi. the
scratched me. kadruva na dakuqu. scratch my back (to relieve itch). e dua na ikadru n. a scratch , or a scraper. see kaku, kakuva.
n. univalve shellfish, considered a type of sici. it thrives in brackish , tidal water. it is prickly, hence the name.
other. ena yasana kadua. on the other side.

first, as the first in some sport, first among things that are counted, as in first century, or reference to a king or queen, as in ilisap eci i elizabeth i. see imatai. see also isevu which implies the very first time something has occured. from ikadua, there follows na ikarua, the second, na ikatolu, the third, et cetera.
. native, countryman, (familiar term, with place-name added). kaiviti fijian (as a familiar term,
polite in formal conversation). kaicolo highland people (of viti levu). kai vata fellow countryman. kaivalagi european. kaiidia indian. kai jiaina chinese. kai mereke american,
foreigner. kaiwai or kaimua seaman, sailor. kai veikau bush person. dui kaikai different
(usually different races, ethnic groups, or nationalities). ko ira na dui kaikai people of

(various) origins. kaivata fellow countryman, person of the same territory (sometimes abbrev. as kai). kainoqu my fellow countryman. kainona his countryman . kai . n. score, goal(s) or point(s) in a sport or game. na kedratou kai their score. rawata e dua na kai.
a point, make a score, goal. e vica na kai? what is the score? e qaqa tiko o suva ena lima na kai. suva is winning by five points.

. as a prefix before the name of certain traditional fij ian territories, indicates a member of that particular kin-group, tribe or set of tribes. they are the original people of the territory. not all fij ians
n. bivalve shellfish, mussel, clam, a general term for several genera and species. commonly sold in

is the freshwater mussel from the wailevu (rewa river), batissa violaceae, much of that from around village kasavu, and some also from verata territory. canu kai, canuma na kai pick up, gather kai. qe, qeva na kai dig kai out with the hands. sili kai, silima na kai to wade (even neck deep) for kai. the small bamboo basket used for collection in the wailevu is referred to as ikata; it allows water to flow freely through it but retains the mussels. butu kai v . to feel for kai with the feet. gege na kai v. to open the kai. vali, valia na kai v. to separate the kai from the shell. ciciga na lewena v. to prise

the flesh. sa siki na kai. the kai is full and fat, seasonally good. vadololo soak in water to remove sand. syn. (west) tave. idiom: butu kai dance, usually the taralala, of european origin in fiji but now tradition of fijians.
holds each other side by side with movement resembling the shuffling movement of women feeling for mussels with their feet as they tread in the rivers.
n. highlander of viti levu of melanesian origin (vanuatu and solomon islands) with a
of being proud, feisty, independently minded, with no aristocratic pretentions. viti levu
the only original highlanders in fiji, though some have dispersed to other locations. quite different, muscular physique and culture compared to lowlanders and fijians of the smaller islands

there has been an infusion of polynesian stock . main centres were the early provinces colo east, colo north, colo west, later incorporated as part of larger provinces, ba, ra, naitasiri, etc., for the central administration to keep control of them. syn. (insulting) siromai. kaicolo-taka v. to do something ineptly, to mess it up, to be clumsy about something. this is an impolite
to highlanders kaicolo being simpletons, inexperienced in what is thought to be more evolved ways of coastal fij ian.
adj . (slang) ungiving, stingy, as a clam like a stone (vatu) that cannot open.
n. ponyfish, laeognathidae nathidae, relatively small edible fish found close to shore. very often

these days with small hook and line by urban, spare-time fisherfolk. syn. cebe. in cicia and lakeba, according to geraghty, the tongan name is used j ap aj ap a. kaikai may refer to more than one species, including caranx spp.
(or) kaikaiya adj ., n.,v . fatigue, tired from exertion, lifting something excessively heavy.

koso n. saltwater surf clam, ark shell, andara cornea, the shell ridged and white with serrated edge. eaten raw or cooked, rich in iron. sold in the market this is a dangerous food. when stale and rotten it
smell, yet becomes quite poisonous, even causing death. burglars use it to poison dogs to facilitate breaking and entering. syn. (nadro., macuata) qeqe.

kuku n. bivalve shellfish, mussel, mytilidae, generally modiola tulipa a specialty of the lower rewa river, supplying the suva market. the shell is often used to split pandanus leaves preparatory to matweaving. kuku is a place-name, and a name of a people in southeastern viti levu island. kaila, kailavaka v. to shout out loud, to yell. kailavaka yani vei koya. call out to him/her. kailavaki koya! yell at him/her ! kaikaila v. to shout loudly, as of a crowd. na ikaikaila the shouting. e levu

ikaikaila ena vale ni kuro. there is a lot of shouting in the kitchen. kaila! is the name of a children ’s weekly newspaper published by the fiji times. kaile n. high-climbing, semi-cultivated or wild edible yam, dioscorea pentaphylla, with five leaves, thick

stems very prickly in lowest internodes, twining to the left, counterclockwise. aboriginal introduction. three basic varieties, eaten usually when there is a lack of other food, though for eastern highlanders in viti levu, this was a staple food. syn. bulou, tokatolu. (colo east) koile.
kubu or kaile dina n. “true” (dina) kaile, the tastiest variety, smooth skin, rather like a potato in texture. eating quality depends on exact stage of harvest.

mila or kaile gaga or kaile dranu n. wild, high-climbing aerial yam, d. bulbifera. only the large hairy underground tuber is eaten, not the more poisonous small round tubers that grow off aerial roots.
have a reddish tinge. they twine to the left, counterclockwise (as does true kaile but not the

yam uvi or the wild yams tivoli, tikau). the tuber is bitter and poisonous until cooked thoroughly, grated finely and washed in several changes of running water. this makes a bland starch food with the texture of very soft mashed potato. fij ians may add strip s of the boiled seeds icibi, from the vine walai, entada phaseoloides, which adds a nutty taste. some highlanders kaicolo of colo east
to this as revereve, with first fruits isevu offered to the chief around april. traditionally eastern highlanders rarely cultivated yams; their main starch food was cultivated taro or wild yams.
n. tubers of this var. of wild yam have heavy fibres that are spit out after chewing. kainaka v. (rewa) to tell.
v. said, from kaya to say. e kainaki vei iko. it has (already) been said to you. e kainaki vakavica
iko ? how many times has it been said to you? sa kainaki . . . it is said . . . , often beginning a sentence. e kainaki ni sa yali. it is said that it is lost.
or kainakoro n. (slang) simple village person unfamiliar with town life and the ways of modern urban living. koro n. village.

(slang.) n. town person, unfamiliar with traditional village ways. there is an implication of acting “smart” or “uppity” but lacking proper courtesy and village manners. tauni (eng.) town. syn. kai-nasiti. siti city. syn. susu madrai. lit. raised on (european) bread.
n. coconut scraper for making coconut cream. syn. kari ni niu.
. n. low-class commoner, one who is ill-mannered. this is a common and rather serious insult. the
si here refers to human semen, as if kaisi were the result of casual copulation. itovo vakaisi

vulgar behaviour. tabu kaisi n. finely woven mat from ono-i-lau, “forbidden to lowerclass people”. syn. (kadavu) qala. (vanua levu) aisi. kaisi . v. torn, split, from isi, isia to split, of cloth or wood.
n. white person, “european”, as they are called in local english. it would be more polite to say
ni valagi. by ext., certain playing cards are referred to as kaivalagi, those of the royal suite,
(turaga), queen (marama), j ack (j eke). kaivale n. a certain clan or extended family may be traditionally intimate with the chiefly family, virtually
chiefly household, but in a subservient capacity. such a kin-group is referred to as kaivale.
house.
n, sailor, seaman . kaimua crew member of a boat or ship. idiom: kana vakaiwai v. to eat as a sailor does, mostly protein with very little starch-food.
n. a large parrot, from the sound of its squawk. prospeia spp. the yellow-breasted musk parrot (mainly on viti levu, and does not learn to speak) and red-breasted musk parrot, widespread on the

island and can learn to speak. both can learn to be friendly. often fly at dawn or dusk , frequently in couples. call and either bird may answer. they like to feed at cassava patches and on the seeds of mokosoi trees. syn. koki. (west) rove. kaka, kakavaka v. to stammer, to stutter.
n. a small bird, white rumped swift, collocalia spodiopygia. swoops with jerky flight. nests in caves, rarely if ever seen to land.

adj . split, cracked (eggs), smashed into many part (bottles). sa kakaca tu na mata ni dau veivacu. the boxer's face is all cut up. sa kakaca tu na yaloka kece. all the eggs are cracked. dry earth may be kakaca. see kaca.
bloodshot, infected (of eyes), probably conjunctivitis.
v. stride with fast long steps. see kalawa.
n. short piece of wood across a drain or ditch to step on in crossing. syn. ikawakawa though
much larger crossing.
n. food. idiom: kakana dina "real food", i.e., a traditional prestigious root crop such as taro, yam. meat, fish, or anything accompanying it would be considered only secondarily, as garnish icoi.
is the main element of a meal. kakana droka uncooked food. kakana buta cooked food. kakana draudrau leafy green vegetables. vaka ta-kakana n., v. picnic. see kana, kania to eat.
v. feed itself (people, animals, fish). kaka-ni-oro n., v. adj . ticklish, bothersome (can ’t get it off one ’s mind). e kakanioro vei au ni kadruvi na
my feet are ticklish. e kakanioro vei au ni ra dau vosavosa na gone. it is bothersome to me when the children keep chattering. syn. sikisikinea .
v. to hock, as in bringing out something stuck in the throat. kakase n., v. to gossip. this is an often mentioned characteristic.
split badly in many places (mats, clothes, paper).
v. to look forward to something.
snapped, chipped (plate, cup) in many places, branch of a tree.
dry, flaking off, peeling off, of human skin. sa kakavo na kulina ena kati ni siga. his/her skin is flaking off from sunburn.
broken in many places (glass, the heart). sa kakavorovoro na utoqu mai loma my heart
all broken up inside (words of a popular song in fiji). such a romantic notion for the heart is an anglicism. for fij ians, the heart was never a centre of emotion.
crumbled away in many places (biscuits, cake, bread, bamboo).
n. sea perch, lutj anus russelli, russell ’s snapper, the grunt, fish found at reef and mangrove areas,

used fishing lines with hooks. this fish has silvery colouring with five or six yellow stripes longitudinally, black spot on either side near the tail. similar lutj anus spp. include damu, bati, tanabe.
(eng.) n., adj . khaki.

(eng.) cargo. kaku, kakuva . v. to seize forcefully in the hand(s), to grab a hold of. kaku, kakuva . v. to scratch. syn. kadru, kadruva . kakua! don ’t ! as a forceful expression. syn. kua (though usually less forcefully, depending on the tone or emphasis of speech).
n. red-breasted musk parrot, prospeia tabuensis, on all larger fiji islands except ovalau. syn. kaka, koki, ka kula. readily learns to speak . various subspecies.
. (eng.) n. colour. syn. roka-na. fijians had not developed the concept of ab stract colours of a spectrum. words for colours depended on the obj ects described. fij ians now tend to follow the

system. kalavata refers to clothes of the same colour, as for school uniforms, or a choir or church group that decides to dress in the same colour and type of clothes. kala . v. to lean over, be tilted. kala yani vua lean on her/him. vakalakala leaning slightly. vakalakalataka lean it over slightly. veikalayaki to sway back and forth . matanivola kala italics, lit. “leaning letters”, one of those new expressions invented by teachers of language. sa kala na siga. it is
(the sun is leaning low). caution: in vanua levu kala may refer to male sexual organs, qala-na in standard fijian. idiom: sa kala na matanisiga. he/she is getting old (their sun is setting).

adj . slanting rather than staying straight up, as of a house, a tree. kalabuci n. a well known shrub, ornamental and medicinal, usually growing at low altitude, wild or semicultivated, acalypha insulana, euphorbiaceae, red flowers in a cat-tail, large round leaves. this is a
at nalawa in ra, symbolic of their human genitals; the name of the plant is not to be pronounced
fern spp. that is open under the hot sun, closes as the sun declines, as implied in the fij ian name.
(eng.) n. clutch, as in an automobile.
walk about or work under the hot sun.
bowed, as with age or infirmity (people).
bowed in posture, from respect.

(eng.) to classify, to arrange in classes or groups, or by qualities. kalavo . (eng.) social club, night club.

small rats. mice were inadvertently introduced and are now sometimes called mausi.

a long tail (longer then the head and body), and is an agile climber of trees, capable
