have caused serious depradation of birds that nest on the ground, including the aboriginally introduced jungle fowl. (i am indebted to paddy ryan for most of these notes.) kalavo . n. (slang) prostitute. kalawa, kalawaca v. to step, step over. kalawaca na ikelikeli step over the ditch. e kalawa ga vakavica . he took just a few step s. syn. lakawa. by ext. kalawaca to omit, to skip, or to pass over, improperly but perhaps inadvertantly, some item or some person(s).
n. step, as in walking, used sometimes as a crude measure of length.

broken, hanging down (branch of tree). kalevu or kwalevu n. chiefly title at the coast of nadroga. with some degree of presumption, this title is now considered by the national administration to be paramount in nadroga province.

n. (archaic) neck-rest, traditional artefact of carved wood or bamboo, to support the head while sleeping. it also protected a man ’s coiffure, an important feature of vanity. now carved and sold only
tourist souvenir. though no longer used, the neck-rest is comfortable to one accustomed to it. indigenous fijians used no soft pillows; that was a european and tongan innovation.

ni qio n. a beautiful, very common bright blue type of starfish, quite useless, “shark ’s pillow”, linckia laevigata. syn. ilokoloko ni qio. kali, kalia, kaliraka v. to separate forcefully, to split something, as in the hand. to tear off by hand, as a page from a newspaper. kaliraka to grasp away, snatch away, as in kaliraka o nadi na icovi ni rakavi.
(from suva) the rugby prize.

separated, of a married couple. keirau sa veikalikali dede. we () have ben separated a long time. kali v. to wean (a child or young animal). ikali ni gone n. ceremony celebrating weaning of a child, a time
when husband and wife may resume sexual intercourse. this delay of time between births of children is traditional, preceding christianity.
n. of banana or plantain, the lower hands on the bunch, thought to be of less good quality and size compared to the upper hands of the fruit. see veta-i-cake.
. n. edible double-headed parrot fish, greyish light brown in colour, large scales, bolbometopon muricatus, nibbles at the coral, schools at night.
. n (archaic, syn. drua, now the more common name). a huge obsolete type of sea-going canoe
mainly by tongans in fiji in the last quarter of the s. the ship had great carrying
and could beat to windward. it was a major factor in the conquest and trade that brought
influence to dominate and integrate in fij i. the timber was fij ian vesi (instia bijuga) which
abundant at kabara and in parts of cakaudrove. with its outrigger, the kalia hull was partly a
concept. the bow-shape, mast and sail-plan owe more to micronesian technique, with stern and bow interchangeable to facilitate tacking. two famous samoan builders in fij i, lemaki
n. (eng.) calico, but in fiji, the term covers several sorts of cotton fabric.
fifth (in sequence). lima five. lima is a proto-polynesian word for “hand”.
n. secret.
(colo, nait., namosi) to bring water (bauan taki). see talo.
dented (car), mis-shapen by being bent, folded over (piping, timber), slumped down (person). see lobi, lobia, lobika.

n. star. no distinction was made among stars, planets, comets. idiom: raica na kalokalo mataidua. (anglicism) knocked silly, knocked out, "seeing stars", severely stunned. matakalokalo n. constellation of stars. only polynesian navigators had a knowledge of the stars. that knowledge is now mostly forgotten . they were aware that stars maintain a constant
(celestial latitude) and knew what islands were to be found under which major star’s declination. the star sirius, for example, signals the latitude of fij ian islands.
(eng.) clock, o’clock. e vica na kaloko ? what time is it? e lima na koloko. five o’clock.
na lima half past five. sa vo tini na miniti me lima . ten minutes to five. kaloko ni liga wrist-watch. kaloko ni vakayadra alarm clock.
bent or leaning to one side, as a growing plant might be.

(eng.) n. cologne, after-shave lotion. kalou n. spirit, god, many in form and nature, always to be feared. they are everywhere. a fij ian would hardly dare stay alone in the forest at night. certain places may be especially fearful. syn. (west) nitu.
n. god, a word adapted by methodist missionaries for their christian god and then used also by

catholics and later denominations. earlier, kalou meant “ghost” or “spirit”, in some cases tribal gods who might be protective, as in kalou vu. these days one tends to refer to spirits as tevoro, a word of tongan origin, meaning devils, a concept that did not previously exist in fiji. devils are very
to many fijians. the ancient fijian kalou might be powerful and sometimes dangerous but they were not perforce evil and they were certainly not satanic.
unfortunate(ly), unlucky.
. adj . happy, lucky, blessed. the word seems to refer to the supreme snake-god degei who

a benign or indifferent creature, certainly not threatening. (kalou spirit, gata snake.) modernism: mo kalougata tiko! be happy ! see degei, legendary immigrant chief, later a sacred spirit. kalou-gata . n. good fortune, happiness, blessings.
. n. hookworm, or also pinworm that may cause itchiness at the anus when it itches at night. pinworms emerge at night to lay eggs at the anus. local people are often accustomed to the
do not feel any irritation. usual medication is mebendazole pills available in fiji without prescription.
. n. larvae of mosquitos that wriggle about in water. they feed on tiny particles of organic
(such as decaying leaves), moult three times, and then transform to pupae at the fourth moult. pupae look like black commas. they split and release a fully formed mosquito within three days.
vu n. a spirit-god of some social group (tribe, yavusa or clan, mataqali), not usually a human
leader (and thus differing from the vu, an originating ancestral person, often later considered
(often a snake, pig, dog, shark) or reside unseen within some obj ect such as
clan within the tribe and there was often a temple bure-kalou for that purpose. there
some temples counted at bau island in . the founding ancestral spirit vu is is sometimes shared between two peoples who later became divided. they are then said to be related as vietauvu to
other. this allows permissive joking and privileges they make take with each other. similar relations may have resulted from an ancient chiefly marriage between two groups.
bent (as of a nail). love, loveca v. to bend. kalu, kaluva v. to whistle, whistle at. kalukaluva (or) va-kalukaluva to whistle at (person, people, dog)

n. whistle. formerly carried by some chiefs in the western highlands of viti levu, attached to a cord around the neck. no certainty as to the function of those whistles. kama, kamaca n., v. to fire, burn, scorch (may refer to sunburn). wai kama hot spring, hot acid (sulphuric, hydrochloric). kama bula wild fire, hot fire, still burning, spreading. kama bulabula burn alive. kama mate burned to death. kama yavu burned to the ground. vosa ni vakamakama inflammatory words, speech. vakama, vakamaca v. to set fire, burn it. vakama tamata cremate. e
au na sitovu. the stove burned me. idiom: kama na veigasau refers to the incredible rapidity with which rumours or surprising news travels about on “coconut wireless”.
v. to dry (clothes), usually by hanging. see mamaca dry.
adj . badly tangled (rope, fishing line). medre tangled.

(or) kamica adj . good tasting, sweet, flavourful, nicely salted (food), pleasant (speech, manners, appearance). wai ni gunu kamica soft drink s. vakamikamica-taka v. to sweeten (something to be consumed), to make it more tasty .
n. traditional fijian riches of ceremonial presentation offerings, especially whale teeth, but
and barkcloth. this word is used mostly by people formally accepting such offerings, speaking of them in a complimentary manner.
cut, broken, rather forcefully. see musu, musuka to break off or cut in two. kana, kania v. to eat, to eat it. mai kana! come, eat ! when eating it is customary, virtually imperative,

vinaka. it tastes good. na kanavalavala n. the part of the human head on each side of the temple, the part that moves when one eats. vakania na manumanu v. to feed the animals. idiom: kana bui ni vuaka. lit., eat pig ’s tail, refers to a child who cannot sit still, wriggling around like the tail of a pig. idiom: matai via kana vuaka. lit., carpenter who wants to eat pork, i.e., refers to a person who might pretend to diligence and skills but in fact is only interested in how the work is rewarded. idiom: sa kua la na kana! playful flattering words said before a pretty girl. implies she is so pretty that it puts you off your food. idiom: kana vosa to take verbal abuse, get complaints. idiom: kana e loma eats away inside (disease, hurtful words). e kana e loma vei au na nomu vosa. your words feel hurtful to me. idiom: kana, kana! ka o lakova mai. lit. “eat, eat ! that’s what you came for.” teasing a friend who is passing by during a meal, invited to join in.

cagi v. n., an idiom, to eat nothing, as in skipping breakfast or lunch. lit. “eat the wind”. syn. (slang) kana “wind”-p ai. kana wai, by contrast, refers to a definitive and total loss, as of a team at some sport.

n. blue-spot mullet, seasonal migrants upriver. a secret, sacred totem among a few colo east kin-groups, as at village naqara. valamugil spp. see also kava. idiom: rokoroko vakanace. lit., show respect like a mullet, i.e., fail to give proper respect, just as a mullet skip s out of the water to avoid the larger, predatory fish.
(ni bulumakau) n. cow pasture.
. n. taste, flavour (food or beverage). vakacava na kena ikanakana ? what does it taste like?
. n. piece of land belonging to a clan, used for planting food crops.
. n. piece of land granted as a food-garden area for someone who is a useful but needful member of the community. the land is not permanently alienated. e dua na qele me kedra ikanakana

adj . edible, tasty.
ca v. to eat alone, secretly, very bad manners in fij i, where one must always offer to share food with other people. syn. kana lo.
dirty, unkempt, slovenly . kana kuita v. to beat or flog, give a thrashing. kanakuita n. corporal punishment (as formerly , in schools).
octopus.
(eng.) n. colonel.

. tasteless or tasting “off”, lacking a proper taste.
lo v., n. to eat by oneself to avoid sharing food, or by extension, to conceal some secret purpose. not sharing food would be despised behaviour to fij ians.
v., adj . . usually after a hard day ’s work, from fatigue, to eat dinner and go right to sleep without delay .
v., adj . . to be lazy , or not having to do any work, just enjoy one ’s leisure, eat and sleep without taking the trouble of working. this is the most common meaning of the idiom.
adj . of pregnant woman, to have crazy, idiosyncratic food desires.
n. lower j aw of the human head, from the notion that it moves yavala when a person eats the food. see galegale.

n., v. meal shared with family, friends or colleagues. vata together. this is informal, with no traditional ceremony, only the saying of grace before a meal, now customary among fijians. sharing of food is very important to fijians.
v. to over-eat, stuff oneself with food to the point of discomfort.
idiom: v. to lose badly, usually at some sporting game such as football; lit. to eat water, to get nothing. see kanacagi.
v., n. to eat here and there, take food where one can, in different places.
n . the bird, velvet dove of kadavu island, ptilinopas layardi.
n., adj . dry scaly skin, often with blotches, that results from excessive drinking of yaqona. kanikani refers to serious cases.
n. cannibalism.

terrified.
sunburn(ed)
adj ., n. of a person, involuntarily possessed by a devil tevoro. this is a fairly frequent occurence. the agitated victim is usually held down and attended to, being told to : eat it ! kania!
spoiled by the rain.
n., v. to tickle deliberately, tickling, usually the armpits, ribs, soles of the feet.
v. to feed (person, animal). vakania na koli to feed the dog. idiom: vakania na qio lit. feed the sharks, i.e., to vomit at sea when seasick.

. to be thirsty for some beverage (water, yaqona, beer). karamaca extremely thirsty. idiom: oi au sa kara . make another round of yaqona, lit. i am still thirsty. idiom: gunu kara after drinking kava and wanting to sleep, to realize the need to drink more to enable sleep

n. dandruff. kara, karaca v. to reprimand, scold. na karakara the reprimand. kara, karavaka (or ) karataka . v. to paddle (boat, canoe). karataka na waqa i cakau paddle the boat to the reef. unlike eastern polynesians, fijians apparently had no elaborately decorated oars. kara, karavaka . v. to pole (boat), to pole for something or someone. ikara pole for poling a boat. karadila n. v. to make a symbol, sign, action that represents something else. that can be a sign, diagram, picture, enactment or re-enaction, perhap s of a drama, or an historical event.

n. representation, that could include say, a re-enactment of the signing of the deed of cession, or a thing, such as an imitation (as a rather modern notion), a sign, symbol, diagram, that represents a thing or an action.
levu v. to talk with unpleasantly loud voice(s), rowdy (as of children) and thus self-assertive and disrespectful.
loud, unpleasant sound grating on the nerves (crackling of radio, children packed in a room, some music bands with electronic amplifiers).
. blue (many things, sky, sea, fish). sa karakarawa na draki. it is relatively cloudless day with blue sky. the fijian colour formerly meant either blue or green, inspired from the colour of some
parrots, which depends on the angle viewed and the light. modernly, drokadroka is used for the abstract colour green, though previously that word would be used mainly for plant material.
. n. sp. of edible parrot fish blue and green colours, as implied by the name, chlorurus sordidus, scarus fasciatus, to cm. syn. rawarawa.

very thirsty. maca dry.
(eng. “grass”) marijuana. kana karasi smoke marijuana.
or karesini (eng.) n. kerosene. also, by extension, a kind of tree that has a wood that catches
easily and quickly even when wet. the tree vesiwai sometimes goes by this name. that is a very dense wood.

v., n. thud, to make a very soft, sudden plosive sound, a far-off gunshot in the distance, a fart, a bag bursting, a coconut falling. karawa, dark green as of vegetation in the shade. also the name of a type of shark, possibly isurus glaucus.
(hindi) indian vegetable, momordica charantia, cucurbitaceae, sold in the public market, naturalised in some places. syn. kerala .
(eng.) n . carrot, also cart. (slang) lover.
(eng.) n. curry, turmeric. tara kari prepare curry (fijian adaption of hindi term "thar kari"). curry
about % turmeric powder and at least % coriander seed powder. other

from mulberry stems, for barkcloth., burnt crumbs from toast, mud from a shoe. karitaka to scrape forcefully. ikari (ni niu) coconut-grater.

and storing in enclosed space (bag, box, hole in ground), where self-generated ethylene gas hastens the process. this is an introduced process.

in drains, wet places, but are little used by fij ians. rorippa nasturtium-aquaticum (or) ipomea aquatica. a few fijians cultivate it for sale. syn. ota karisi. (rewa) karamua.
(eng.) n . christ. syn. (r. cath.) kirisito.
n., v. dusk, twilight. sa karobo mai na vanua or sa lutu mai na karobo. it is becoming twilight,

is falling. syn. (colo east) galo. vagalo v. to have supper (at dusk, just before nightfall). in the tropics, twilight is quite brief, not prolonged as in temperate climates. formerly, fijians normally had their second and last meal of the day before nightfall.
n., adj . pimples, pimply (person, fruit), scabies. syn. karo. moli karokaro lemon, lit. "pimply " citrus.
v. to walk with head down from age, infirmity or respect. also the name of a village in cakaudrove.
v. to cherish, look after, take care of (child, garden , boat, but usually humans) with emotional involvement. na veikaroni love and concern, tender care. dau karoni dearly beloved. cf.
treasured, often referring to a treasured possession.
. n. second one in a sequence.
. virtually the same, duplicate, replicate.
n. a certain type of family relative: first cousin of same sex if one of the cousins is married (the
as a back-up to support the wife if the husband dies). may also apply to two unrelated men who
married to a couple of sisters. two such related people are said to be veikaruani. karua can be
as a form of address, now sometimes used jokingly amongst unrelated people if the potential partner is found to be attractive.
adj . worthless, powerless, useless, dirty, ill-behaved (person). sa karui na nona itovo his/her behaviour is unacceptable. syn. gavui.
(lau) n. small common ground-fern now used in floral decorations. so-called male and female forms viz., karuka tagane and karuka yalewa, the latter, female form used under house-mats to soften

(ni yaqona) n. section of yaqona stem with one or two nodes, planted for propagation, or cut and dried as an adulterant to the beverage when it is sold in the form of powder. virtually all yaqona that is

as powder is adulterated with kasa or the rhizome (lewena) that has a weaker flavour (lower kavalactone content) than the root (waka). that is why fijians often prefer to buy unpounded kava, and do the pounding themselves.
. v. to run aground (of boat), or drift ashore. vakasa make a boat go aground. by ext. also, to be
vakasa e vale ni bula. and to gather firewood drifting in the water vakasa buka.
. v. to understand and quickly commit to memory. loma kasa quick-learner, intelligent. vakasa to make someone understand and remember. vakasama-taka ponder, consider, think about it.
n . partner. ika sa ni drua one of a set of twins. syn. isa.
v. to burst and spurt out (like a boil lanced).
(or) manumanu ni cagi n. lesser frigate bird, fregata ariel (the much more common species,
with two white patches underneath), or greater frigate bird, f. minor (males all black, female
and breast). rarely go out to sea more than miles and thus an indicator of nearby land. cannot land at sea because feathers are not water-repellant and feet not webbed. with long
bill it often steals small fish caught by other birds. in breeding season males can display conspicuous red throat-patch . syn. (regional) lasaqa.

n. a sp. of edible salt-water rock cod, grey background with brown colour markings of a a grouper, to cm. lodges at holes in the reef. epinephelus polyphekadion. same genus as kavu. syn. se-ni-kawakawa. (lau) kerakera. idiom: vunau va ra kasala doing the very same thing he/she advises against, thus a hypocrite. vunau sermon.
n. dry twigs, small kindling, usually for lighting fire. kasa-na n. stem, petiole, pedicule of a plant. usually applies to fruit or flowers. may apply to other things with a small stalk or handle.
v. to suspect. au kasamitaki seru. i suspect seru.
n. dried branched stalk of coconut palm from which the nuts hung, used as a sort of rake or crude broom.

uru v. to fall down amply, as of fruit or coconuts, collap se (tree, house) into a pile. may refer to things in a huge pile. kase, kaseta v. to slander behind the back, back-bite, gossip about (person). kaseti au gossip about me.
n. gossip.
torn, broken open (clothes). kasei rua split in two. kasere, kakaseresere v. to tear in many places, be torn to bits.
n. scab, as of a cut or wound. particle(s) of “sleep” in the eye or on the eyelids, or dried spittle, dried mucus on the face. related to the word imamaca.
. n. abcess or long-term internal injury as from a fall.
. (or) kasiqarisui n. a fijian malady, painful joints, possibly related to arthritis. somewhat similar in notion is kasi-qari-lewe, probably related to rheumatism sasala .
. n. very fine root-hairs, as of yaqona. wa kasi sp. of very thin vine.
. (eng.) n. gas. kasi gaga poison gas (wartime).
. v. to crawl. kasi lo crawl secretly. syn. qasi.

. n. strip of skin from plantain or banana stem, used as string for binding. kasi, kasia . v. to peel or cut off and away, or fall away (dead leaves, useless stem-skin of banana, pandanus), skin (cassava, fruit). syn. (lau) qasi, qasia. kasi, kasia, kasina . v. to tie together on a string something such as mud lobsters mana, sea crabs qari or land crabs lairo.
n. small hermit crabs sometimes used for bait, cancer sp.
n. furry sort of “hair” on the ferntree trunk, which indicates maturity and strength of the trunk.
attractive, neat, well presented, of a person.
(eng.) customs.
(eng.) custard.

n. tiny ant, often appearing in great numbers during rainy weather or even before the rain. syn. (lau) qasivi. kasivi, kasivita n. to spit, spit on. it has been custom, falling into disuse, to spit (or simulate spitting) and
(fair weather, good crops) at the drinking of a bowl of yaqona, particularly
as host. the celebration is called ikasiviti ni vale. in urban areas the custom has fallen into disuse.
. in the old game of veitiqa, the shaft of the j avelin to which the head (ulutoa) was attached. this

source_text: was usually made from a reed
target_text: (gasau). ikaso . n. bar that connects a canoe to its outrigger.
. n. child(ren) born out of wedlock, of a chiefly father. ikaso vesi when the mother is chiefly,
dolou when the mother is a commoner. vesi is a strong, durable wood; dolou implies that the outrigger can be broken off easily, literally like old dead branch of breadfruit tree that breaks easily.
. v. of water, to splash with bubbles, as from a wave or obj ect falling in water, or from boiling.
. adj . of a person, to be very drunk. syn. mateni.
adj . swampy, of land.
spilt, from sova, sova pour it. kaka-sovasova spilt all over the place. vakasova, vakasova v. to pour water carefully, usually on plants, to water them.
. v. to burst open (of a boil, or parcel, bag, basket). kakasurasura burst all over the place, such as rice from a bag, many houses in big earthquake
. v. to fall apart suddenly, collapse (shed, temporary building)
. v. to break-up or disintegrate, of a business, voluntary sports team, political party, club or other group of people.
. (eng.) n. cutter (boat), which replaced fijian canoes. cutters were much used for fij ian interisland sailing from the s or earlier, through the s, before the use of outboards engines,
and scheduled airlines. fijians are a very motile people and this was an historic era of
sailing. ports like levuka and lautoka were sometimes crowded with cutters. the cutters had
or navigational equipment, though some had motors. only the larger cutters had a compass.

the boats were overloaded with people and cargo, and hardly ever had life preservers or extra water. living conditions aboard had no amenities. this word has fallen into disuse since cutters are obsolete. the port of levuka lost its importance in sea traffic when motorised boats became common.

. (archaic) n. hull of an outrigger canoe. cama n. outrigger. kata, katia v. to bite (animal, person), sting (insect, a thorny plant), (lau) itch. kati mai have a bite (from fruit, candy etc., inviting someone to share it). e kati na siwa. the fish are biting. ikata n. bite. na katakata the biting (also meaning “the heat”. e sega ni veikati na koli. the dog does not bite.
v. to hunt with dogs (for pigs, mongoose).
adj . indistinct, unclear, blurred, faded (as of an old photo).
v. to refuse by facial gesture, pouting and pretending to spit, as a forceful rej ection, as if affronted, a particularly fijian grimace.
v. to close both eyes, wink at (person), often in sly, secretive communication.
v. to cluck the tongue in reproach, regret or surprise. katadigita cluck tongue once in strong approval.
v., n. the equiv. of english “psst !”, sort of hissing or kissing sound made by person, often to attract attention of someone; also the noise of a bat.
adj . of cloth or barkcloth, damaged, worn out, disintegrated, faded and weak from age, humidity, insect damage.
adj . hot (weather, person, thing), hotly spiced (of food, with chilli, an introduced condiment).

katakata quick tempered. katakata vinaka good and hot. vakatakata-taka v. to warm it up, heat it up. me vakatakata mada na ovani. please heat the oven. idiom: itukutuku buta katakata idiom: fresh “hot” news, lit. hot from cooking. idiom: katakata vakurokava become quickly hot then quickly cold (object, person's temperament),
a tin-pot that heats quickly but then cools off quickly. people may begin with great enthusiasm, but may lose interest quickly .

n. breakfast food, these days a rather formal word. more modernly, familiarly, one says gunu ti, “drink tea”, specificially meaning breakfast which may or may not be substantial. formerly fij ians ate only two meals a day. they often rose at dawn and worked for a few hours before breakfasting. lunch
never a formal meal. supper was usually eaten just before nightfall. katalau, katalautaka v. to breakfast, to eat for breakfast.
v. to have (something consumed) for breakfast. fij ians often eat a piece of cassava, or some flour-based fried food.
v. to make a sound sucking the teeth, indicating reproach.

v. to flicker, of a light such as a candle or a failing light. katariva, katarivata v. to blink or wink deliberately, make a secret signal to someone. such private signals are common because open talk may be thought to be rude or too revealing.
v. to signal to someone by making a hissing sound. katasisitaki au to signal to me by hissing. in english this might be the equivalent of “psst !”, to attract someone’s attention. syn. katasiu.
v. to make a hissing sound to call someone, or dog. also said of a kettle hissing, or a steam-pipe, or a cat, snake or mongoose. syn. katasomi.
n. tinea, athlete ’s foot or so-called “jock-itch”, a fungus, often treated with tolnaftate or other fungicide.
n. a small tridacna sp., var. of giant clam that is generally known as vasua.
v. to snap (fingers), click (noise of prawns). see vida.
(eng.) n. bulldozer , “caterpillar”.
v. to bite through and break off with the teeth (sugar cane, nut).
adj . chipped (cup, plate, clay pot).
adj . broken, cracked in two (plate, bottle, coconut), separated (land, by flood).
(eng.) n. carton. kateni-taka v. to put things in a carton.
v. spread out widely (weed on land, oil spilled on floor, news among people). see tete.

. (eng. “cut”) n., v. card game with the purpose of collecting money for some local cause. at each round, participants "buy " one or more cards at a set price (these days ¢ up to $), and win a prize if
of their cards is selected at the cut. prizes are usually one or more items of food (sugar, rice), or
(bowl, knives). cuts are made rapidly so that quite a bit of money can
made, and almost everybody goes home with some prizes. this is a good feeling of social togetherness and yaqona is usually served freely by the organiser.
. (slang) n . young girl-friend, boy-friend (opposite sex), implying bother and trouble of a selfinterested young child; cuteness may be implied.
. adj . j ealous, spoiled, demanding (child). kakua ni katikati don't be a spoiled brat. it seems that

people use this word simply referring to children without implying a demanding or cheeky nature. katikati . v. to sting, as from medication on a cut, scratching or scraping of an arm of leg in falling, prick or scratch of thorns. see sasa.

(lau) v. to insist on getting something. syn. cikecike. kati, katia, katilaka v. to bite (food, prey), sting (insect, irritant such as tiny thorns). katilaka v. to bite hard. katikatilaka bite very hard repeatedly.
adj . chipped (cup, plate, clay pot). syn. katebe.
adj . cracked (tooth, plate); from tiki, tikica.
tenth, tithe (as imposed by certain christian sects).
n. angular-shaped basket, bag, or modernly, a box. kato kau wooden trunk (usually for personal belongings). kato ni lako travel bag. kato lili handbag. kato ni vosa n. recorder. (tape or disc). kato
tool-box. kato ni vuli school bag. kato ni volivoli shopping bag. kato ni ki key-case. kato
meli mail-box. kato ni ilavo money-box. kato (or) kisi ni mate coffin . kato ni wai watercontainer, water canteen (of soldiers) kato ni cakamana legendary magic basket or box containing
ancestral objects, lost at sea in a storm in the yasawas just before one of the later, major
arrived at the so-called first landing near vuda on the west coast of viti levu. kato ni tu
or case in which a clan mataqali or other kin-group may keep precious records such as lease records, papers from hearings of the native lands commission, lists of registered members, births
. adj . abundant, of fish caught. one never uses this word before going fishing. that would be
to bring bad luck and poor fishing. idiom: katoa na domo lots of words but only talk, no performance.
. adj . successful. lesu katoa mai vanua tani v. to return successful from overseas.
n. recording (usually music), compact disc or tape. na iyaya ni katokatoni recording equipment.
n., adj . roman catholic. na lotu katolika the catholic church.
third.
v. to retain, to keep permanently (an obj ect, a thought, a feeling). katona, katona-taka v. to record (music etc.).
n. uterus, womb. syn. duve.
n. bladder (urinary). mi urine.
n . recorder, as for musical tapes, compact discs.

n. a rather dated, awkward word for refrigerator or cooler. modernly on might just hear the word “fridge”. katu, katuma v. to measure in fathoms (approx. feet), with outstretched arms and hands. vale katu tolu house three-fathoms in length. katudrau ceremonial barkcloth (masi), of great length, theoretically of fathoms, for formal presentation. the size of a fij ian house is normally expressed as so many
(katu) in length. idiom: vale katu dua burial grave. idiom: katuwalu complicated, hard to understand, especially of english or foreign speech.
v. to run with long steps in the stride. (a katu is about feet in length or height.)
n. doorway but modernly that implies a door. fijian did not have a fixed or hinged door. they
unattached matting or woven leaves as a closure (isogo). in the highland a block of wood was sometimes used that was propped up by a stone that covered up half of the doorway. (see roth, f ij ian
of lif e, p . .) the height of the doorway opening was formerly very low ; a visitor could not
erect. this would delay an attacker. syn. darava. icurucuru entrance/exit. early fij ian houses
only one doorway, usually on the lee side, and no windows. later colonial authorities required houses to have at least two doors and three windows.
(anglicism) n. window. traditional fijian houses had no windows. leka short.
levu n. main doorway of fijian house where most people enter, at the lower end of the house. syn. katuba i sue.
n. side doorway of fijian house where privileged people enter. syn. katuba i kubu. this custom developed after the pax brittanica.
(eng.) adj . funny in a ridiculous way, of a person or their behaviour, from the english, as from a “cartoon” character. syn. kisitoni, sakisi.
v. explode, burst out (laughter, shouting, baloon bursting cannon, bamboo gun, music), punch hard, fight hard, from tuvu-laka. in lau the word is f uf utekateka.
n., adj . plant (small herbaceous plant, shrub, bush, or tree), timber, wood, stick. vu ni kau tree. vale
wooden house. a clan ’s “plant” (kau or kautabu) is its sacred plant totem, a feature of melanesian fij ians, especially on viti levu. prohibitions have surrounded such totems and usually, a
(kaicolo) will not mention the word and cannot discuss the subject when it has fertility
clans have totems). kau-vuata fruit-tree. kau-salusalu tree that yield attractive or sweetsmelling flowers or leaves for making garlands, such as mokosoi. syn. (lau, kadavu, vanualevu) kacu.
n . bunch of bananas or plantain. veta “hand” of bananas. syn. (lau) ua.
. n . introduction of a book, essay, research report. syn. vakamacala taumada.
(ni meke) . n . song sung before an exhibition-dance (meke) begins.

n. forest, bush. veikau loa deep forest, dense forest, remote forest. kau, kauta v. to take, take away, bring, carry. kauta mai bring it here. kauta yani take it away (away from the speaker). kauta na isele me nomu. take the knive as your own (for yourself). idiom: e kauta tu ga na ketena. he/she comes (to the feast, dinner) bringing only his/her stomach, with no food or gift, just to eat “free”.
(anglicism) v. to bring (it) up, as a topic in conversation, an item for an agenda. kau laivi, kauta laivi v. to reject, to take away.
n. a ceremony of introducing children to their mother’s village, bringing substantial
(kerosene, mats, bales of cloth). by this, children are formally recognized at the village. (this
is based on the traditional notion that the mother lives away from her own village, having
village at marriage; these days that is not so often the case.) fijian children are
supposed to appear at their mother’s village till this ceremony has been performed. after it, they

and duties of a vasu. these days parents often wait to take all their children at the same time, so some of their children may already be in their teens. commoners now sometimes ignore the custom as being too expensive for them, and formal village relationships not so important.
(or) kaunicina n. tree with edible nut but very hard shell, hard to crack. the nut oil formerly
by small-island people as lamp-oil. (cina lamp). canarium harveyi, burseraceae, but also two
indigenous species with a small nut, hard to crack, eaten only as an occasional snack. in vanuatu, and especially parts of the solomons and papua-new guinea there are more cultivars and
and cassava that have displaced it completely . in western melanesia, the canarium nut is
know as the galip nut. colourless sap turns white on exposure. see yagai, a lauan name that
from a solomon language. syn. kaunigai, referring possibly to the fact that wild pigs
eat the bark . (gai baby pig). the name kaunicina may also apply to haplolobus floribundus; hardened flammage latex formerly used in torches.
n. timber tree, myristica castaneifolia, syn. maile in eastern fiji, closely related to commercial nutmeg, having a very similar fruit but without the taste. named kaudamu for red bark and sap.

v. to put on airs, be pretentious, self-promoting, pretending to be on par with higher-class people., idiom: kua ni kaukauti iko cake don ’t “put on airs”, don ’t be pretentious, don ’t act “big-time”. in speaking english , fijians might say “don ’t put yourself up” or “don ’t go around collar-up”. vakau, vakauta v. send off (message, package, person). vakau me la ’ki lewai mai vanua tani extradited

overseas. na ivola sa vakauta mai o seru the letter (or book) seru sent here. ke o via vakau ilavo, . . if you wish to send money, . . kau baleta v. to intrude by word or action. kau baleta na tanoa to walk across in front of yaqona bowl tanoa, a disrespectful action; at informal grog sessions, when it may be absolutely necessary to walk in
of the tanoa, one should bow down and touch the bowl respectufully. kau baleta na nodatou
cut into our (several) conversation. vakau-caca-taka v. to slander, speak ill of (person).
. n. (tongan ukamea) iron. wa kaukamea steel wire. kaukamea . n. common weed, introduced, vernonia cinerea, compositae, leaves crushed and applied to cuts to prevent infection. syn. tagi-o-litia.

n. dangerous tree of dense forest, yellow or brown-black sap causing severe itch, blindness, semecarpus vitiensis, anacardiaceae. red inner bark. lves entire, stiff and leathery, dark green above, grey-green beneath, rounded apex. frts all year, small to cm, irregularly rounded, ripening orange to purple-black.the dangerous sap solidifies and becomes black on exposure to air. syn. (lau, vanua levu) malawaci.
(or) kaukauwa adj . strong, tough. modernly one might hear this word applied to a beverage such as kava, but that is not traditional usage.
v. to make it firm, stronger. in spelling, the w may be omitted. see kauwai.
(anglicism) v., n. body-building.
n. goods (mats, sinnet, barkcloth, kava, whaleteeth) brought in formal presentation, exchange, in traditional manner.
n. sp. small land crab, used as bait, not eaten by fijians. rotumans eat it raw by sucking on it.
n. firewood ready to carry, already cut up.
adj . thorny (of plant).
n. tree, several different genera, including some of the ebony family.
n . plant(s), cassia spp., weeds that have leaves folding up at night.
n. j awbone. see galegale.
n. wood to be lit by friction in making fire.
n. flagpole.
(eng.) n. consul (foreign service). councilor (as in town council).
ni siwa n. (anglicism) fishing rod. the rather archaic terms cavo and cavocavo may also apply to fishing with a rod. fijians never used fishing rods and only very rarely do in modern times.

n. legendary ship of immigrant lutunasobasoba and degei, probably in s, settling at vuda, then with some of those of this so-called “first landing”, moving on to nakauvadra. these immigrants arrived long after the much earlier, more melanesian settlers.
v. to reach, as of a path reaching a village, or the tide reaching to a certain location. this is not common usage. see kau, kauta.
. n. sp. prickly plant. syn. salato, dendrocnide harveyi, tree to feet, leaves and sap causing
irritation aggravated by water. planted around ancient fijian village-fortresses, this would help deter attackers.
. n. central longitudinal post in house-roof.
. n. totemic plant associated with a kin-group, clan or tribe, a melanesian concept of a sacred
(icavuti) of that kin-group ’s fertility and reproductive viability. similarly, the kin-group may
a sacred aquatic totem (ika tabu) and/or sacred animal (manumanu tabu), that may be a bird or insect. among some fij ian groups, especially viti levu highlanders, it is forbidden to mention names
totems. formerly, drastic consequences could ensue if anyone mentioned the name. that
sexual assault, stripping of clothes, throwing the culprit in a river. still today, offenders
be required to drink a huge bowl of yaqona, or have a bucket of water thrown over them. elsewhere, kin-groups or tribes may have iconic plants, plants with which they are closely associated,
. n. pile of sticks criss-crossed, usually to keep them dry for fire. this word supplied the origin for the concept of the christian cross.
n. sawn timber. varo to saw. kauvuata n. fruit-tree, or tree that produces edible nuts (tavola, tarawau for example) or starch foods (ivi, j ak-fruit, breadfruit).
n. a common soft-wood timber tree with compact crown, endospermum macrophyllum, euphorbiaceae, endemic on fiji ’s larger islands, at altitudes below m. treated chemically for
and formerly , for wooden boxes. slightly triangular alternate leaves, spirally arranged.
yellow fruit, mm diam, eaten by pigeons. smooth whitish bark and white timber, as suggested by the name meaning “white timber”. colourless sap. syn. (namosi, colo east) lekutu.
v. adj ., to be interested, supportive. au sega ni kauwai kina vakalailai. i am not at all interested in it. i cannot be bothered with it.
v. to support, believe, care about, be concerned about. au sega ni kauwaitaka na ka era
i do not care what they say, don't go along with it. kauwaitaka na lotu na levu ni wiliwili ni vakalutu. the church is concerned about the great number of abortions.
n. fruit of the tree vunikavika , semi-cultivated, malay apple, syzygium malaccense, myrtaceae,
meters, some varieties tasteless, some delicious. (very similar species, s. j ambos and s.
are tasteless.) exists from southeast asia through the pacific. fruiting from may to
mainly around early october, november, december. the flowers are scarlet. inner bark
to gale s. troxler who studied fij i bark-cloth. two main varieties: kavika damu or k.

(reddish at maturity), and kavika vulavula (whitish at maturity). syn. (polyn.) ka ’ika and cognates. idiom: kavika dreu lo refers to a girl with a beautiful face who as yet does not adorn herself correspondingly with flowers, perfume. lit., kavika fruit ripening secretly.

(cakau.) n. edible fish, though not highly prized, diamond-scale mullet, or square-tail mullet, liza vaigiensis, yellowish body, yellow tail. unlike some other mullet (kanace), does not migrate upriver.
schools close to shore. syn. kanace (general name for mullet). waikava is a river on the southern
of vanua levu island. waikava was the place of the second council of chiefs (actually only a
roko tui, salaried heads of provinces with advisory powers only), organised by governor a.

in . (only one roko tui attended all meetings; others were casual in their attendance.) later, chiefs decided to call themselves the great council of chiefs though many members were not chiefs. today the place is a wilderness, with no sign remaining of the historical event. one chiefly
tribe a i sokula returned to live there after the tui cakau set aside their land on taveuni to provide for morris hedstrom facilities. syn. (tonga) ‘ava.
. (tonga) n. yaqona, the beverage shrub piper methysticum, familiarly known as grog. fijians of
background remove the skin (civicivi) from the rhizome (lewena) to make a whiter drink that is somewhat less bitter. the root (waka) makes a stronger beverage, preferred by many fijians.
. (tongan “kapa”) n. sheet metal, corrugated iron, also a can or tin, as of meat or biscuits. vale
n. house made of sheet metal. kava ni benu n. rubbish bin.
. n. tin, can. kava bulumakau tinned beef. kava p amutaki aerosol can. kava, kavana v. to roll up (mat, sinnet).
fourth. kava, kavata (west) v. to comb (the hair). kavata na ulu-na comb his/her hair. ikava n. comb. these are older words than seru, seruta, and iseru.
broken , smashed (glass, coconut) . syn. kavoro.
broken off (tree-branch, bunch of fruit like coconuts, citrus, dawa).
n. (eng.) n. cabbage. kaveti olo english cabbage, brassica oleracea, var. bullata. kaveti ni
chinese cabbage, several types but perhaps mainly “wong bok”, brassica pekinensis.
(eng.) captain.
adj . cracked (coconut, cup, plate, yam), split (wood), sharply divided (people’s opinions). syn. see vida, vida to split. see also kacavida.
n. indigenous temporary drinking cup or vessel improvised from large leaf (plantain, taro). in the
of viti levu there were no cups and certainly no half coconut shells to use as cups. drinking was normally done by pouring water into the open mouth , or by lapping it up.
as in lotu kavitu, an american christian sect, seventh day adventists, that retains saturday as
sabbath, tithes for church contributions, largely vegetarian, follows dietary restrictions of leviticus, forbids tea, coffee and yaqona, tobacco. vitu seven.
broken, cracked, from voro, voroka . ikavokavoro sherds. kakavorovoro smashed completely (bottle, eggs). kavu! interj ection, usually surprise and disappointment. syn. bala! (or) pala!

v. to be blown about by wind, as sand (nuku) might be, or dust (kuvu). kavukavu adj . dry (skin, as on face, from exposure; throat, as when suffering from a cold). kavu n. edible fish, a rock cod, grouper, sea bass, j ew fish, promicrops lanceolatus. that can grow large, to , pounds and a length of feet according to rob wright. more commonly , large ones might weigh lbs and extend to seven feet in length. kavu now mainly classified as a couple of species of genus epinephelus. see kasala. kavuru v., adj ., n. to crumble, crunchy, crunched, crumbs, broken into pieces, crushed, from vuru, vuruka. by ext., kavuru n. butt, stub of a cigarette. ka ni kavuru ash-tray. see kavoro. idiom: kere kavuru beg for crumb s, beg for food, but more commonly, to cadge a cigarette.
. n. family lineage, progeny (humans, animals, plants). na ivola ni kawa bula the genealogical
all registered fijian clans and registered members. kawayali (or) kawa boko extinct
(tribe, clan).
. n. blood-relative from the father's side of the family. bula kawa! hello kinsman ! (colo greeting). the equiv. for a relative by the mother would be bula vasu!).

v., adj . to have children, progeny. kawa, kawaca v. to walk on (prone tree-trunk, stones) or in (water), in making a crossing, as of mud, swamp , river. ikawakawa improvised crossing-place, used as rough bridge. idewadewa i tai n. crossing to the other side.
n. fish-trap of wire or wicker with two "pockets" to retain fish.
adj . extinct (race, species). vakawaboko-taka to exterminate.
n. edible fish, sea bream, upper body yellowish, belly white, lethrinus nebulosus, caught inside and around the reef. same genus as sabutu.

n. cultivated species of edible yam, dioscorea esculenta, specialty of certain places with a dry climate, particularly in tavua, ra and macuata. not as noble a ceremonial food as the regular, more common yam, uvi, d. alata, which usually matures later and can grow to a much larger size. also, by contrast, kawai stems twine to the left, counterclockwise, and have alternate (not opposite) leaves.
referred to as the chinese yam, or lesser yam. the flesh is drier and whiter than the regular yam, and it is less chewy and perhaps a little sweeter.
. v. to be critical, to criticise. au vakawai koya ena nona isulusulu. i am critical of the way he/she dresses.
. adj . watery, soggy, as a melon might be. not common usage.
v. to add water, as to a pot, in cooking. kawakasa n. bird mainly of the bush, usually heard, not so often seen, near rocks, waterfalls, long tail that
on landing, long-tailed cuckoo, breeds in new zealand, arriving in fiji during april, departing by october, sometimes as late as december.
n. place to cross on foot, usually a foot-bridge improvised (permanently) with a tree-trunk.
any substantial, safe footbridges no matter how frequently used the crossing. (there have been sigificant exceptions, such as ancient river crossings in rewa.) ikawakawa
n. footbridge of a coconut-palm trunk. substantial, modern road bridges are referred to as
(“wharf”).
n. edible fish, grouper, several species; cephalopholis spp., epinephelus spp. names vary regionally. bearing this name is the variegated grouper that is dangerouly poison.
eighth.
n. something useless or unimportant, useless thing.
n. extinct stock (tribe, clan). syn. kawaboko. yali lost.
v. to bend (sail).
v. to say, said. syn. (rewa) kanaka.
with him/her/it. lako vata kaya go with him/her/it. na gone au sa lako kaya ki lautoka . the child i went with to lautoka. abbrev. of kei koya.

if. shortened form of kevaka. ke au o iko . . . if i were you . . . . ke o lako ki suva, ke drau sota kei mere, qai solia vei koya, kevaka e rawa if you go to suva and if you meet mere, give it to her, if possible. when ke follows kevaka in a sentence, ke means “would”, i.e. kevaka ko a tiko kina, ke o mate. if you had been there you would be dead.
here. see oqo.
over there, at that place.
(eng.) n. camp (military, boy scouts).
all. kece ga absolutely all. ena veika kece in all things. na tamata kece all the people. see
whole, all, referring to things rather than people.
we (many, incl.). includes the person spoken to. our (many) food.
we (two, incl.). our (two) food.
we (several, incl.) our (several) food.
their (many) food for them to eat themselves. also their (many) something that is integral to them.
their (several) food for them to eat themselves. also their (many) something that is integral to them.

their (two) food for them to eat themselves. also their () something that is an integral part of each other. kedrau iyalayala o ra kei tailevu the border between ra and tailevu, lit. their border, ra and tailevu.
v., n. to snore, to snort. na ikedrukedru n. the snoring. this is often caused by a physical or nerve

called sleep apnea, a malady that is not recognised by fijians. it is most common among people who sleep on the back rather than the side. idiom: kedru toso v. facetiously refers to someone who shifts about (toso) while pretending to be sleeping, moving secretly closer to desired person of opposite sex . informally, people may sleep fairly close to each other on the comfortable and clean, soft matted floor of a traditional fijian house.
. and (or) with. veitalanoa kei seru chat with seru. seru kei au seru and i. kei na so tale et cetera, and so on. na nona veimoceri kei na dua na yalewa his sleeping with a woman. lako vata kei
to go together with seru .
. of (in certain applications, when something is an integral part of another). na qele kei viti the land
the outskirts of suva.
. concerning, on the subj ect of, about. na italanoa kei seru the story about seru. a itukutuku kei
the history of fiji. na irogorogo kei cakobau the fame of cakobau. this implies that something is an integral part of something or someone.
we, us, our (many, excl.). excludes the person spoken to.
we, us (two, excl.). the person being addressed is excluded from the couple referred to. keirau sa veikilai. we (two, exc.) have met, know each other.
we, us (several, excl.). in speaking to an outsider, a fijian may refer to himeself and his own kingroup as keitou we.
if that is so. ke ka, daru lako. if that is so, let us () go. keke . (medical) n . lumbago, i.e., persistent pain in the lower back.
. (eng.) n. cake. fijians have firmly adopted the custom of baking and eating cakes, even the necessity of birthday cakes in urban areas, especially for children.
v. to dig in the bush for wild yams such as tivoli.

(tonga kekeho) n. type of clam shellfish found only at waqava island (next to kabara island, in lau), no doubt imported from tonga. in fiji, it is a local curiosity. kele, kelea . v. to anchor (boat), stop or park (motor vehicle). kelea (the vehicle). kelea ina wavu to
at the wharf. kele ciri v. to anchor out, away from j etty or shore. keleravi, keleravita v. to
(or stop) next to (something, some place). kele, kelea . v. to push down, stick in the ground, usually to set up a fence-post, fish-fence post, signpost, etc.
n. anchor, anchorage (boat), bus-stop, garage, parking place. keli, kelia v. to dig (a hole, drain). ikelikeli ditch, drain . na kekeli the digging up of wild yams.
n. man-made canal. reference may be to suez canal, or more commonly , to the old canal
a waterway from bau to rewa, joining the wainibokasi river with the wainiki river (now
n. bend or turn in a road or river. see takelo.
(eng.) n. chemist-shop, pharmacy. syn. kemisi.

. possessive pronoun: your (one person), food for you to consume. oqo na kemu here is your food. oqo na kemu ika here is your fish (for you to eat). idiom : kemu! (interj ection to a person): you deserved that ! serves you right ! you had that coming !

. possessive pronoun: your (one person) thing or characteristic, as in na kemu irairai your (personal) appearance, the way you appear to others. na kemu italanoa the story about you, your story. contrast with nomu, “your” that is less personal, less a part of the person.
you (several), as obj ect of sentence. possessive “your” and may refer to food to be consumed
(several). also used as interj ection oh, you !, in mock reproach.
you (two), as object of sentence. may be a very polite form of address to a person.
you (many), object of sentence. also used as polite form of address, even to a single person. na

your food (many, or very politely, a singular person). kena . its (almost anything). na kena duidui its difference. idiom: na kena levu in ending a message, report, or letter: that’s all there is to say, to report. kena . his/her/its (food), for that person (or animal) to consume, always as na kena. idiom: vakalevu kena to restrain oneself, by modesty or shame, not accepting, usually food, when actually one is quite hungry.

. his/her/its, referring to some integral part of the person or thing. na kena rewa its height (tree, building, mountain, never a person). na kena irairai his/her/its appearance. na kena italanoa the story about him/her/it.
n. part of woven thing (sinnet, rope, mat) to make it longer.
n. expert, someone who is adept.
n. person adept at speaking.
(eng.) n. cancer.
(eng.) n. canvas shoes.
. possessive pronoun: my food (to eat), as contrasted to mere possession that would be indicated by the word noqu. also applies to tobacco na kequ tavako my tobacco, cigarettes (that i will consume).

my (personal) appearance. na kequ italanoa my personal story (the story about me). kere, kerea v. to ask for (something), ask of (person). kere wai ask for water. kerea na wai ask for the water. kerea vei pita ask pita for it. kere veivosoti vua to apologise to him/her, to beg forgiveness (usually in light social matters). idiom: kere wai to be seriously needing water. idiom: mai kere liti-momo-wai said about a person who comes to ask for one thing, then greedily keeps adding more requests. idiom: kere cagi to be “winded”, short of breathe from exertion.
n. gift in a ceremonial presentation, usually a whale tooth, in gratitude for some request granted,

for the use of a piece of land for gardening, the use of fishing grounds, or for the use of a name for a child or a boat. permission may be required for the use of certain names that “belong” to a family or other kin-group. ikerei ni yaca n. gift requesting the use of a personal name, or name for a vehicle (boat, aeroplane) when that name “belongs” to some person or some community.
. please, a word that introduces a request. kerekere bibi introducing a serious, earnest request that is extremely difficult for a fij ian to refuse.
. n., v . custom of making demands on relatives, friends, employers, that are difficult or
for a fijian to refuse. reciprocity occured usually later, perhap s quite indirectly to a close relative, a favour done, some food given, schoolbooks bought, some help with garden labour. it might
considered vulgar to pay back too directly too soon. the system was based on mutual
that is still quite functional in segments of fijians society. but the social system has
changing, with some abuses occuring. nonetheless, a person might be resented if he bluntly
a request and as a result, fijians usually have trouble saying “no”. it could be thought rude and unkind. thus it is difficult for a fijian to accumulate much wealth while living as a fij ian in the
context. kinship relations are extremely important to the fijian, not individual advancement,

v. to boil, bubble actively (liquid), purr (cat), wheeze (sleeper, person with cold), reinforced by redup. kerekere. vakerea na wai to boil the water. idiom: tabu rogoca na kere ni cakau said to one who does not listen to instructions or good advice. lit. does not listen to the sound of the sea against the reef.
there, in the place where you are (the person being talked to), kere preceded by “i” or “e”, which may not be heard in certain situations
(eng.) n. carrier, van, truck. this relatively modern, general term has virtually replaced the older
lori (eng.) lorry. the change occured with the popularity of vehicles rented (with driver), to
goods for fijians going to and from their villages. road access to villages has increased greatly in recent years and there is a strong demand for rented “carriers”.
(eng.) charismatic, referring to the evangelical, demonstative christian sects that emphasize
singing, speaking in tongues. assemblies of god is a primary example but there are
several branches of christian sects that have a so-called charismatic orientation. the origin is

. n. a small tree, the long ago introduced annatto, bixa orellana, bixaceae, bark use for dyeing bark-cloth . seeds supply bright red colorant. in english, sometimes referred to as the lip stick tree.
. n. dye as used for decorating barkcloth masi, whether or not the colorant is made from this tree or some other plant. brown is usually made from boiled bark of mangrove tree dogo. black was often
candlenut-tree fruit lauci. today on vatulele, the black is usually made from

soot, fixed by mixing it with root-sap of the trees koka, or kaudamu. kesa may also be a woman ’s name. kesa, kesava v. to imprint with kesa dye. at vatulele and at moce, this is normally done with a stencil (kup eti or kup ej i in lau), formerly made of plantain leaf, now made of used x-ray film cut with a razor blade. lauans may use free-form designs in tongan style. na kesakesa the dyeing. na kesavi ni
the dyeing of barkcloth.

n. the slight depression at the upper back side of a person's head, crown of the head. kesu dudu "pin-headed", i.e., dolichocephalic (person). kesu sababa flat-headed at back, i.e. brachycephalic (person). fiji has both types of skull, indicating various origins. syn. buredela-na. idiom: (anglicism) mila kesu-na to be perplexed, not to know what to do or say; lit. to scratch one’s head. idiom: solia na kesuna v. to turn one’s back (on someone), showing disrespect. kete-na . n. belly, stomach. kete levu big-bellied. idiom: kauta tu ga na ketena lit. brings only his/her stomach , referring to a person who comes to a feast but brings no food, comes only to eat and makes no contribution.

. n. womb. bukete pregnant. kete gone (or) ketekete gone bears children easily or often (woman). syn. kato ni gone, duvu. kete-na . n . of a woven pandanus mat, the “good”, shiny side, in contrast to the back, dull underside.
n. (west) n. sub-clan, a type of kinship group, larger than the extended family (tokatoka). some place-names, even in lau , refer to kete-icake, kete-ira, locations of a family group.

n. bird, golden-breasted whistler, pachycephala pectoralis, widespread in fij i and vava’u, tonga, especially in mature forest. many local variations in incidental coloration. ketedromo n. riverine fish with a yellow belly, eliotridae.
n. woven coconut-leaf basket carried on the back by women. idiom: lewe ni ketekete n. land given to a vasu by the village. see vasu.
n. type of mullet, smaller and shorter than kanace, silver coloured, yellowish tail, travels far upriver. keu . if i, often seen as ke ’u, an abbrev . of ke au. ke itself is an abbrev. of kevaka if.
. n. v. to cry, of certain birds (onomatopoeic).

if. abbrev. ke. if ke follows kevaka in a sentence, the ke indicates the result of the “if”. kevaka o a tiko kina, ke o mate. if you had been there, you would be dead. keve, keveta (bau) v. to lift and carry in front at chest-height with arms underneath (baby, stack of books). keve liga to fold the arms. ikevekeve n. what is carried in the arms this way. syn., more common, roqo, roqota. kevu, kevuta, kevutaka v. to clamber down, climb down (as from tree, roof) or climb down in the direction of. kevutaka climb down bringing (something).
over there (far away), also seen as kea or e kea.
. to, toward (a place). kivei to (specific person, as in addressing a letter).
. for. sa dodonu ki na matanitu me cakava. it ’s right for government to do it.
. (eng.) n. key. vakitaka to lock with a key.
. n. a small edible fish, surmullet, yellow striped goatfish with a split tail, upeneus vittatus. annual
in great numbers celebrated at kaba, kiuva, daku and nasilai at viti levu, nagigi at
levu, and at vatoa island as well as other places. this little fish squeaks when it is touched.
side. village daku and settlement kaleli have a tradition of catching ki

sp., blechnaceae. a legend from vatoa island tells of this fish and a devil-woman (na viti lima, p . -). syn. (cakau.) ose, deu. (ba) kiki. voro (noted in na viti lima, p . ). ki, kitaka (eng. “key”) v. to set the pitch, usually for a church choir about to sing. na ki n. the pitch (musical). see kitaka with a different meaning, “to do”. vaki-taka to lock with a key .
(archaic) n. type of warclub.
v. to retreat into a hole (crab, rat, mongoose). mata kibo having the face shrunk back like an owl. see kino.
startled to a state of shock (of person, animal) resulting in sudden concealment, hiding, or crouching. kida . (eng.) n. abbrev. of kindergarten. syn. kidi.

. startled, to give a “start” in surprise. kidakida easily startled. kida is a root-word suggesting something that happens suddenly. kida . v. to break, of dawn. sa kida mai na mataka. dawn is breaking.
v . to realise too late, to have a sudden, belated realisation. kidacala, kidacala-taka v. to be surprised pleasantly (at something). e yaco vakakidacala mai na vulagi.
(one's eye, finger, leg) invisible to others. kida, kidavaka v. to greet or welcome a visitor, introduce a stranger. na kidavaki the welcome na

the formal greeting, formal introduction, usually with speeches and responses. kidi, kidia (or) kidiva v. to crease (as in folding paper napkins), crimp (cloth), sorokidikidi wrinkled (cloth), crinkled (paper), choppy (sea). kidi . (or) kidikidi adj . itchy (of body). syn. milamila.

(eng.) n. kindergarden. syn. kida. kidolo, kidoloka v. to choke or snap the neck (person, animal), or snap off (flower) forcefully. see doloka v. to break off, snap off, as a piece of sugar cane, or a small branch.
v. to throttle deliberately (person, animal), to strangle. kuna refers to formal, ceremonial strangling, as for widows of a recently deceased chief to accompany him in the next world, and also

(rare) event of hanging as a punishment, a custom derived from the english. domo n. throat. kidroa, kidroataka v. to be startled, give a "start", be stunned, shocked, as with usually unpleasant surprise.
n. a sucking sound of something removed from a sticky mass, usually used for feet in the mud. or a startled gasp with unpleasant shock, bad news, sudden fear.
v . to splash, as of an oar in the water or a stone thrown into the water.
(or) kiekie (lau, kadavu, macuata) leafy plant cultivated for weaving mats, baskets, pandanus sp. syn. voivoi.
n. common bird spp. onomatopoeic name with a very commonly heard call. wattled honeyeater.
are two species, a large one and a smaller one. the larger one has a much louder cry and has a larger body. exists only where there is no concentration of snakes, as noted by p. geraghty. there are
different synonyms in different localities. syn. sovau, visilo. (west) kitou. (lau) kaisevau. (nadroga) kikitou. (vanualevu) kaisau.
. (kadavu, lau) n. rattan. syn. wa ulo. this very woody vine can grow many hundreds of yards. it is used in securing house-thatch. legends tell of it allowing magical transport from fiji to tonga.
. v. to chirp , as of a small bird.
adj . very timid, extremely shy. kikilo adj . bumpy (usually of a road), having a lot of “potholes” (qara ni gaunisala),

adj . wild, shy (of animals). kila, kila v. to know, recognise. kilaka intelligent. kilaseva v. to fail to recognise. drau sa veikilai tiko ? do you two know each other? are you known to each other? have you met? e kilai. it is known.
recognised, realised. vakilai na yaga ni veisusu vinaka. the value of proper upbringing is recognised.
adj . conscious. au a sega ni vakilai yalo-qu. i was unconscious.
v. to reveal, make known.
n. mark, sign, sign-post, signature, indication, indicator (book-page marker, road-sign, army flag, symptom (medical). vakatakilakila ni taif ote symptoms of typhoid.
v. to make the introduction of people, to introduce or present someone.
adj . intelligent, quick to learn, understand, knowledgeable.

(or) va-kilakila v. to guess. kilakilai au “guess who i am”, a phrase that often begins a childrens’ riddle. similarly one may hear kilakila mada announcing a children ’s riddle and you are to guess the answer to the riddle.
adj . secretely sly. kilaleca, kilalecava, kilalecava-taka v. to mistake one thing or person for another, fail to recognise. syn. kilacala, kilacala-taka. kila-kasami, kilakasami-taka v. to suspect.
n. adjective, a word invented by schoolteachers. kilaseva, kilasevataka v. to fail to recognise someone or something, due to passage of time, or changes that have taken place.
v. to avoid, mistrust, be shy of.

adj . unsociable, uncouth, loner. vanua kilavaki wild bushland. kili, kilica . v. to upturn stones, as at the seashore, for shellfish, clear away stones or heavy earth from an oven when effort is required. vakili vatu turn up stones. kilikili n. small stones tossed onto a lauan grave, a respectful custom from tonga. kili, kilica . v. to open an earth-oven (lovo) after completion of cooking (ni sa buta oti). cele, celea v.
(eng. clear) v. to cast off, as of a boat, departing.
. n. (lau only) small stones which are dunked in coconut oil and spread on a grave, a ceremony

source_text: called vakadranu kilikili on the occasion of bogidrau
target_text: (one hundred nights after burial).
. adj . befitting, good manners (of behaviour). sa kilikili vei au meu cakava . it is fitting for me to do it. rairai kilikili suitable, fitting appearance.
a root-word: depression (as in road, pothole, person ’s face) kilokilo having a lot of potholes (road); ravine; qakilo valley. e kilo na baluna he/she has dimples on the cheeks.
v. to plunge head-first (usually into the river). me daru kilu qai lako. let us (two) take a dip , then go. kilu, kiluca v. to make sawtooth edge (mat); ibe va-kilukilu mat with sawtooth edge.

or kilipati (eng.) n., adj ., v. gilbert islands, gilbertese; by extension, to go diving with a single-pointed spear propelled by stretched rubber. gilbertese are superb experts at diving for seafood.
n. crop, stomach (of birds).
v. to squint the eyes due to glaring sun.
. n . j ar-shaped fishing trap woven of wa me vine.
. n. piece of weaving material (mat, rope, sinnet) for interweaving to extend the length. me vakina
interleave the sinnet to extend the length.
. particle. to which, to whom, of which, where. na vanua sa lako kina. the place where (to which) he/she went. na nona itikotiko o koya ko vakau ivola kina. the address of the person (him/her) to
you send the letter.
similarly, like this, like that. kini, kinita (or) vakini, vakinita v. to pinch between the fingernails as in pulling a splinter, or pinching

hard and painfully, as in punishing a child, or very lightly as in drawing a person's attention in secret signal ; to snap off, as in picking rourou, bele, or ota leaf vegetable; pinch mashed taro to form
for vakalolo pudding. e dua ni ikini masima n. a pinch of salt. kinilaka v. to pinch (a child) very forcefully, as punishment.

n. (archaic) type of wide, thin oar-shaped warclub with relatively sharp edges. kinivari, kinivarita v. to attract a person's attention secretly by pinching lightly . syn. tarakini, tarakinita, lit. touch by pinching. such secret signaling is common in fiji.

v. to shrink back, wither, withdraw as into shell, or into hole (marine animal) and thus to disappear; by ext., may apply to a person or animal, making themselves scarce at some impending danger or fear.

sunken face, as in illness of a person, or the face of an owl. see kibo. kino, kinoca . v . to stifle, withhold a sneeze or cough. kino, kinoca . v.to restrain, to curb, to keep within, defuse (tears, sobbing, anger, feelings of shame or other feelings of emotion, sneeze).
adj . has a plump, attractive body. kinokinota has a very plump and attractive body.
v., adj . squint, have narrowed eyes, have eyes with megalanthic fold, as do many orientals. syn. matadre.
n. chicks (many types of young birds), from the sound they make. kiri, kirica v. to tickle under the armpits.
(eng.) n. cricket (the game), greatly favoured by polynesians, now being played by more fijians with coaching and management by australian aid.
v. to tickle the armpits, ribs.
(or) kirikiri-na n. armpit(s). kiriwana v. to carry under the arm(s). syn: kirukiruwa-na.
(or) kirimu (eng.) n. cream. aisikirimi ice cream.
(eng.) christmas. also siga ni sucu. kirisimasi-ivi christmas eve.
(roman catholic) christ. syn. (prot.) karisito. kiro . v. to get down (as from a tree or roof). kiro . adj . hollowed out, curved, as dugout canoe; dimple on the human face; or other body depression,
from a wound.
. n. a sp . of bird, black-faced shrikebill, only on large islands. may also refer to polynesian starling, according to dr. watling.
v. to reverberate with rhythmic throbbing sound, or sobbing sound. could be a child sobbing or a drum perhaps, throbbing; to warble, to whimper repeatedly.
v. to cry sobbingly. kisi, kisia v. to shift, move (self or object), usually something heavy, not lifting it high, not moving it far.

to move forcefully. kisi mai! shift over here ! (seated). idiom: kisi kaba to put oneself up with pretension. idiom: dabe ena ibe qai kisi ki na tabakau. to be demoted. after living at a high level, then finding oneself in reduced circumstances. kisi . (eng.) n. case, box. kisi kau crate, wooden box. kisi ni mate coffin. see kateni cartom. kisi . (eng.) n. case (court). kisi, kisiva . (eng.) n., v. to kiss. kisilaka to kiss ardently. fijians never knew any form of kissing,
they did and still do sniff with nose to the face regu, reguca as an affectionate greeting or farewell, including the final farewell at a person ’s death, especially in areas of polynesian influence.

to lip kissing, and respectful kissing of the hand (often done by women) was learned from europeans. kissing babies in now common custom as is romantic kissing among the young, though romantic kisses are never done in public. ikisikisi n. kissing.
kaba (anglicism) n., v. (familiar) pretention, acting pretentiously, lit. to climb on top of a box (case).
(anglicism) “customs house”
(archaic) n. customs, now more commonely called kasitaba.
n., adj . (“keystone” cops of fame in old films) clown, a traditional role, usually mimicking

known, often in pantomime, spoofing them hilariously, an act that may be done by spontaneously in public by an ordinary person. by extension, a funny person, a person who makes you laugh. for the formal role of a comic who livens up a group-dance (meke), the term used is manumanu
meke. he is a funny, very skilled dancer, very adroit, agile, active, spoofing the other dancers to keep them performing at their peak. syn. sakisi, katuni.
v. to hop on one leg. yava kiso limp on one leg.
. hopping, "hop-scotch ".
. n . cramp (of the muscles) or other lameness that causes a person to limp or favour one leg.
v. to do (something specific). speaking broken fijian, some people over-use this word rather than
appropriate cakava. it is somewhat archaic. in modern fijian of the lower classes kitaka can imply sexual intercourse.
. n. ball of sinnet (coconut-fibre cord called magimagi).
. (lau, kadavu, nadro.) n. bird, swamp hen, porphyrio porphyrio. syn. teri.
. n. variety of coconut with very large shell, used as a water container when the shell is green and then dried. some used for salt water as a condiment to flavour food.
. (archaic) n. pottery j ar for water with clay handle, water spout on both sides, no longer used.
(or) kakiva v., adj . to act sly, cunning, to act smart for one’s age, to be a little too bold, presumptuous, “smart-ass”. mona kiva! is a form of rebuke, sometimes intended facetiously. mona brain.

to (person, as in addressing a letter, customarily written before the name). also ki vei? where to? kivi, kivita . v. to turn the head to one side, or to glance to one side with the eyes only; raikivi to glance to one side, over the shoulder; rogo kivi, rogo kivita cock the head to hear better. tikivi at one side, alongside, next to. e dua na yanuyanu lailai ka koto tikivi ovalau. a small island that lies to one side of ovalau . kivi, kivita, kivilaka . v. to knock someone (usually child) on the head with the knuckles, "dong the head" in fiji english, a typical fijian punishment for children, at home and in school. syn. qou, qouta.
indicator of proper name, person or place when used as the subject of a sentence, or when it stands alone. ko viti fiji. ko jone john. the letter “k” is sometimes dropped, as in polynesian languages.
you, singular pronoun, only as the subject of a sentence; ko iko used as object. alternatively one may drop the initial “k”: o and o iko.
n. birthmark of dark skin covered with fine hair.
(eng.) n. coal. this is a seldom used word since coal is not used in fij i. in early days, both fij i
n. bottom end of a yam, always used for eating, rather than as seed-stock for planting. syn. dromu-na.

. n. part of the penis removed by circumcision; may refer to a boy who has not yet been circumcised. see kulina. kobi . adj . astringent, of taste, as of an unripe banana. kobi, kobita v . to sting with astringency, can be used figuratively, of a person's speech.
(eng.) computer.
. n. sores on the scalp, under the head-hair, usually of children.
. v. to knock on the head with the knuckles, either as punishment to a child, or one child to another in hard play or bullying. syn. ikivi, ikodi, iqou, in this sense.
indistinctly visible, of limited visibility , usually due to fog, mist, faded daylight. syn. kabuata.
. adj . misty, foggy.

. n. type of grass. koca v. to be tired of something, long speeches, dull movie, certain foods. syn. oca. koco, kocova v. to covet. kocokoco greedy, covetous. this is a frequent reproach to children . koda, koda v. to eat raw (fish, shellfish, seaweed). kokoda n. marinated raw seafood with lemon, often also onions, chilli (introduced condiments), a polynesian concept. idiom: gunu koda to drink strong alcohol “straight”, without diluting in water, fruit juice or soda. .
v. to scream, squeal, screech (usually of a pig), when fearful, knowing it is about to be killed. kodro, kodrova v. to bark, at something (of dog). kodrovaka v. to bark because of something. na
the barking.
. n. part of a man's hair-do that juts forward in hair-style.
. n . a feather stuck up in the hair.
. n . a fish, small crevally.

(or) kofi (eng.) n. coffee. coffee has never been a successful commercial crop in fiji but overgrown plantations exist, as at gau island. fruiting is around may. the ripe fruit is sweet to eat as a snack and

the seeds may be munched, though one spits out the fibre. until recently, fijians rarely drank coffee. tea had been more common due to early british influence. now there are fashionable coffee shops in the cities, pioneered by john philp. what is called fiji coffee is roasted fresh, packed and sold in fij i after having been grown in papua new guinea.
(roman catholic) v. to confess.
(roman catholic & anglican) confirmation.
v. to grunt or squeal, as a pig does.
(or) oi pronoun particle, koi au i, me. occasionally this appears (and sounds) as koi yau, or oi yau.
(lau, vanua levu) here.
(archaic) n. flag. syn. kuila.
(colo) n. type of wild or semi-cultivated yam. see kaile.

n. a useful tree, j ava cedar, bischofia j avanica, euphorbiaceae, often used to mark borders because it lives long and endures high winds, heavy durable timber, white with reddish brown heartwood. clear sap turns red on exposure. lower altitudes, below m., from china, se asia, east to samoa, tonga. trifoliate lves with toothed margins, turning red as they die. fls small, cm diam., cream to pale green
. (colo) you (bauan ko iko) heard in the highlands of naitasiri and namosi.
. (eng.) n. cocoa. there are efforts to revive the industry . the problems have been a severely
world price, black pod disease in rainy areas, and a lack of disciplined care for the trees. there has been a lack of organised, equitable and competent marketing for export.

. n. fijian pudding of grated ivi fruit (polynesian chestnut), baked in earth oven. this is a regional food of rewa, where the tree has been common; it grows in low-lying, wet areas. also a food specialty of beqa island.
. (eng.) n. cork usually used as float for fishing line or stopper for a bottle. a piece of coconut
(qanibulu) often serves as a bottle stopper.
. v. to crow, cackle, croak, of hen, frog, parrot.
v. to clear the throat with a kind of cough.
(eng.) n. cockroach.
(eng.) n . goose, also now applied to a native bird, fiji shrikebill. geese are rarely kept in fij i.
(lau) to be playful, play a game. kakua ni kokosi! stop playing !
v., n. about to burst, of boil, pimple, blister. kovu bud. kola, kola or kolata v. to split wood, coconut, dalo with something sharp . kola rua split in two. may

to cutting up of kava, especially the way the basal stem (lewena) is chopped up into pieces for drying. kola musu, kolamusutaka v. to cut up in pieces. kolarua, kolaruataka v. to split into two pieces. similarly, this can be extended to more pieces, as in
three pieces, kolava four pieces, etc.
(eng.) n. collar. idiom: kola up , means to go about in a challenging, proud manner, often said of hoodlums, pretentious youths, ready to make trouble.
root word, used as a prefix that implies something close to happening (but usually used as an exaggeration: kolai mate see below.
mate idiom, lit. close to death, or figuratively to be "dying " with desire, as to see someone, or to eat some savoured food. syn. kolai ciba.
n. dog. the term does not derive from english "collie ". polynesians raised dogs, fed them a

starch diet, and ate them. some still eat dogs, as i have recorded from lakeba, vanua balavu, and gau island. killing was by strangulation. but the dog is sacred in quite a number of places, as with the clan nanuku-ira of the daulakeba tribe, who have a black dog as their founding spirit. a dog is the iconic animal of a fair number of tribes. fij i melanesians have no tradition of
dogs for eating but highlanders would eat almost any living thing they could catch and that

feral dogs and cats, introduced by europeans. dogs are often kept to help them in hunting pigs. fijians have almost never kept dogs (or cats) as close members of the family, as the british do. caution: in macuata, koli can refer to fish. feral or domestic dogs in fij i are sometimes subject to

caused by the scabies mite, sarcoptes scabiei, which can be treated with pyrethrin, or its synthetic equivalent, permethrin . heartworm is also a problem for dogs. idiom: lesu na koli ki na nona lua. lit. the dog returns to his vomit. i.e. the criminal returns to his crime. idiom: sa moce na koli e matadravu. lit. the dog sleep in the fireplace (where food is cooked). there is no food at home. idiom: vesu koli extremely hungry. idiom: koli ni koro lit. village dog, a person who always stays around in the village.
archaic honorific warrior title, now a common name, sometimes also an abbrev . for kolinio (colin).
(eng.) college.
n. a “fij ian sickness”, not readily identified in western medicine, often involving a persistent backache, or for women, a hardness in the abdomen, usually attributed to being chilled by being wet
throw (them) repeatedly, many times. kolotaka na tauwelu v. to quit, to throw in the towel, as in boxing, to have had enough and admit defeat, an anglicism, of course.
idiom: to drink kava in the morning, lit. as if a stick were being thrown at the sun, a waste of time. ikolo ni bogi the same, in the evening, night-time.
. (eng.) colony. ena gauna vakoloni in colonial times.
. (eng.) colon, as a punctuation mark ; a newly invented word.
. (eng.) comma, as punctuation in a sentence (iyatuvosa). again, words invented by school teachers. syn. icegu leka.
. (eng.) coma as a medical condition.
(ang.) apostrophe, as a punctuation mark in a sentence. koma-lili-rua quotation marks. words invented by teachers of fij ian language. lili to be hanging up, as of clothes on a clothes line.
formal title of a minor chief, followed by place-name, used in tailevu and cakaudrove provinces. literally, it means "he from . . .". in cakaudrove, it is pronounced 'omai.
(eng.) commander.

n. part of the cultivated yam that is cut off for cooking and eating. the other part of the midsection of the yam (na kobe-na) is the vaci, the outside parts with skin, to be planted. ta-ulu n. head of the yam, a piece to be planted. syn. dromu-na.
(or) komodoa (eng.) n. commodore, as in commodore frank bainimarama.
n., adj . communist. syn. kominisi, komunisi.
(eng.) communion, as a religious sacrament.
or komisina (eng.) n. commissioner. na komisana mai na yasayasa vakara the
western (of the government ’s western division). reference may be made to na talai veivuke ena yasayasa vakara. komisina ni ovisa police commissioner.
(eng.) n . committee.
