. n. genitals. vunitaka na matamu! cover your genitals ! (said when genitals are not properly concealed by clothes, typically when a man is seated, wearing a isulu but no underpants).

. n. front. ena matamu just in front of you. na matanivale front yard, of house. mata va glasses, or a person who wears spectacles. mata-i-va digging fork (implying four prongs). matanalevu openly, candid, without secrecy or hidden meaning. idiom: sa tawa na matana. she is pregnant.
n., v. traditional greeting pronounced outside a house to announce one ’s presence. formerly, it
extremely impolite and dangerous to approach a house silently. even today it is extremely bad manners. sa rogo na vakamata ena mata ni katuba e vale levu. the greeting was called out in front
adj . conspicuous, striking, stands out, as with striking colours on certain clothing.
(ang.) n. band, orchestra.
n. council. matabose levu vakaturaga great council of chiefs. see bose v ., n. to confer in a group, conference.
n. united nations.
n. native land trust board.
adj . squint-eyed, cross-eyed.
n. shrub six to eight feet tall, leaves that have a white underside are used as tea. leukosyke corymbulosa, urticaceae. syn. dra ni gata.
(tonga & samoa “strong wind”) name of a resort island off taveuni.
iloilo n. spectacles, glasses, or person who wears them. matailoilo ni nunu diving goggles. iloilo originally referred to a reflected image, as from a pond.
adj . adroit, skilled. matai na tuli kuro skilled in making pottery. matai na tara vale. skilled at building houses.
n. boat-builder with carpentry skills. these often formed clans (mataqali) attached to fijian tribes (yavusa), especially in coastal areas and the smaller islands of lau and cakaudrove. most were of
as mataisau, having that as a function, and even their clan name. the most significant boatbuilders were samoans who came by way of tonga, serving the tui nayau, and settled at kabara island.

first. first, as in some sport competition, or first student in class.see also isevu, the very first of an occurence, such as the fruiting of a tree, first fruits, or the first time something has ever happened. see also ikadua.
adj . detailed and fine (of a work done), done with attention to fine detail.
n., v., adv. fine work, as in weaving very finely .
adj . sloppy, coarse (as contrasted to matailalai fine, in reference to mat-weaving). kua ni matailelevutaka na nomu cakacaka. don't be sloppy in your work

n. idiom: person who talks big but cannot perform, not skilled or motivated. he undertakes work only for the pay. in earlier times, village workers building a house would be thanked with a feast, including pork (vuaka).
(anglicism) n. steel digging fork , usually with four prongs.
n. army. mataivalu-i-wai navy. mataivalu curu lo commando. mataivalu cola dakai infantry.
air force.
. n. morning. ena mataka cake morning of tomorrow, morning of the next day. ena mataka
early morning. mataka-caca extremely early in the morning. ena kida ni mataka at the break of dawn. vakamataka early (that is, morning-time). ena veimataka every morning.
. n. as in ena mataka (or) ni mataka tomorrow. ena mataka ni mataka tomorrow morning. matakarawa . (archaic) n. ceremonial presentation of goods, food, in appreciation for some kindness.

. (archaic) customary ceremony in western viti levu, presentation of plantain, coconuts at arrival of high chief, before the qaloqalovi ceremony. matakarawa . n. edible univalve shellfish, cat ’s-eye, turbo petholatus. syn. (kadavu) la.
. (modernism) n. doll as a child's plaything.
. n. carved human figure or wood or whale-tooth ; traditionally a female fertility image of an

spirit, always kept wrapped and hidden in barkcloth . all or virtually all were made by polynesians in fij i. only a few carved figures still exist, including a couple of wooden ones in the fij i museum. the museum also has a colour photo of another one that was for sale in the u.s.a., a photo donated by ronald gatty. there have been two carved of whaletooth called the drua tabua, or radini waimaro. one, sometimes referred to as the tui waimaro, remains at village nadakuni, waidina district, colo east. the other, was retained by tribe siko at village taulevu (formerly village vuniduba), matailobau district, both being people of super-tribe waimaro. the matakau at taulevu was declared missing in , after being photographed by a foreigner. the chiefly family around that time became
wealthy. one has to assume the matakau was sold away. another matakau was named nalilavatu , and kept by the tui sabeto. ultimately, in , it was given to governor arthur gordon.
carvings of people, or any other natural images. modernly, the word matakau now include carved images, such as roman catholic statuettes and the hindu gods.
n. statue, carved bust or figure, referring to a modern representation. fijians themselves
practically no carving besides making clubs and spears and some rather plain bowls, neck-rests,
for priests. the carvers of wood or whaletooth in fiji were generally tongan, samoan or maori, and later, certain fijians in lau.
n . official representative from one village or one territory to another. mataki burebesaga local
who receives visitors from burebesaga and acts as a go-between in any communications. the people are said to be veimataki.
(archaic) n. staff borne by chiefs or elders, longer than a walking stick (i titoko). being left by the entrance of a house would indicate the presence of that significant person.
(naitasiri) adj . n. “black face”, an unkind insult, sometimes said jocularly. syn. mataloa (or) mataloaloa. matalevu . adj . wide-eyed with desire.

. adj . “bug-eyed”, having large protruding eyeballs, an unkind reference to a distinctive feature of many tongans of mature age. syn. mataboto (insulting) “face like a toad”. matalevu . n. an edible river fish, to three inches in length, with very large eyes.

. n. black race, literally “black face”. fijians sometimes insult other fijians by calling them mataloa. some fijians are colour-conscious, a characteristic that long preceded the arrival of europeans. young urban women frequently use modern cosmetic creams to bleach their face to a lighter colour. fair-skinned children are often favoured. mata loaloa . n. black eye (injury).

adj . sweet, gentle-faced, lovely , pretty (girl, woman). matamata . n. gate, main entrance. prior to cession, all villages were fortified and fenced. matamata . n. goal-posts (as in football). matamata . (slang) n. messenger.
n. dance-group that performs a traditional exhibition type of dance meke.
n ., adj . sleepy-faced, sleepy head.
n., adj . pretty-face, gorgeously beautiful, of a person. syn. matavutu.
adj . haughty.
n. direction from which the wind is blowing.
(anglicism) n . electric light bulb, light bulb for an electric torch.
n. pearl. fiji has only black pearl, not gold-lip pearl. it is extremely rare to find any natural
of much value. some pearls now cultivated in fij i around nasavusavu. traditionally fijians placed no value on pearls.
n. eye of the needle.
(insult) n., adj . face like human excrement. may refer to the rectum icici itself. one does not normally pronounce these words.
(insult) n., adj . person with a face like a rectum. mata-ni-fika n. (lau) idiom : idea (in the sense of intention).
n. digit(s) , , , , , , , , , or , of a number, numerals.

n. ceremonial presentation of a formal apology, accompanied by the gift of tabua whaleteeth. lit. presentation of a reed (gasau). ro lala mara had such a presentation made at village lomanikoro, rewa, as an apology for her absence from the chiefly village while she retained a firm
to the title of roko tui dreketi. she lived away from the village and devoted little time to
duties associated with the title. in fact, she had “married away” to lau , which by custom should have released her from an attachment to her father ’s village in rewa.
n. door-face (outside surface of the door), as in tukituki ena matanikatuba knock at the
of the door, a modern custom, to gain admittance. formerly one would cry out a tama and there were no wooden doors and certainly no swinging doors of any kind.
(anglicism) n. choir, chorus (of people).
. n. sun.
. adj . eastern (of a province or territory), as in tailevu matanisiga eastern tailevu. also
matanisiga, referring to the kingdom of tonga, as distinct from places in fiji that bear the name toga.
n. nipple. may refer to rubber nipples as well as part of the human body.

adj . idiom, referring to a person, usually a child, who so relishes some food that he/she cleans up every scrap of food on a plate, licks the plate or spoon, or keep s the spoon in the mouth after eating. can also refer to someone, not used to good things, who obtains something good, tries to show off with it.
n. since cession, at cakobau ’s suggestion (according to a. b. brewster) this word has taken

to cession in a sequence of such extensive territories each endured not much longer than fifty years. laucala was one of the earliest known such territories, then verata, lau, cakaudrove and, of course, bau. in their early creation, they depended on sea-power. for bau , there was early acquisition of european mercenaries who had guns and could use them effectively. historically, the concept of matanitu is fairly recent, within the last couple of hundred years.
n . rain-drop. uca rain .
n. herald, protocol officer, who handles formalities for the chief, and is normally chosen from a clan mataqali that has that express function. he is a spokesman for the chief.

ni vola (anglicism) n. letter (of the alphabet). matanivola kala italics. matanivola levu capital letter. matanivola lailai lower-case letter. words all created by teachers of fij ian language who feel a necessity for such words in fij ian.
n. water well, spring, source of water, pond. syn. vure.
(tonga) n. . in tonga, a traditional social and kin-group who served the chief as heralds, protocol officers, and in some cases had specialised functions such as navigation. . in fiji, there are
bearing the name matapule, descendants of matapule who migrated from tonga. . title for head of clan welitoa at village dreketi, taveuni.
. n. type, class, kind. na veimataqali tamata the various types of people. na noda veimataqali kakana. our (many of us) kinds of food. na mataqali tei the type or species of plantings.

. n. clan, more inclusive than the extended family (itokatoka, or in parts of the west bito, or in lau, bati ni lovo) and less inclusive than the tribe (yavusa). mataqali have a definite kin-group origin
the yavusa are often the result of political aggregation, only sometimes (as with super-tribe
in namosi, or super-tribe waimaro in the viti levu highlands) related by kinship. the

is often blurred in fij ian society . historically, native land commissioner maxwell attempted to define and standardise these groupings for the purpose of assigning title to native lands. in fact, fijians do not much use these terms in identifying the level of their own social group. in eastern coastal areas, mataqali usually serve definite roles and functions in the larger society of the village and

empower the chiefs (na sau). other functions are as protocol officers and emissaries (matanivanua), warriors (bati), priests (bete), fishermen (gonedau), boat builders (matai or mataisau), commoners (lewe-ni-vanua). there are far fewer different functions in the highlands where the "men ’s house" (bure) was the basic social group and there were not necessarily any tribes (yavusa) as such,

source_text: and no use of the word mataqali
target_text: for clans. highlander men of the bure all slept together, side by side,

source_text: one or more of the clans may be original
target_text: settlers and landowners (itaukei ni qele) who then accepted

immigrants as chiefs, as warriors, or merely as dependents.. fijians usually feel a closer attachment to their clan, rather than the tribe but they do not often differentiate these social divisions. when

say "we" (keitou, referring to themselves, their own people) they are usually speaking of their clan. clans by the same name exist in various parts of fiji. they may not be functionally related any more, having split off some of their family groups who moved away due to internicine disputes or in a
for more land. many clans have become extinct. others have been functionally merged into larger clans though land records may record them as distinct.
. n. relationship of two regions where the people may refer to people of the other region as
or mataqali and address them as such. implied is a common origin. today these relationships,
specific, have now become generalised between to whole provinces, for example ra province and naitasiri province.
adj . cunning look.
n. band, orchestra.
n . team (sports). qito play. syn. timi.
adj . cross-eyed, eyes with a squint.
n. beach landing, shore.
adj ., n. squint, squinting.
v. to represent (as an ambassador represents a nation, or sportspeople represent their country).

n. race (of humans). veimata tamata n. various races of mankind. na idabedabe vakamatatamata communal (i.e. racial) seat, in political elections. this is in contrast to the “open” seats (open to any race) idabedabe veicurumaki.
adj . unable to cope well, unfortunate, a failure, of a person.
adj . extremely insulting term, usually referring to a white man, lit. with a face like a boar's testicles.
adj . clear (statement, question, attitude -- not a liquid or other object). vakamatata-taka v. to
(a matter). matau . on the right-hand side. ki matau to the right. ki mawi to the left.

. adj . adroit, adept, experienced, capable, accustomed to something. matau ena vosa adept at speaking. ena vanua e dau mamatau kina in the place he is accustomed to be. idiom : o sa matau tiko ? jocular, rhetorical question, you think you can carry that off? what makes you think you can do that?
. n. axe, a polynesian or proto-polynesian development, only as specialised adzes, used mainly
stone sinkers (vatu-kata-i-lawa) for river nets to catch the fish ika loa (cestraeus pliatilis) as
efforts. metal axes came via tonga, from tongans and early european traders who were
vatu n. stone-axe, today also an idiom for a person, old-fashioned, ignorant , "stone age "; fijian

use the term, referring to parents and elders who remain in the villages and do not adjust to modern times, modern values. some of the earliest fij ian settlers of the highlands did not have stoneaxes or any chisels. these so-called kaicolo were a pre-stone age, more melanesian culture.
( slang) n. person who wears glasses ("four eyes"), an unkind reference.
(insult) refers to a person as an asshole; lit. with a face like a rectum sona.
n. court of law. mataveilewai e cake high court.
(anglicism) n. native lands commission, which investigates matters of native
rights and chiefly titles. its decisions are definitive and authoritatively binding though disputes

titles may be referred to a tribunal. necessarily, much of the formal investigations (veitarogi vakavanua) is incomplete, contains errors and omissions, and has included a great deal of biased, selfinterested testimony from only some of the relevant elders who were present at the hearings. elders
asked to record and swear to their testimony of land ownership and history in what is referred to

itukutuku raraba for each tribe or clan . deliberations have been difficult and sometimes quite arbitrary in the face of conflicting versions of oral history, complexity of the issues involved, and limited time for deliberation. in some case the n.l .c. staff have not had the local knowledge to make proper determinations. in earlier times the power of the club was the main determinant of chiefly titles
for study. pandora’s box awaits being open for study and criticism. at the present time,
a specific social group may gain access to records of their own group. because knowledgable elders are now long dead, there is really no hope for easy clarity. part of the problem lies in
considerably and most of the land was a vast no-man ’s land, too dangerous to be habitable.
to make a decision, commissioner maxwell defined the primary landholding unit to be the
(mataqali) and that simplification has caused problems. social divisions and the names for them
considerably around fiji but smaller family units would have been more appropriately listed

custodians of the land. there was no permanent ownership in the sense that europeans understand, only usufruct, a right to use the land. it is a further complication in that many chiefs and elders considered that they alone had total control of the land, including the right to sell it, give it, or assign it to whomever they liked. it has been a fabrication to impose the notion that the land belonged to the people. curiously also, the notion persists, even today, that native land is to remain native land, forever
in common. in fact the original land ordinance of stipulates that communal land rights

“desirable until the native race be ripe for a division of such community rights among individuals . . .” governor arthur gordon never intended that native land should remain forever communal property .
n. methodist group of youngsters who plan some activities together. the purpose is religious and social, involving girls and boys.

n. mask for the face. very anciently crude masks were occasionally made of vegetation, sticks and leaves, sometimes with added human hair, used by men in some ceremonial dances. some served to conceal one’s identity in combat.
n. shore, place where boats approach and anchor. na matavura kei suva . the shore of suva.
n., adj . beauty, beautiful (usually referring to a woman ’s face). vakamatavutu adv. beautifully (in this sense).
n. death, sickness, disease. v. to die. sa mate o koya he/she is dead. mate ni veiyacovi venereal disease. mate ni suka diabetes. mate ni uto heart disease. mate ni vakasama mental illness. na
na aids the aids disease. siga ni mate good friday. tauvimate adj ., n. sick, sickness. sickness often meant death to early fij ians. they did not always draw a sharp distinction. people aged

hospital, more modernly called vale ni bula. syn. bale to die, of a chief. by ext., mate may mean exhausted, dead tired, finished, about to give up, as from great effort, usually work or even love-making when a person is sated. syn. (respectful) toki yani. idiom: mate vakabalabala to die without progeny. lit. die like a fern-tree (balabala). fij ians knew

well who can eat at two different houses but might die of hunger if one eats only at one’s own family house. vakamate, vakamatea v. to cause death, to kill. e rawa ni veivakamatei. it is possible to die from it. au a tovolea meu vakamatei au. i tried to kill myself. (suicide has been traditionally very rare among fijians.) veivakamatei n., v. killing(s), manslaughter, to die from some deadly cause. beitaki ena cala ni veivakamatei accused of the the crime of manslaughter.
v. to desire, lit. to be dying for (something desired, such as a food, some object, an experience).
a loved one that (figuratively) one would die for. mateci koya die for him/her. in
a slice across his own neck ; the girl will understand that he pretends he will kill himself if she does not yield to his affections. there are the usual accompanying smiles and laughter.
n. infectious disease (as a generality). dewa transfer.
adj . sickly.

n. weakness. au kila na nomu matemate. i know your weaknesses (i know how to appeal to you.) mateni . adj . drunk, inebriated (from alcohol, or excessive yaqona). the term is indigenous and formerly applied only to yaqona. (formerly , fij ians had no alcohol and no other intoxicants.) yaqona intoxication can occur only with considerable consumption of the beverage in fairly strong form. it affects
coordination but not mental acuity. some people become addicted to yaqona with resulting social irresponsibility and affliction of a skin condition called kanikani.
. n. (eng.) mutton. low-grade, fatty mutton from new zealand has been one of the common foods bought by urban fijians.
n. stomach ache. syn. mosi ni kete.
n. headache. syn. mosi ni ulu.
n. (of women) menstruation, monthly period. formerly, women used moss or barkcloth as menstrual pads.

v. sick with infectious malady (flu, cold, viral infection etc.) veitauvi ena matetaka. afflicted with matetaka. syn. (lau, rewa) bacataka. mate vou adj . of fruit usually, dropped prematurely before ripe, unusable.
adj . useless, futile effort, usually to arrange for something that does not happen.
n. low tide, tide that has ebbed. used only in certain expressions: sa di na mati. the tide is out.
very low tide. mati ruku n. morning low tide. mati yakavi n. evening low tide. sa mati na vanua. it is low tide. sa ua levu. it is high tide. references to an incoming tide (so na ua) may imply
n., adj . low water, shallow.
adj . crazy, mad (related to the tide being out). ruku underneath. syn. lialia.
adj . scratched, and thus damaged, of a thing (pot, glassware), a person or animal, such as a horse on barbed wire.
(or) matumatu n. a common small silver fish to ten inches by the shore caught on lb line with size hook with bait of kasikasi or prawn, gerres macrosoma or g. oyena, gerridae, silver biddy.
is a small form of this fish. matu-sa is larger, to inches, around reef, or in lagoons at clear patches, caught by net, or or two at a time from small boat.
adj . mature, of fruit, crops, fully developed but not yet fully ripe. yalo matua responsible, no longer childishly irresponsible. gu-matua earnest. ulumatua eldest child.
(vanua levu): sa ma ’ua na raisi. no problem, nothing to worry about, everything is “set”, lit. the rice (raisi) crop is mature (ma ’ua) so there will be plenty of food.
(anglicism) n. script, lettering, alphabet. both fij ian and english languages are written in
script, that is, using a version of roman lettering. a different script would be hindi script for the hindi language. matuavosa is a word invented by schoolroom teachers.
v. to gamble, to contest, match up, to take a position (as in making a decision), to confirm: sa mau
nona lewa. his/her decision is confirmed. sa mau na veivosaki it was confirmed in discussion. syn. dei (implying being fixed, firm.).
n. “pieces” of a game, such as cards, or domino pieces, or the “men” on a chessboard.
v. to play some game (not an active, physical sport), such as cards, typically tarabu or warotu,
of “trump”, played with two or four people. vota yalima deal out five cards each. esi ace.
or tevoro joker. turaga king. marama queen. j eke j ack. daimani diamond. kalavo club.
spade. yate heart (yate is literally “liver”, the centre of courage for fijians.)
(anglicism) n., v. to gamble for money. this is a formal, stilted expression. the notion is
a major lottery has become established that attracts poor people with dreams, especially in urban areas.
(tonga, “fakamau”) n., v . formal and official marriage, to marry. the suffix mau might imply

to some sort of inquiry and became adapted for this use in christianity. in fiji the older, more traditional word is veitube, and also vakawati. anciently there were no great formal marriage ceremonies, though there might be a feast when a chief took an important woman into his household. formerly, the main point was for the man to provide housing for the woman and the children she might then have. the word for this is vaka-vale-taka , to provide housing. custom evolved to bring a whaletooth to request the woman , or after an elopement, to bring one in a ceremony of informing the woman ’s parents, and another, later, begging forgiveness bulubulu. rejection of the suitor is indicated
another whaletooth. many arrangements today are informal, outside the authority of a church, and referred to as vakawati. o rau na vakamau the newlywed couple (formally married). o

the husband and wife (formally married or just living together). idiom: tiko vakasuva (or) tiko vakasamoa living together, of man and woman, without a formal arrangement. certain liberties are possible in the city that would not be allowed in the village.
adj . rich in the sense of being ample, meaningful, elaborate, as of a speech.
adj . spoiled, wasted (as of food, fuel, or some work).
refers to a hilltop that is dry, barren. name of a village near bau island. people of maumi were early settlers on nayau island, lau province.
v. to sulk, pout.
(or) maue adj . noisy, of a crowd.
adj ., n. constipated, constipation, bloated, flatulence. see guguraki.
adj ., v. healed, to heal, of a cut, wound. mavomavo dredre difficult healing. imavomavo scar.
n., adj . injured, wounded (person), damaged (goods). mamavoavoa very badly injured. vakamavoa-taka to injure (someone).
(eng.) n. marble(s). veimavolo n. boys’ game of marbles. two types: in one there is a circle

on the ground, in the other, there is a central pit that is dug that is called a “pillow”. toa n. large marble used for shooting; smallest marbes are referred to as de ni me (goat droppings, from their

shape and size) or “kind one” while middle sized marbles are “kind two”. vana na mavolo shoot the marble; this is done with a thumb on the ground, forefinger against the marble, flicking that forefinger with the other hand. (it is not done by holding the hand as a fist and flicking with the thumb
might be more common with european children .) while it is normal for the thumb to be on the

(“clean down”), one may by announcing it in advance, shoot from the knee or stooping posture (“five-eighth”, so called), or from a standing position (tu cake). rules are to be followed strictly and violations may well lead to a scuffle.

n. timber tree endemic to fiji, only known on southern coast of viti levu, gonystylus punctatus a.c. smith, gonystylaceae. globose woody fruit, - cm diam., - segments with smooth seeds, white fls clustered at the end of branches, thick shiny, simple, alternate leaves.
n. the pounded mash of cooked starch-foods (taro, breadfruit, cassava, plantain), used to make fijian puddings (vakalolo). waki, wakia na mavu mix the mavu with a stick iwaki. sa wakiwaki na
the mavu is sticky, gummy. sa tata-ciqiciqi na mavu the mavu is lumpy. mono, monoka na

form balls of the mavu. kini, kinita na mavu pinch off the mavu into balls. the cultivated rootcrop yam uvi is never used for fijian puddings. in coastal areas and some small islands, uvi is the most noble of the “true foods” kakana dina.

n. poisonous plant, antiaris toxicaria var. macrophylla, shrub or tree in lowland rain forest areas, the latex used for arrows but mostly for food poison, especially by priestly castes in coastal areas (such as tailevu) where the tree was often to be found growing around temples and in villages in
it on arrows. (and tongans never used bows and arrows in war.) the more potent variety toxicaria of this species has been widely used as poison in southeast asia. in fiji, a more common poison
super-tribe waimaro was the shrub lobau, formerly mixed with kava to be consumed unwittingly by the victim. it is an introduced plant related to datura. it disables a man. he would then be

with a club. the fij ian dictionary na ivolavosa vakaviti lists macaranga vitiensis, euphorbiaceae, as having the name mavu ni toga; i have been unaware of that as a fact, and it is not so listed as such in a . c. smith flora vitiensis. nonetheless, it may be correct. mawa v., n., adj . stink, off-flavour, spoiled (of food). idiom: (vulgar) gusu mawa! stink mouth !
n. tracks, trace, as of an animal, or human, as in footprint. syn. we ni yava-na. may refer scars or residual effects of strong winds or even fire.
n. (anglicism) fingerprints. syn. we ni liga-na.

left, on the left-hand side. ki mawi to the left. as a n. may refer to a left-handed person, sometimes with the implication that they are different, doing things "opposite", in a different and sometimes difficult way. left-handed people were regarded with suspicion, often avoided as somewhat dangerous. e
in a fight, a “left”, a left-handed punch.
(eng.) n. may (month). na vula o me the month of may.
. preceding a pronoun (not “you”), me indicates a suggestion, polite request or implicit command: me daru lako. let’s go (us two). meu lako ? should i go?
. indicates an obligation, something that should be done, something that should be. meu (or me ’u) lako. i should go. na cava meu cakava ? what should i do? me vakasakei na minisita the minister

sacked. o cei me toboka rawa ? who can (should) catch him? tukuna vua me kana. tell him/her to eat. me rua ga. only two (in response to a question as to how many of something are needed or desired). me . particle between an adjective and a verb. dredre me cakava. difficult to do.. me . before a noun, for the purpose of, to serve as. solia vei koya me kena. give it to him/her, as food to eat. me . n. (onomatopoeic) n. goat. there are wild goats on some islands such as cikobia, in lau province. kadavu is usually associated with goats, which are joked about. idiom: luve ni me lit. son of a goat, a derogatory but usually j ocular way of addressing a person from kadavu. also me damu! the damu implies brown or auburn colour, from heavy tongan influence in kadavu.

prefix indicating a beverage to be consumed. the suffix serves as a possessive pronoun indicating who will consumer the beverage. the possessive pronoun may stand alone without naming the actual beverage, or the beverage may be named after the pronoun. for fijians, beverages include fruits such
mango, melon, citrus, pineapple, and ice cream. (they often tend to suck fruits, rather than treat them as a solid food.)
my beverage, for me to consume.
our (two) beverage for us two to consume.
our (three or so) beverage for us to consumer.
our (many) beverage for us to consume.
