(rob wright ’s information from fisheries experts.) walui, waluiya v. to scrape voivoi leaves or sedge leaves (usually with a sharp mussel shell), to soften and stretch the leaves prior to weaving mats. the spelling of this word varies.
adj . wonderful, wondrous, delightful. this word is often an exclamation. wananavu! great ! splendid ! perfect ! syn. daumaka!
n . fishing line, a concept from central polynesia.

n. umbilical cord. vicovico n. navel. wanono, wanonova . v. to stare, regard fixedly. it is normal for local children to stare relentlessly at strangers, and follow them around. wanono, wanonova . v. keep a close eye on, examine closely, continue to scrutinize. wanonova matua sara na ka oqo. keep a very close eye on this thing. ena wanono tiko ko vuravura. the world will be watching. waqa, waqaca, waqara v. to light, lit (fire, lamp), burning. me waqa na cina. please light the lamp .
waqa na buka. the fire is lit. waqawaqa ni buka n. piece of burning wood that can be used for lighting a fire. see caudre.

. n. boat. dau-ta-waqa boat-builder. (cakobau ’s boat-builder was an american black, probably earlier a ship ’s carpenter.) syn. (tonga) vaka . idiom: waqa vata (anglicism) lit. “in the same boat”, enduring the same conditions.

. (anglicism) n . envelope (as for letters). waqa ni lokoloko pillow-case. such soft pillows were unknown to fijians, but adopted from tonga. waqa . (anglicism) n. book-cover. waqa vavaku kaukauwa hardcover. waqa malumulumu soft-cover.
n., adj . sickly, often sick, weak.
n. filiarasis infection that ultimately, after about ten years, may result in elephantiasis (tauna)
(anglicism) n. aeroplane. rara ni waqavuka or iroro ni waqavuka airfield, aeroport. vuka to fly.

. n. residence or visible form as taken by a spirit kalou or kalou vu that may exist in a rock, or sometimes in an animal such as a dog, shark. waqawaqa . adj . wide eyed with fury, of facial appearance.
(west) v., n. game. syn. qito.
adj . extremely skinny (person, animal), “skin and bones”. this is thought to be an unhealthy condition. it may refer to a thin and weak plant. of fruit, dried out, wasted.
(eng.) n. warrant, summons (court).
(regional: ra) no, not. syn. warai, sega. idiom: ’auria se wara! take it or leave it ! idiom: wara me soa not a good match (do not belong together).
(regional: kadavu, rewa, namosi) no, not. syn. sega.
v. to wait for. waraka na basi wait for the bus; waraki au wait for me. wawa! wait !
to wait with anticipation. idiom: waraka qai namuka! exclamation: it is futile to wait for it !
v., n. to sting painfully, as by a switch or perhaps a burn.

v., adj . to be agile, quick in physical response; may apply to a hyper-active child. syn. waritorito. waro, waroca, warolaka v. to whack with a thin stick, usually hitting a child as punishment. iwaro n.
stick so used, but may apply to a golf club. qito wawaro a rather affected, precious term for the game of golf.

n. fijian card-game with four players, or two, a version a “trump” tarabu. see veimau. waru, waruta, waruka v. to stroke with the fingers, snot from the nose, leaflets from the edible ota fern, cured vanilla beans to straighten and smoothen them. syn. wadru, wadruca.
v., n., adj . to sting, cause pain. by ext. may apply figuratively to stinging words, admonitions.
v., n., adj . extremely powerful (sporting team, strength of sun ’s rays, etc.), to do something powerfully.
(colo east) n. small wild terrestrial fern used as a condiment in place of salt which was usually
in the highlands. highlanders consider this condiment to be superior to salt. not yet
botanically . curiously, this is also the name of a clan at sabeto, western viti levu. (the local chief, apisai tora, notable retired politician, does not know any meaning for that clan name.)
n. open ocean, deep ocean.
n. sea, ocean.

v., n., adj . very wrinked, as of elderly person. salulu wrinkled, as of aged skin . see sanuki crinkled or wrinkled. wase, wasea . v. to divide. in addition to the general meaning, this is commonly used for the dividing up
a food-presentation, before it is given out, a very common custom of ceremonies. it requires
judgement to share out food or goods to the satisfaction of all recipients. wase-i-rua,

v. to divide in two. waseitolu divided in three. wasei vakatautauvata vei keda. divided equally with us. erau sa veitawasei vakadua. they () have divorced, separated permanently. see vota v . to share out. wase, wasea . v. to sort out, classify, arrange in coherent types or amounts, put together those things that belong together. wase, wasea v. to discriminate, that can include ethnic or gender discrimination. syn. vakaduidui-taka.
a new notion to be talked about in fij i, and a new use of the word wasea . kua ni wasea na mata tamata. (modernism) don ’t discriminate people on the basis of race. see veiwasei, below.
v. to discriminate. kua ni dau veiwasei ena soli veivuke. don ’t discriminate when distributing aid.

v. to share out or divide up carelessly , without careful judgement. vakatawase n. new year’s day . this implies the division of the years, though years were never counted. children may go about banging on tins; if they approach a house they may expect food, cake or candy, perhap s money. iwase . n. portion from a division of things, such as food at a ceremonial food presentation (magiti). iwase . n. food served and eaten , in conjunction with drinking of yaqona, usually eaten after the yaqona is drunk. iwase . n. chapter (book), something divided off.
n. share (as something is divided up), portion allotted.
n. (anglicism) term of school.
ni yaqona (vakaturaga) n. formal ceremony presenting uncooked food, usually part of series of
welcoming a chief. the original notion was that the food would counter-balance the drinking of yaqona though food is not eaten at the ceremony itself.

(or) wa-seisei (archaic) n. chiefly necklace of finely split whaletooth, now seen only in museums. these were made by tongans. bauans gave them to highland chiefs who would cooperate with their purpose of bauan domination with acceptance of christianity. "wash-down " (eng, slang) n., v. to drink alcohol, usually beer, after a session of drinking yaqona. yaqona may potentiate the effects of alcohol.
adj . dried out, shrunken, shriveled, of a person, sick or old, or of an object, such yaqona, copra, or a dried fruit that has been exposed to the sun.
frequently, often, quite a bit.
n. plaited sinnet cord attached to head of yaqona serving bowl (tanoa) and stretched out in
of important guest or chief. at the head of the tanoa there are attached two white cowry
and one is attached to the distal end of the cord, closer to the guest(s). this is symbolic of a
with two testicles. it it forbidden for anyone to walk in front of the tanoa. (at informal occasions, if necessary to cross in front, one would walk bowed down, and touch the bowl in passing.)
of this formality and ceremony, and the tanoa itself are tongan introductions though the watabu itself is a fij ian innovation. tongan bowls had the wooden nubbin but not the sinnet cordage.
adj . very lovely, sweet, of singing voice(s). syn. memela sara.
(archaic) n. very emotional, erotic dance of women, welcoming successful warriors with their

(corpses for cannibal food). syn. dele. wati-na n. spouse. also refers to a cross-cousin (tavale) of the opposite sex, a preferred marriage partner, but not yet married. formerly, future marriage partners were sometimes selected for children. if a man
a young woman may become violent if a fij ian man courts her without serious intentions.

(vakamau) in church or civil registers is not always thought necessary except within traditional villages. as it now occurs in many other countries, fijian couples may live together without any formal arrangements in urban areas. they may marry later or just remain as “partners”.

n. couple(s) of married people or co-habiting man and woman. vakawati v., adj . to take a spouse, usually with no formal ceremony. all that is required is to live together (tiko vata), and after a time (in the case of young couples) for the man to present a whaletooth to the

of the woman, a ceremony of bringing a whaletooth ibulubulu, asking forgiveness. in rural areas, if a man takes a young woman away from home for a night, he is considered as having married her. for modern ceremonies of formal marriage (with church, service and probably also, civil registry)
married by civil registry. vakawati vasamoa (or) vakawati vasuva just living together as a couple, in common-law marriage or as “partners”.

(archaic) n. general word for wooden war-club. specific types had specific names. iula throwing club. other types: bowai, gade (pole club s), cali (bladed club), totokia (“pineapple” club), kiakavo (spur club, often used in meke).
n. hibiscus fibre or cordage, from the inner bark of these small vau trees, used in tying parcels, tying up crabs or fish or fruit.

v ., n., adj . restless, hyper-active, cannot sit still, of a child. wavoki, wavokita v. to go around a place. au a wavokiti lautoka i went around lautoka. o laki ivei? wavoki ga. where are you going? just going around. e rawa ni kau wavoki. it can be carried around, is portable. rai wavoki look around. e wavokita na vale e dua na bai. a fence surrounds the house.
person with no fixed job or address, a drifter. syn. yavoki, yavokita. see wavoliti and voli, volita.
n. roundabout, place to turn around (as for a car). sala wavoki roundabout, indirect path (the more traditional meaning).
n. (anglicism) round (as in boxing). ena katolu ni wavoki in the third round. syn. (eng.) rauni.
around. era vakaitikotiko wavoliti korovou. they (many) live around korovou.
. (eng.) n. wharf, jetty.
. (eng.) n. bridge (usually a substantial one). wavu lili n. suspension bridge, hanging bridge such as the one that formerly crossed the tovu river at village nalele, nadroga province.
. v. to stand upright, still (of a person, as in standing watchfully, or supporting a post, or a soldier at attention). see also wavusasa. sa wavu mai na drau ni uluna. his/her hair raised in fear.
(eng.) n. pumpkin. syn. wavukeni, p ap ukini.
sasa v. to be standing around with erect posture. if others are seated nearby, this could be considered disrespectful.
n. intestines. syn. wewe. wawa, waraka v. to wait, waiting. waraki koya . wait for him/her .
n. feast to welcome someone who is awaited.
adj . interim, temporary, tentative. na matanitu tu vakawawa the interim government. na
the temporary or tentative approval.
adj . tired out (after some effort, work), worn out physically, of the whole body, or arms or legs, from exertion. syn. wawa.
(eng.) n., v. wire. na waya ni talevoni. the telephone wire. waya votovotoa n. barb-wire. waya
n. electric wire. idiom: sa bau waya it ’s very difficult.

n. trace, footprint, scar. na we ni mavoa the scar (of the injury). na we ni yava footprints (yava foot, leg). we ni liga n. fingerprint (liga hand). wede, wedeva v. to flirt, act up, trying to be cute, showing off, usually to person(s) of opposite sex .
n., adj . flirting. lauan: makamaka . wedru adj . soggy and soft, as of wet hair, food, or perhaps wet clothing or a wet mat. syn. sauwelu.
n. family relative, colleague, associate. this includes people with any affiliation or association,
all people who are recognized as part of the extensive social network. na wekana voleka the
(again a vastly wider network than that recognized by europeans).
v., n., adj . related by family or traditional relationship among different clans or tribes. na

n. the relatives (in fiji that may include a very great number of people). in a sense, everybody is related to everybody else. wele v., adj . idle, inactive; quiet, unconcerned, have the mind at ease (usually after tension), unmotivated
v., n. to pacify a child, usually with a lullaby.
v. to relax, take it easy. na veika e rawa me vakawelei kina na yaloda. things that can relax
(many) minds. wele, weletaka v. to neglect. eda weletaka na noda itavi. we (many) neglect our duty.
n. toy, plaything, anything that helps one relax, such as hobby equipment.
adj . idle, relaxed, doing nothing. vakawelewele v. to malinger, be neglectful, to neglect. me da kua ni vakawelewele. let us (many) not be neglectful. na vakawelewele the neglect, carelessness.

n. papaya, carica papaya, caricaceae. syn. (rewa, lau) maoli, (lau) leweti. introduced by europeans. green fruit eaten cooked by lauans. leaves and sap used as meat tenderiser though fijians rarely bother. mostly the fruit grows where seeds have been discarded, often near cement or concrete,
the plant does not thrive in acid soil. trees are almost all male or female, some hermaphrodite. only one male is needed for ten or more females. fijians believe that cutting into a

tree may convert it to the more useful female. tests made of this have not been successful. fruits year-round. skin of papaya fruit is used to treat boils known as soso, which is really a carbuncle. syn. (nadro, west, macuata) wi.
n. saliva, spittle. luka nasal mucus.

adj . slimy. were, werea to garden, clean away weeds. werekoro v., n. to clean up the village as a community task, often for some special occasion, or as routine work. idiom: were ubiubi deceptively to make like one is weeding, but in fact merely knocking the grass down, from laziness failing to cut the grass properly. often used figuratively, for pretending to work at something.
(or) veiwere n. yam garden.
(west) n. house, formerly with thatching that makes the house appears rounded in shape despite its rectangular interior. syn. vale.
v. to repeat oneself, telling the same story over and over again, especially passing along rumours and gossip.
(lau) v., adj . n . keep repeating, tiresomely. “run off at the mouth”.
n. guts of shellfish, the part that is not eaten.
n. exhibition war dance (meke wesi) in which men dancers each brandishing a spear and a fan. the

could be protective against hurled weapons but mostly signifies nonchalance in the face of the enemy. this dance features mainly in vanua levu, though in legend, it is a dance of the gremlins (na iveli) of viti levu.

ni gusu-na idiom, as in: sa iwewe ni gusumu. you are always talking, thinking only about it/him/her. something has impressed or fascinated the person, focussing their attention. wi n. a semi-cultivated tree-fruit, to altitude meters, and thus unknown to highlanders in early times, spondias dulcis, anacardiaceae, relished by fijians, fruiting around april, may, august to december. fls small, white. probably aboriginal introduction. firm fleshed, it is too sour for most europeans. the very firm, yellowish flesh is sweet only very close to the prickly kernel. skin of the fruit remains green

or turns yellowish, orange. indians especially favour the fruit for pickles. vili wi to gather wi fruit. (vili, vilika to pick up, gather). lves used to flavour meat; they have distinctive fruity smell when crushed. the bark is chalky, grey-brown, trunk is smooth and sometimes difficult to climb . syn. wikacu, wi ’acu. idiom: vili wi to lose out badly (sports, any competitive activity), with the implication of getting only the leftovers fallen on the ground. the “winner” climbs the tree and gets the best fruit. in fact, fijians often rej ect fruit fallen on the ground, even if it is edible. wili, wilika . (anglicism) v. to read. syn. wilivola (properly perhaps, wili ivola). wili, wilika . v. to count. wili leca v. to mis-count.

adj . infinite, uncountably large number. wili-seva, wilisevataka v . to miscount. syn. wili leca. idiom: wiliseva na yalewa kalou vast number, so big that literally, a woman-spirit could not count it.
(eng.) n. wheelbarrow. wili n. wheel. wili-gusu, wiligusutaka (anglicism) v. to read out loud, to recite.
(anglicism) n. census. tabana ni wilivanua census department.
(anglicism) n. v . to read. vale ni wilivola (ivola) n. library.
n. total count, total number added up. sa mai toka na iwiliwili. the count has reached .

adj . quantitative. wini, winitaka (eng.) v. to win, a word often used in sports. idiomatically, this can mean for a man to succeed in having sex with a woman, or perhap s, the woman with a man. wiri, wirica, wiricaka, wirilaka v. to spin, twist forcibly something that is held in the hand. fast
action is also implied in the verb cowiri-taka to make something spin. coco wiriwiri to be spinning, rolling around. vakaso wiriwiri to be twirled, or spiralled as with the shape of a screw.
v. to be made to feel dizzy .
v. to draw a circle, as in responding to a questionnaire, or in checking the proper answer to question on an exam paper. wirina na isau ni taro circle the answer to the question.
. n. gyrocarpus americanus, hernandiaceae, introduced physic nut, shrub in wet zone, tree in
zone where it thrives; soft and useless wood, poisonous fruit (dangerous to curious children).
medicinal, used for diarrhoea. cuttings used as living fence-posts, and for support and shade for cultivated vanilla vines.
. n. a soft-wood timber tree of coast and inland forest, thespesia populnea, malvaceae, also
called mulomulo. easily cut and often used by tuvalu people at kioa island for simple,
canoes (bavelo). both fijian names refer to a spinning action of the two-winged seeds that float down, rotating as they fall.
. (anglicism) n. dial, as on a radio, clock, electric or electronic device that is twisted to adjust it.
n., adj . sour, acidity.
rugby sevens (seven men on a side). yatolu na tiaina three bananas each. e yatolu na dola na kena isau. three dollars each is the price.
(lau) n. mat. syn. ibe.
v. to lie (falsehood), lie about. yaba, yabaca v. to hold something next to a fire; warm something by holding it next to a fire, sometimes to smooth out wrinkles of cloth or matting.
n. year. former meaning was annual harvest (mainly of yams, which figured in traditional fijian
calendars, beginning late february or march), the “months” being separated approximately by natural phenomena relating to gardening work or marine harvests. see the end pages of this book for
of this indigenous lunar calendar. ena veiyabakai every year. vakayabaki annual(ly). o sa yabaki vica ? how old are you? (to a child). na cauravou yabaki the -year old youth. na tamata
vata the people of the same age. early fijians never counted months or years and the
of “week” did not exist for them. they knew their age not in number of years but only as
or less than others of the village, especially their siblings. or they might say they were born

or after a certain well known public event. kakana ni yabaki n. seasonal food. yabaki balavu (anglicism) n. leap year. yabaki ni bula n. age (of a person). fijians normally report their age by the next year, not the last year, as in european custom. yabe, yabeta v. to walk, stroll unencumbered. o ira na yabe those (many) who marched (as in a public demonstration). tayabe march , marchers, parade. yabe vakawelewelei to stroll casually, idly, with no
in mind. ya (or) yaya migration of land crabs toward the sea around november, december, for spawning in saltwater. na iyabeyabe n. the strolling, the stroll
n. starch-flour (and by extension) the arrowroot plant, “true” yabia, tacca leontopetalides, taccaceae, and less commonly t. maculata, more often referred to as yabia sa in fij i. the root can be

source_text: poisonous but was eaten usually in the form of
target_text: a well washed, flour-based pudding, especially in dry,

areas at low altitudes where it grows best. hardly ever cultivated, yabia grows semi-wild in drier areas of tailevu, other parts of fij i but less common and even unknown in the interior, and where there is high rainfall. t. maculata is not found at sandy beach areas but rather in the dry hilly country
meters. the true yabia grows widely throughout the pacific from india across the eastern polynesia. it may have reached fiji naturally or, as john parham suggested, have been introduced to
by polynesians who long ago favoured arrowroot as a more important food than it ever was to melanesians.
. (regional) cassava, an introduced american plant that has assumed great importance in the fijian diet. name copied from the arrowroot name, possibly because both can be used to make starch.
loa refers to cassava starch, often used after laundry, to starch clothes in modern european context.
ni vavalagi n. arrowroot, west indian arrowroot, maranta arundinaceae, marantaceae, origin in

and central america, an early introduction to fij i, but not common and not grown or used by fijians. this is the commercial species on the world market, used for arrowroot flour and arrowroot biscuits. yabo, yabora (ra) to kiss (traditional sniffing, nose to side of nose, or face). syn. regu, reguca. such
island sniffing may be done on greeting or farewelling friends, relatives, and formerly, to

a corpse in a ceremony called ireguregu. these days for babies and live adults, light cheekkissing or forehead-kissing tends to replace sniffing. yabo, yaboca v. to pass the hand over, touching lightly, as if checking something.
n. (obsolete) man who has traditional role of handling the body of a dead chief, in only some areas
such as the noemalu of viti levu. bouta or bauta serves in some places as a synonym; it is the function of one kin-group.

n. name. na yacamu your name; na yacaqu my name. vakayacana v. to name. vakatokayacataka to decide on a name, formally give a name (usually to a person, boat, house-site), normally done with ceremony. vakatokayacataki vei seru named after seru (or for seru). for many names one must

source_text: ask permission to use it if
target_text: some other people feel that they own the name na yacana vakavuku n. the
(this of course, a modernism). see vakatoka.
n. namesake. nomu yaca your namesake (who may be addressed as yaca). there were no
some fij ians began to follow that european custom. but in many cases both the
and the family name might be given to someone quite outside the family. formerly, a child was never given the name of its parent. before christian times a person might be given different
at different stages of life and even after death. if someone has been given the name of your
you may address that person as father tamaqu. also, one’s paternal uncles (father ’s brother) are considered as one’s father.

v. to bear a common name, as for example, in referring to all races of fij i citizens as “fijians” or all white people as europeans. yaca, yaca, yacaraka v. to grate (cassava, other root crops), scrub (laundry). yacaraka to scrub hard but by ext., may mean to beat up a person. syn. solo. yaco, yacova . v. to happen, occur, take place, become. n i yacovi iko na karamaca . . . when you

. . . . . ena yaco ni na dave na dra. it will end up with bloodshed (lit., when blood will flow). see vakayaco, vakayacora v. to cause to happen . yaco, yacova . until, reach (in time), as in me yacova. me yacova nikua up until today. me yacova mai

up until this month. me yavoca na macawa ka tu mai until next week. yaco, yacova . v. to arrive, extend to, reach (a place). yacova na takete reach the target, achieve the goal. au a yaco mai ena noa. i arrived here yesterday. yaco vata arrive together. me vosa ga ena ka e yacova nona kila . he should only speak about what he knows. idiom: eda na yaco vata ga ki namuka. lit. we (many) will arrive together at namuka (at the same time, though by different boats), implying that haste or some improvement will not affect the outcome. you do it your way, i’ll do it mine. it makes no difference. vakayaco, vakayacora v. to bring about, to happen or cause to happen or occur, take place. sa

tiko na adi senitoa hisbiscus festival (in suva, in august, annually) is taking place, is underway. na bose ka vakayacori tiko mai tubou. the meeting (or conference) that is taking place at tubou. na veika era rawa ni vakayacora na kai idia ena noda vanua the things the indians can
(bring about) in our country.

n. end, final outcome or result. na iyacoyaco ni gaunisala the end of the road. ia, sa kena iyacoyaco oqori. yes, that is what was going to happen in the end. veiyacovi v., n. sexual intercourse (the appropriate, polite word), to have sexual intercourse. mate dewa ni
sexually transmitted disease (std).
n. widow. yadi, yadia . (ra, northern tailevu) v. to raise up. . v. to take yadia na kuro take the pot. yadia mai
bring the pot here.
(lau) n. chiefly title that precedes a woman ’s name, the same as adi but in a form more common in
in earlier times, and also in lau where names or words beginning with “a” are often preceded by a “y”. thus the man ’s name aminiasi can become yaminiasi in lau.
v. adj , awake, to wake up. sa yadra! good morning ! sa yadra tu. he/she is awake. vakayadrati

wake him up. yadra bogi stay awake during most of the night, work at night. yadra cecekala wake with a start, suddenly . yadra, yadrava v. to guard, watch for (something). yadra n . guard, watchman. vakayadra, vakayadrava v. to to wake up (someone). ivakayadra n. alarm clock. an old usage of this word was in describing the function of turukawa, the pet
of legendary god degei, that woke the chief each day at nakauvadra. the ciri twins killed the
at a place called conua, enraging degei who expelled them. this is one of the best known of all fijian legends.
v. to be on the look-out for (something, someone).
n. forehead. syn. edre-na. idiom: yadre toso having a bulging, prominent, expressive forehead.
n. mature bull, sometimes referred to as bulumakau yadru. cattle are an introduced species. it is difficult to explain the origin of this word.
each one, one each , every one. na veitamata yadua each and every person. yadudua absolutely
(for more than one).
v. to do it one by one.
one at a time, each one. lako yadudua to go one at a time. yadudua ni rua na itubutubu ni
each one of the two parents. yarurua two at a time, each couple.
. n. adj . useful, necessary. e sega na kena yaga. it is of no use. tawa yaga useless.
. n. spider shell, (french “lambis”), edible monovalve shellfish, usually found in dead coral areas,
hidden by camouflage colour of algae on upper side with bright orange underside, lambis lambis, strombidae. two types, smaller one sold in the market, flesh removed with a fork. larger one,

lambis, is usually thrown in a fire, destroying the shell which is then cracked to remove the flesh. if boiled, the flesh becomes too touch and chewy. perhap s because of the rubbery texture, some fijians believe that eating yaga helps children who have speech problems (lisping, for example). such
at the end is tied with a string, and by this it is hung, till gravity causes the shell to drop.
a spooky process to watch with the eyes looking at you. feel guilty and cruel? syn. (west, parts

(ega). -yaga . as a suffix, occasionally used at the end of a place-name, to indicate “place”. on kabara island, for example, there is a village nakeleyaga, meaning “place useful for anchoring” boats. vakayaga-taka v. to use. na kena vakayagataki its use, how it is used.
n. gratuity , usually money, given in appreciation of service rendered. tipping, however, is not at all the custom in fij i. this is an uncommon word of dubious origin.
(or) nagai n. a tree, canarium spp., burseraceae, the pili nut, an edible nut. fiji has fewer species
root crops such as sweet potato and cassava. it has never been a significant item in the
diet ; any fijian variety has a small nut with a very tough shell, not really a practical food. generally now known in vanuatu as nangai, in papua-new guinea as galip, and it is there sometimes

as a commercial nut-crop for eating and for oil production. in indonesia the name is kanari nut, and in parts of southeast asia, the pili nut. other fij ian names are kaucina, kaunicina, kaunigai, the gai referring to the nut, as in yagai. the name kaucina “lamp-tree”, indicates the usefulness of the
or resin as lamp-oil, though that type of artefact was unknown in the highlands of viti levu. oil lamps, using coconut oil, were introduced on the coast by early polynesians.
n., v. fornication. syn. veidauci, a more formal, proper word.
n. physical body of human or animal, hull of a boat. o ira na yago vulavula the (many) white people. vakaukauwa yago physical fitness.
n. corpse. mate dead.
n. forest tree to meters, dacrydium nidulum, podocarpaceae, a gymnosperm, branching only at

n. evening meal. vakayakavi v. to have dinner. formerly this meal was the second of the day, eaten just before sunset. there was no formal lunch, only occasional snacks in the middle of the day. breakfast (katalau) was usually eaten at home only after several hours of early morning work in the food garden. it is now more common to have three meals a day, following the european custom. yaki, yakia v. to beat up, give a hiding, a brutal beating and kicking. this may be done by several men on a single victim. syn. buturaka .

n. a kind of fijian sweet pudding (vakalolo) usually made of grilled breadfruit, sometimes with taro or cassava, with sweet, uncooked coconut cream (lolodroka), not caremelised coconut cream (lolo buta).
n. handful. yaku, yakuta, yakulaka (or) yakuraka v. to pick out something with the fingers, usually food such as a piece of fish or pudding, something soft.

v. to be sloppily done, as of some work, clothes worn, package wrapped, dance exhibition (meke). yala, yalana v. to limit, to stop short, as of a road that ends abruptly, or of a meeting with limited time. na iyalayalani n. the limitation. ka ni yalani n. contraceptive. na itutu me yala ga vei au. the (chiefly)
ends with me. (such a statement was made by ma’afu saying the the title of tui lau would be
after his death. colonial authorities, however, revived the title for ratu sukuna and it was continued by ratu kamisese mara.)

n. limit, extend to, end (of some physical thing). tawa yalani limitless; iyalayala boundary limit, border. yala, yalaca . v. to extend to (some point of time or physically, to some place), to end in the sense of
(than some boundary). iyalayala n. boundary. yala, yalaca . v. to bring fire from one place to another with a burning brand, or to re-arrange burning logs in a fire to burn better, burn longer.
v. to promise, to set a limit. veiyalayalati mutually promised, agreed, contracted. na
the covenant (bib.). na veiyalayalati vou the new testament. veiyalayalati n. committment, contract. ivola ni veiyalayalati n. written contract.
v. to divide in two parts. yala-limataka divide in five parts.
n. locally owned exclusive fishing grounds, many of them registered formally with the native land trust board. syn. qoliqoli.
n. boundary, limit, border. see yala, yalaca.
n. woman. dabe vakayalewa to sit like a woman, with both legs to one side. gone yalewa girl.
womaniser, "girl chaser". mata yalewa man who always has eyes for the women. lewa!

address used by men to a woman who is not higher in the social hierarchy than they are. lasa vakayalewa (of a woman) lesbian. yalewa saumi n. prostitute (very formal expression, little used.) vakasalewalewa n ., adj . male homosexual, effeminate man.
ninini n . lit. "trembling woman ", an attractive wild plant, lycopodium cernuum, fairly common, used as body decoration at dances, or in flower arrangements.
adj . absent, away, missing, lost, and by extension, dead. sa yali ko koya he/she is gone, absent; sa
it's not here, it's lost, gone. sa yali makawa. it (or he/she) has been gone, missing, a long time. syn. (west) reva . (rewa) leca.
v. to walk here and there, wander about, pointlessly, doing nothing.

v. to spend (or waste) money, time, or to lose (anything). vakayalia na ilavo spend money, lose money or fail to keep track of it. vakayalia na nomu gauna (anglicism) to waste your time. yalo n. spirit, mind, emotion or temperament, soul, ghost. yalo tabu holy ghost. yalo bula spirit of the dead. na bula vakayalo the spiritual life. yalo vinaka please, if you please (as an expression that
alone, preceding a formal request). kaci yalo a mental illness when a person is not conscious of what he/she does or says.
. adj . capable of reason, said of a child mature enough to be responsible. . (church) adj . spiritual.
a prefix in word combinations, describing a person ’s temperament (indicated by the second part of
of the same mind, in agreement.

. n. “party person”, always interested in music, parties, opposite sex . . n. modern term for a “goon squad”, a group of ruffians who try to intimidate an outspoken deviant. yalo, yalova v. to beckon (to someone), to wave (the hand), this is normally a hand motion, or hand and
motion, with the palm facing down, not up, as is european custom. it would be rude to beckon
n. egg. formerly many fijians did not eat birds’ eggs, considering them disgusting, like saliva,

would say, though some would eat cooked turtle eggs. yaloka ni gata type of solanum plant. ("snake's eggs"). yaloka ni mata-na eyeball(s). yaloka ni vonu lit. turtle eggs, fig. fried balls of leavened flour dough, often eaten sopped in tea as a breakfast. vakalutu yaloka to lay eggs.
n. eyeball. dakudaku ni mata eyelid.
adj . timid, lacking courage.
adj . reasonable, sensible, humble, respectful.
adj . brave, courageous.
n. holy spirit, holy ghost.
adj . quick to anger.
if you please, in good spirit. this is essentially a rather formal request to be of “good mind”. as a single word it usually precedes a formal request.
adj . immature, lacking self-discipline and willpower, irresponsible.
n. (anglicism) cinema, movies. properly, fully , the expression is iyaloyalo yavala . retio
television. sara iyaloyalo to go to the movies.
n. pupil (of the animal or human eye).
n. (anglicism) moving pictures, movies.
v. to wave (the hand, in greeting, farewell, etc.). yaloyalo vei koya . wave to him/her.

n. a common, wild, leafy-vine epiphyte that grows on trees, dumb cane, toga plant, epipremnum pinnatum, araceae, used by europeans as a decorative plant in fiji and elsewhere. the sap is poisonous and even small quantities have a numbing effect on the skin. (more is seriously dangerous.) a pet parrot died from pecking at the leaves next to its cage. yalu dina var. with very large leaves, the
fibre of stem called wa me, twine for weaving baskets (sova). yalu tagane var. with entire leaves, yalu yalewa var. with leaves having holes.

(archaic) n. ancient var. of yaqona, much prized for ceremonial presentations. the root is very large and grows horizontally in the ground, making it easy to harvest. yalu, yaluma v. to reach out the arm to grab, grasp (something). yaluyalu-lala v. to reach out to take, but fail, empty-handed. lala empty . yaluma . n., v . grief, to grieve, anguish, in agony, mental or physical. yaluma . v. (archaic) to retrieve, take, pass over to someone. usually heard as yaluma mai get for me, retrieve for me. yamaraka . v. to smash, knock down, as of a tree in a gale, a house in a hurricane. yamaraka . v. to beat up, give a beating to someone. syn. buturaka.
n. military scout sent ahead to check the situation, spy (wartime). yamata vuni secret spy, an anglicism sometimes seen in translated novels.
. n. tongue. yameleka n. tonsils. dara yame or salayame v. to stick out the tongue. yame ni

n. flame, or “tongue” of fire. idiom: yame-sa "sweet-talk ", liar. yame-na . n. blade (knife, razor, axe). yameyame . v., adj . talkative, voluble, glib , liar, smart and rapid talker. yameyame . n. flames. na yameyame ni buka the flames from the fire. yameca . v. to light up something, with light from a lamp, or flame from fire. yameca . v. to deceive with clever, ingratiating words.

v. to be very unsettled in manner and feelings. yamo . v. to go about at night, feeling one ’s way in the dark. yamo . v. to fight at night in the dark. yamoraka beat up people under cover of darkness. fij ians would often attack from a concealed position, using the element of surprise. yamo, yamoca, yamoraka v. to stroke with the hand, to massage with the hand, to grope for something with the hand. by extension, to “feel” a sexual partner.
v. to toss and turn, as in unsettled sleep.
v. to use one ’s hand(s) to find one’s way around.

n. small patch of submerged reef separate from the main reef. motu is an ancient polynesian word for “island”. idiom: sa vakaua ga na yamotu. said of a powerful person with great strength or great appetite. lit. the reef-patch has waves. yana, yanaka v. to wash off, clean off, especially shellfish, swilled about in water to separate them and remove sand or dirt. yanaka v. to grope around with the hand, feeling for something, perhaps furtively. see yamo, yamoca. yanaraka v. to scatter around as in flapping out a mat to remove crumbs, or dust. also as in spreading out
of yaqona drying out in the sun. yanaraka na lewe ni yaqona ena vata. to spread out the pieces of kava on the drying-platform.
away (from the speaker, following a verb). lako yani go away (from where the speaker is located).
(in the direction of the speaker).
n. small island, now used only as a place-name for small islands, such as the tiny island where the shangri-la fij ian resort is located at the nadroga coast of southwestern viti levu.

n. small island (not normally used for large islands like viti levu). yanu is an ancient protopolynesian word for “small island”. occasionally yanuyanu might appear as the name of an island. there is one such just offshore of lomaloma, vanua balavu island. yaqa, yaqava v. to sneak along crouching, usually to attack. fijians are expert at such attack s, excellent as jungle fighters, exemplified when they were fighting communists in malaysia.

of its natural gene pool), used as a ceremonial and social beverage. the polynesian name of

(eng.) n. yacht. syn. iota. fiji traditional calendar
lived by a lunar calendar with a climax of human activity around february, when they

begin to harvest the cultivated yam harvest. this is a “noble” crop, yams being prestigious at ceremonial food presentations. cultivated yams were also the only basic food that could be stored in their
state and kept for use much later in the year. all other vegetables and fruits were perishable. the
yabaki signified the annual yam harvest and that has been adopted as the word for “year”. first

isevu of some crops were presented to chiefs or priests, and more modernly also the christian church. fijians never counted the years and had no concept of a weekly cycle. there were no dates on their calendar and no names of days, only lunar monthly cycles. they simply followed a seasonal calendar

signalled by the flowering or fruiting of certain plants, or by the sea, with the changes in the available seafood. highlanders of viti levu are of a different culture. they did not cultivate or honour yams to the degree of coastal fijians. and they had no seafood, only aquatic life from the rivers. much of this calendar does not apply to them. all too often when people speak of fijians they are talking only of fij ians around
in history and biology, and the practical matter of what fruits, vegetables or seafoods may be found at the market.
calendar. when we name the equivalents in european months it is only approximate. also, in fact, the tropical climate has inherently variable seasons, not dependent only on the phase of the moon.
list here what is supposed to happen in each lunar month in following the seasons. most of these
have been cribbed from various previous writings; only a few are are original with this author.

Fijian Idioms (listed in alp habetical order) B . baca kuita . Literally translated as “octopus bait.” The expression is usually used when enticing someone. In conversation, someone may ask in jest, “O iko baca cava?” What bait (enticement) are you using? The reply is, “Na baca kuita.” This implies something entici ng that will surely succeed! 2. E sega ni dua na nomu baigani eke . Literally translated as, “It’s none of your eggplant” meaning ‘It’s none of your business.’ 3. Vunibaka ga sa tevoro . Literally translated as “The banyan tree is the devil!” It means that a big person may on first impression look very impressive but beware as he can be dangerous too. 4. mate vakabalabala . Literally translated as “To die like a fern tree.” The idiom indicates that someone died childless, like a fern tree (balabala). The fern that grows abundantly in forests does not have suckers or seeds.(Editor’s Note: It grows through its spores.) 4. Vosa mada o iko, e rovu e liu na batimu. Literally translated as, “Please go ahead and talk, because your teeth sprouted first.” The expression is usually said in jest when two people talk at the same time. One will say, “Please go ahead and speak. You are my elder. Your teeth sprouted first.” 5. Basu bawara. Literally translated as “To break open an unopened flower shoot.” Bawara is the spathe (unopened flower shoot) of the coconut palm. A spathe bursts open as it dries and matures, and reveals its flowers. It means that a person (usually young) wants to brea k free of discipline in the home, village or the workplace. The Flying Fox a fruit and insect eating bat is the inspiration of 4 idioms. 6. (Slang idiom used especially amongst young people) beka ni bogi Literally translated as ‘the night bat” (Slang) A person who is active only at night. 7. lako vakabeka or vuka vakabeka. Literally translated as ”to go like a bat” or “to fly like a bat.” It means that someone takes his own food when going on a journey or that someone finds one’s own food and thus is not dependent on others. (Sometimes it has subtle connotations of someone being westernized!) 8. samusamu beka means that someone stands around idly while others are working. 9. tuvani vaka bati ni beka Literarily translated as “Very neatly arranged like the teeth of a bat. 10. gunu wai ni bele . Literally translated as ”To drink the boiled juice of the hibiscus spinach (bele) (which is unpleasant!).” It means that someone is humiliated and / or being reprimanded. The reef heron (belo) is the subject of 2 idioms: 11. domo ni belo Literally translated as “The cry of a heron.” It means that an individual has had a very light meal, perhaps just a cup of tea for lunch or dinner. 12. Sa suru na belo . Literally translated as “The heron has sneezed.” It means that the allocated work for the day is done. It has been completed. Fijian idioms on bici, the banded rail bird . 13. Ketekete ni bici na lomalagi translated as “It is a fine clear sky with light strips of cloud, like the breast of the bici.” 14. E lauta na bici na kena ikolo . Literally translated as “The bici bird gets hit with the projectile meant for it.” It means that someone gets a just punishment. The punishment fits the crime. Fijian idioms on the ‘coconut’ shell cup . 15. bilo cicila . Literally translated as, “Like a leaky cup.” It means that someone cannot be relied upon. 16. bilo vata (usually said in jest as in Daru sa bilo vata or Kedaru sa bilo vata . Usually said as a joke by a man to a woman “Let’s share the same cup” It implies that they have much in common, and should have an intimate relationship. 17. vakabilo (Literally translated as “S/he has a cup.” It means that someone has occult powers derived from pouring a cup of yaqona (kava) to an evil spirit. Another meaning of vakabilo in a positive sense is someone of chiefly rank who has been installed by having been given the official cup to drink. The individual has been given the ceremonial cup of yaqona ( vagunuvi ) to the chiefly position s/he has been installed in. 18. Dui seva ga na bua ka tea : Translation: You will reap the bua (frangipani) that you planted. Meaning: You will reap what you sow. (Usually said when something bad happens to someone whose evil/negative behavior may have caused it.) 19. Maca na wai ka boko na buka . Literally translated as “There’s no more water and the fire has gone out” It means that the cupboard is bare in the sense that there is no more kava, tobacco, food etc. 20. vakabula ika levu Literally translated as “The big one (fish) got away”. It means that you missed your big chance. The big fish was saved (by escaping). . 21. kana buta Literally translated as “to eat food that is cooked and ready.” This refers to a person who expects to be fed or rewarded as if he had helped substantially in the work activity. 22. Au butuka tu . Literally translated as “I am standing (on) my ground.” This is a defiant response (said in a good natured way) to someone from another place who is acting with presumption. This might be said by a Vitilevu highlander to someone from the smaller islands, a kai-yanuyanu. 23. butu cala Literally translated as “to put one’s foot on slippery ground.” It means that someone makes a gaffe of impropriety in traditional custom, such as speaking out of turn in a formal situation. C 1. kana cagi Literally translated as “to eat wind!” It means that someone has nothing to eat. 2. tamata vakaicaqe Literally translated as “someone capable of kicking!” It implies that a particular individual is an influential person. Implies that one is rich and powerful. 3. caqe veva Literally translated as “to kick paper around” It means “to fool around, doing nothing.” 4. Sulukui na vudi, e dua e cika? Sulukui na vudi refers to ripening stalks of plantain that are cut and covered with leaves on the ground but they do not deceive the kikau birds. e dua e cika? Does someone have conjunctivitis? (That s/he is not able to see that the ripe plantain are concealed with leaves) It means (in conversation) ,”You are trying to hide something from me as if I cannot see clearly. 5. malumalumu vakacikinovu Literally translated as “looks weak like a centipede.” It means that a man may looks harmless but is dangerous like a centipede, 6. cokacoka na vula . Literally translated as “trying to strike the moon (vula) with a spear.” It means that one is too ambitious, striving for the impossible, This idiom often refers to a person desiring a certain romantic match that is impossible. 7. E dua ga na siga ni cola qele . Literally translated as “It is only one day of carrying soil.” Meaning as expressed in a conversation: “Let’s try hard to finish this work; we surely can finish it today.” 8. curu vale Literally translated as “to enter a house or to sneak into a house. Meaning: To abscond with someone else’s spouse. Refers to a man taking another man’s wife or taking in a mistress. 9. tamata curu -suka Literally translated as “person entering in and out” Meaning: An offender who is regularly in and out of prison. D These two idioms use the word “daba”. It refers to mud lobsters and rock lobster crabs having their seasonal egg bearing plump (with considerable meat) around April. . Sa daba o iko! Meaning: “You’re awesome, you’re great!” 2. Sa daba! Meaning: “That’s marvelous” 3. vaka e cavu na dalo matua . Literally translated as ‘like mature taro being pulled out of the ground easily.” It means that something is done easily and quickly. 4. Na dalo e tei ka vakasulina . Literally translated as “Taro is planted and has suckers.” It means that a woman has responsible, caring parents who must be approached traditionally by a suitor seeking her hand in marriage. 5. kena na isamu ni dawa . Literally translated as “S/he has been struck by the projectile used to bring down lychee fruits from the tree.” It means that someone has suffered from someone else’s actions. . 6. Tara na dike ni niu qai kevu . Literally translated as “touched the ‘dike’, the central branch of a bunch of coconuts then fell.” This assumes that someone climbed a coconut tree (to get coconuts) but quit the effort after reaching close to the (dike) goal. It means that someone did not accomplish what he set out to do. 7. vakuli-ni-dilo: Literally translated as ‘like the bark of a dilo tree. (Dilo is a seaside tree used for making wooden drums, furniture, boat keel) It means that a man is very strong, implying that he is not easily hurt and having tough skin. 8. waiwai dilo : Literally translated as “dilo oil.” (The dilo tree has nuts that is used for oil for body massage.) It means “to sweet -talk someone to get what is wanted.” 9. Na nomu dodomo sa vaka e dua na tiaina dreu . Literally translated as “Your love is like a ripe banana.” It means that it is ‘puppy love’. It won’t last. 10. dramica na vusi Literally translated as, “The cat licked it up” It means that some food or item is so relished / desirable that it disappeared quickly, or something has been stolen secretly. 11. Sa dre ko Malolo . Literally translated as, “Malolo is pulling” or “The sun is setting.” (Malolo Island is in the west of Vitilevu Island, off the coast of Nadi). It may mean that something is coming to an end. It can also mean that time is being wasted in idleness. 12. Dromu na vula, dromu vata kei na kena kalokalo . Literally translated as. “The moon sets and its star sets with it.” It means that the death of one individual can quickly bring on the death of a spouse, close relative or associate. 13. Dua mai keri! Literally translated as “Your turn!” (to speak, tell a story, entertain the group). This is said by someone, in a pleasant tone, who has just finished telling a yarn. 14. Dui mate ga ena nona ucu ni vatu . Literally translated as “Each person is ready to die defending his home territory.” It means that there is a close attachment to the land and when cornered, a Fijian will fight to the death. 15. ucu mai duru : Literally translated as “Taking out of the knee” or “Like a nose growing out of the knee. It means that it is fiction, unbelievable, a tall tale. F & G 1. Meca i a fika ga, or Meca qo na fika ga . Literally translated as, “The thing is to think it through” It means that ‘things will be done or solved in due time (by hook or by crook!) 2. sili vaka ga (siliva vaka maina) Literally translated as “to bathe like a duck or a mynah bird” Usually said to a child who takes a quick, superficial bath, not bathing properly. 3. dau gasa yawa Literally translated as “always wanting something that is inaccessible.” This is often said of an individual who stays away from home, feeling more comfortable elsewhere. 4. Daru qai laki sota ki na gasau leka . Literally translated as, “We will meet next at the place where the short reed grows (at Bua, supposedly the jumping -off place to the next world, after death). It means that we are not likely to meet again 5. silima na gau ni dali Literally translated as “to dive for the middle (rather than the end) of a rope fallen in the water.” It means that someone intrudes in a conversation. 6. Mo muria na nomu gaunisala . Literally translated as “You should follow your appropriate path .It means that one is to follow proper protocol, as in the formalities of entering a village, or approaching a chief. K 1. vakaseuta na bure ni kadi Literally translated as “to scratch into an ant’s nest” It means “to stir up trouble.” 2. Sa kala na matanisiga . Literally translated as “The sun is setting.” It means that someone is getting old. 3. matai via kana vuaka . Literally translated as “The carpenter who wants to eat pork” It refers to a person who might pretend to be hard working and skilled but is only interested in how the work is rewarded. 4. Sa kua la na kana! Literally translated as “I do not feel like eating.” It implies playful flattering words said to a pretty girl. It implies that she is so pretty that an admirer looking at her has filled his stomach up that he does not feel like eating. . Kana, kana! Ka o lakova mai . Literally translated as “Eat, eat! That’s what you came for.” Usually said when teasing a friend who is passing by during a meal and is invited to join in.]

source_text: Vosa mada o iko, e rovu e liu na batimu
target_text: [Literal Translation:Please go ahead and talk, because your teeth sprouted first. ] [Meaning:The expression is usually said in jest when two people talk at the same time. One will say, Please go ahead and speak. You are my elder. Your teeth sprouted first]
[Literal Translation:The banyan tree is the devil!] [Meaning:that a big person may on first impression look very impressive but beware as he can be dangerous too.]
[Literal Translation:dilo oil. (The dilo tree has nuts that is used for oil for body massage.)] [Meaning:to sweet-talk someone to get what is wanted.]

[Literal Translation:to fake the work of cutting grass, weeds, by just knocking vegetation down to lie against the ground] [Meaning:To pretend to work. This idiom may imply that someone is not telling the whole story, that they are concealing some truth.]
[Literal Translation:to club the carpenter prematurely] [Meaning:To judge a job prematurely before the work has been completed.]
Vakatikitikitaki e vale me 14 na siga.

source_text: You need to self-isolate from the day the first person in your household started symptoms.
target_text: E dodonu mo vakatikitikitaki mai na siga e vakilai kina na tauvimate vei koya e liu ena nomu matavuvale.

source_text: If they have no symptoms, self-isolate from the day of their test.
target_text: Kevaka e sega ni laurai na ivakatakilakila, vakatikitikitaki iko mai na siga e caka kina na veivakatovotovo.

source_text: Self-isolate means stay home and do not go to work, school, or public areas.
target_text: Na ibalebale ni vakatikitikitaki e vale: mo tiko ga e vale ka kakua ni lako icakacaka, vuli se na vanua era sota kina vakalewelevu na lewenivanua.

source_text: Do not use public transport or taxis.
target_text: Kakua ni vakayagataka na tolili ni lewenivanua se na taxi.

source_text: If you experience difficulty breathing, seek immediate medical attention.
target_text: Kevaka o vakila na taqa ni icegu, qarai vakatotolo na veivuke vakavuniwai.

source_text: Persistent chest pain is a warning sign.
target_text: Na mosi ni sarisari e sega ni cegu rawa e dua na ivakatakilakila bibi.

source_text: New confusion or inability to stay awake requires urgent care.
target_text: Na veilecayaki ni vakasama se dredre me yadra vakabalavu e gadreva na veivuke vakatotolo.

source_text: Anyone over 50 or with chronic illness should visit a screening clinic.
target_text: O ira na sivia na 50 na yabaki se tauvi mate vakadua me ra gole ki na screening clinic.

source_text: Dementia describes symptoms caused by changes in how the brain works.
target_text: Dementia e vakamacalataka na ivakatakilakila ena veisau e yaco ena ivakarau ni cakacaka ni mona.

source_text: Alzheimer's disease is the most common type of dementia.
target_text: Na mate na Alzheimers e mataqali dementia e dau kunei vakalevu.

source_text: Anyone can get dementia, but the chance increases with age.
target_text: E rawa ni dua ga e tauvi dementia, ia e tubu na kena loloma ni sa qase na tamata.

source_text: Early signs of dementia can be difficult to notice.
target_text: E dau dredre me kilai na ivakatakilakila taumada ni dementia.

source_text: Many treatable illnesses can cause dementia-like symptoms.
target_text: E levu na mate e rawa ni qaravi ka vakavuna na ivakatakilakila e vaka na dementia.

source_text: See your doctor if you are worried.
target_text: Raica vakatotolo na nomu vuniwai kevaka o lomaleqataka.

source_text: Recent memory loss that affects daily life.
target_text: Na guiguileca vou e vakaleqa na bula wasoma.
Na dredre ni cakava na itavi e kilai tu vakawasoma.
Na leqa ena vosa.
Na lutusobu ni vakatulewa se vakasama cala.

source_text: Vascular dementia is caused by poor blood supply to the brain.
target_text: Na vascular dementia e vakavuna na sega ni veirauti vinaka na dra e drodro ki na mona.

source_text: A third of people with Alzheimer's have a close relative with dementia.
target_text: E rauta ni dua mai na lewe tolu vei ira na tauvi Alzheimers e tiko na wekadra voleka e tauvi dementia.
Na dementia e sega ni dau tubu ga ena kawa.

source_text: If you find out you have dementia, help is available.
target_text: Kevaka o kila ni tauvi iko na dementia, e sa tu na veivuke vei iko.

source_text: You can get information, medication, and support.
target_text: E rawa ni ko rawata na itukutuku, wainimate kei na veitokoni.

source_text: COVID-19 symptoms include cough, fever, runny nose, red eyes, and loss of taste or smell.
target_text: Na ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19 e oka kina na vuvu, katakata, savu ni ucu, wadadamu na mata, kei na sega ni vakila na ikanakana se boica.

source_text: If you have difficulty breathing, go immediately to a health facility.
target_text: Kevaka o vakila ni leka nomu icegu, gole vakatotolo ki na vale ni bula voleka duadua.

source_text: Most people will recover at home without medical intervention.
target_text: E levu na tamata ena rawa ni bula vinaka ga e vale ka sega ni gadreva na qaravi vakavuniwai.

source_text: Workers with symptoms can get a medical certificate for 14 days of self-isolation.
target_text: O ira na tamata cakacaka e vakila na ivakatakilakila era rawa ni taura na ivola ni 14 na siga ni tiko vakatikitiki e vale.

source_text: Testing helps identify people at risk of severe illness.
target_text: Na veivakatovotovo e vukea na kena kilai o ira era beci vakalevu ni rawa ni tauvi mate bibi.

source_text: Screening clinics focus on high-risk groups.
target_text: Na screening clinic e vakatabakidua vei ira era tiko ena iwasewase ni rerevaki vakalevu.

source_text: Self-isolation helps prevent the spread of COVID-19 to others.
target_text: Na tiko vakatikitiki e vale e tarova na kena vakatetei na COVID-19 vei ira na tani.

source_text: Mika is the first case of COVID-19 in this household.
target_text: O Mika e imatai ni tauvimate ni COVID-19 ena nona matavuvale.

source_text: Everyone in the household starts self-isolating on the day Mika's symptoms start.
target_text: Na siga e laurai kina vei Mika na ivakatakilakila era sa tekivu tiko vakatikitiki kina na lewe ni matavuvale taucoko.

source_text: High-risk family members should visit a screening clinic and get tested.
target_text: O ira na lewe ni matavuvale e tiko ena iwasewase ni rerevaki vakalevu me ra gole ki na screening clinic mera qai vakatovotovotaki kina.

source_text: Stop isolating if you have completed 14 days and had no symptoms for at least 3 days.
target_text: Cava na tiko vakatikitiki kevaka sa oti na 14 na siga ka sega ni laurai e dua na ivakatakilakila me 3 na siga sa sivi.
E duidui na kena vakilai na dementia vei ira na tamata yadua.

source_text: Symptoms get worse as brain changes increase.
target_text: Na ivakatakilakila e qai ca vakamalua ni sa levu na veisau ena mona.

source_text: Finding out early that you have dementia means you can get help sooner.
target_text: Na nomu kila taumada ni tauvi iko na dementia e kena ibalebale ni rawa ni vukei iko vakatotolo na kenadau.

source_text: Memory lapses alone do not mean you have dementia.
target_text: Na guiguileca duadua e sega ni kena ibalebale ni sa tauvi iko na dementia.

source_text: Changes in mood and behaviour can be a sign of dementia.
target_text: Na veisau ena ivakarau ni yalo kei na itovo e rawa ni ivakatakilakila ni dementia.

source_text: Abnormal proteins build up in the brain in Alzheimer's disease.
target_text: E tubucake na protein vakatubu mate ena mona ena mate na Alzheimers.

source_text: The symptoms of vascular dementia can start suddenly after a stroke.
target_text: Na ivakatakilakila ni vascular dementia e rawa ni tekivu vakasauri ni oti e dua na stroke.

source_text: For concerns about a family history of dementia, talk to your doctor.
target_text: Kevaka ko leqataka na isema ni vuvale kei na dementia, vosa vua na nomu vuniwai.

source_text: Treatable conditions can cause memory lapses, confusion, and forgetfulness.
target_text: Na veika e rawa ni qaravi e rawa ni vakavuna na sega ni nanuma, veilecayaki kei na guiguileca.

source_text: If you are worried that you or someone you know may have dementia, talk to your healthcare provider.
target_text: Kevaka ko leqataka ni rawa ni tauvi iko se dua ko kila na dementia, vosa vua na nomu vuniwai se vakailesilesi ni tabana ni bula.

source_text: Alzheimers New Zealand has many resources about dementia.
target_text: E tu e Alzheimers New Zealand e vuqa na itukutuku me baleta na dementia.

source_text: These resources can answer many questions you may have.
target_text: Na itukutuku oqori e rawa ni sauma e vuqa na taro e tiko vei iko.

source_text: The booklet About Dementia is a guide for people diagnosed with dementia.
target_text: Na ivola About Dementia e dua na idusidusi vei ira era sa kilai ni tauvi ira na dementia.

source_text: The booklet explains early warning signs and diagnosis of dementia.
target_text: Na ivola e vakamacalataka na ivakatakilakila taumada kei na kena vakadeitaki na dementia.

source_text: The booklet covers brain health and risk reduction.
target_text: E vakamacalataki talega ena ivola na bulabula ni mona kei na kena vakalailaitaki na vakatarausui ni mate.

source_text: The booklet explains what support is available.
target_text: Na ivola e vakaraitaka na mataqali veitokoni e sa tu.
Na ivola e uqeta na kena caka na ituvatuva me baleta na veigauna mai muri.

source_text: COVID-19 testing is targeted to people at high risk of severe illness.
target_text: Na veivakatovotovo ni COVID-19 e vakatabakidua vei ira era tiko ena iwasewase ni rawa ni tauvi mate bibi.

source_text: Testing helps identify and treat people at risk of severe COVID-19.
target_text: Na veivakatovotovo e vukea na kena kilai ka qaravi o ira era beci vakalevu ni rawa ni tauvi COVID-19 bibi.

source_text: If you have mild COVID-19 symptoms and are over 50, you should visit a screening clinic.
target_text: Kevaka o sivia na 50 na yabaki ka vakila na ivakatakilakila lailai ni COVID-19, o dodonu mo gole ki na screening clinic.

source_text: If you have diabetes, heart disease, kidney disease, asthma, or are obese, you are at higher risk.
target_text: Kevaka o tauvi mate ni suka, mate ni uto, mate ni ivi, dau cegu oca se levulevu sivia, o tiko ena iwasewase ni rerevaki vakalevu.

source_text: Pregnant people with COVID-19 symptoms should be tested.
target_text: O ira na bukete tiko ka vakila na ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19 me ra vakatovotovotaki.

source_text: If you test positive, health teams will provide immediate care.
target_text: Kevaka e vakadeitaki ni sa tauvi iko na COVID-19, ena qaravi iko vakatotolo na timi ni Tabana ni Bula.

source_text: If you have mild symptoms and are not high risk, you may not need a test.
target_text: Kevaka e lailai ga na ivakatakilakila ka sega ni tiko ena iwasewase ni rerevaki vakalevu, e rawa ni sega ni gadrevi na veivakatovotovo.

source_text: Most people with mild COVID-19 will fully recover at home.
target_text: E levu era tauvi COVID-19 lailai era na bula vinaka taucoko ga e vale.

source_text: You should isolate from your family members if you have COVID-19 symptoms.
target_text: Kevaka o vakila na ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19, o dodonu mo vakayawaki iko mai vei ira na nomu lewe ni matavuvale.

source_text: Monitor your symptoms closely while you are at home.
target_text: Ni o tiko e vale, vakaraica vakavinaka nodrau veisau na nomu ivakatakilakila.

source_text: If your symptoms become severe, go immediately to a dedicated health facility.
target_text: Kevaka sa bibi na ivakatakilakila, gole vakatotolo ki na vale ni bula e qarava vakatabakidua na COVID-19.

source_text: Workers with symptoms can attend a screening clinic to obtain a medical certificate.
target_text: O ira na tamata cakacaka e vakila na ivakatakilakila era rawa ni gole ki na screening clinic mera taura kina na ivola ni tauvimate.

source_text: A medical certificate can provide 14 days of self-isolation at home.
target_text: Na ivola ni tauvimate e rawa ni solia na 14 na siga ni tiko vakatikitiki e vale.

source_text: Private doctors approved by the Ministry can also provide medical certificates for self-isolation.
target_text: Na vuniwai taucoko era sa vakadonuya na matanitu e rawa tale ga ni solia na ivola ni tiko vakatikitiki e vale.

source_text: If you have diabetes, you are at higher risk of severe COVID-19.
target_text: Kevaka o tauvi mate ni suka, o tiko ena iwasewase ni rerevaki vakalevu ni COVID-19.

source_text: If you have diabetes and COVID-19 symptoms, visit a screening clinic immediately.
target_text: Kevaka o tauvi mate ni suka ka vakila na ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19, gole vakatotolo ki na screening clinic.

source_text: People with diabetes should monitor their symptoms closely during COVID-19.
target_text: Ira era tauvi mate ni suka me ra vakaraica vakavinaka na nodrau ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19.

source_text: If you have heart disease, you are at higher risk of severe COVID-19.
target_text: Kevaka o tauvi mate ni uto, o tiko ena iwasewase ni rerevaki vakalevu ni COVID-19.

source_text: If you have heart disease and COVID-19 symptoms, visit a screening clinic immediately.
target_text: Kevaka o tauvi mate ni uto ka vakila na ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19, gole vakatotolo ki na screening clinic.

source_text: People with heart disease should monitor their symptoms closely during COVID-19.
target_text: Ira era tauvi mate ni uto me ra vakaraica vakavinaka na nodrau ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19.

source_text: If you have kidney disease, you are at higher risk of severe COVID-19.
target_text: Kevaka o tauvi mate ni ivi, o tiko ena iwasewase ni rerevaki vakalevu ni COVID-19.

source_text: If you have kidney disease and COVID-19 symptoms, visit a screening clinic immediately.
target_text: Kevaka o tauvi mate ni ivi ka vakila na ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19, gole vakatotolo ki na screening clinic.

source_text: People with kidney disease should monitor their symptoms closely during COVID-19.
target_text: Ira era tauvi mate ni ivi me ra vakaraica vakavinaka na nodrau ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19.

source_text: If you have asthma, you are at higher risk of severe COVID-19.
target_text: Kevaka o tauvi dau cegu oca, o tiko ena iwasewase ni rerevaki vakalevu ni COVID-19.

source_text: If you have asthma and COVID-19 symptoms, visit a screening clinic immediately.
target_text: Kevaka o tauvi dau cegu oca ka vakila na ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19, gole vakatotolo ki na screening clinic.

source_text: People with asthma should monitor their symptoms closely during COVID-19.
target_text: Ira era tauvi dau cegu oca me ra vakaraica vakavinaka na nodrau ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19.

source_text: If you have obesity, you are at higher risk of severe COVID-19.
target_text: Kevaka o tauvi levulevu sivia, o tiko ena iwasewase ni rerevaki vakalevu ni COVID-19.

source_text: If you have obesity and COVID-19 symptoms, visit a screening clinic immediately.
target_text: Kevaka o tauvi levulevu sivia ka vakila na ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19, gole vakatotolo ki na screening clinic.

source_text: People with obesity should monitor their symptoms closely during COVID-19.
target_text: Ira era tauvi levulevu sivia me ra vakaraica vakavinaka na nodrau ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19.

source_text: People over 50 years of age are at higher risk of severe COVID-19.
target_text: O ira na sivia na 50 na yabaki e ra beci vakalevu ena COVID-19 bibi.

source_text: If you are over 50 and have COVID-19 symptoms, seek medical care.
target_text: Kevaka o sivia na 50 na yabaki ka vakila na ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19, qarai vakatotolo na veivuke vakavuniwai.

source_text: People over 60 years of age are at higher risk of severe COVID-19.
target_text: O ira na sivia na 60 na yabaki e ra beci vakalevu ena COVID-19 bibi.

source_text: If you are over 60 and have COVID-19 symptoms, seek medical care.
target_text: Kevaka o sivia na 60 na yabaki ka vakila na ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19, qarai vakatotolo na veivuke vakavuniwai.

source_text: People over 70 years of age are at higher risk of severe COVID-19.
target_text: O ira na sivia na 70 na yabaki e ra beci vakalevu ena COVID-19 bibi.

source_text: If you are over 70 and have COVID-19 symptoms, seek medical care.
target_text: Kevaka o sivia na 70 na yabaki ka vakila na ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19, qarai vakatotolo na veivuke vakavuniwai.
Qarai vakatotolo na veivuke vakavuniwai.
E tu na valenibula e qarava vakatabakidua na COVID-19.
Na ivakatakilakila e rawa ni oka kina na katakata.
Gole ki na vale ni bula voleka taudua.
Savata wasoma na ligamu.
Tokara na iubinigosu kei na ucu.
Veiyawaki me rua na mita.

source_text: Stay home if you feel unwell.
target_text: Tiko ga e vale kevaka o sega ni bula vinaka.
Vakaraica vakavinaka o ira era tiko ena iwasewase ni rerevaki vakalevu.
Vakatikitiki na lewe ni matavuvale era dau veikilitaki voleka.

source_text: Follow medical advice and isolate at home. (sample 1)

source_text: Vakatikitikitaki e vale me 14 na siga.
target_text: Self-isolate for 14 full days.

source_text: E dodonu mo vakatikitikitaki mai na siga e vakilai kina na tauvimate vei koya e liu ena nomu matavuvale.
target_text: You need to self-isolate from the day the first person in your household started symptoms.

source_text: Kevaka e sega ni laurai na ivakatakilakila, vakatikitikitaki iko mai na siga e caka kina na veivakatovotovo.
target_text: If they have no symptoms, self-isolate from the day of their test.

source_text: Na ibalebale ni vakatikitikitaki e vale: mo tiko ga e vale ka kakua ni lako icakacaka, vuli se na vanua era sota kina vakalewelevu na lewenivanua.
target_text: Self-isolate means stay home and do not go to work, school, or public areas.

source_text: Kakua ni vakayagataka na tolili ni lewenivanua se na taxi.
target_text: Do not use public transport or taxis.

source_text: Kevaka o vakila na taqa ni icegu, qarai vakatotolo na veivuke vakavuniwai.
target_text: If you experience difficulty breathing, seek immediate medical attention.

source_text: Na mosi ni sarisari e sega ni cegu rawa e dua na ivakatakilakila bibi.
target_text: Persistent chest pain is a warning sign.

source_text: Na veilecayaki ni vakasama se dredre me yadra vakabalavu e gadreva na veivuke vakatotolo.
target_text: New confusion or inability to stay awake requires urgent care.

source_text: O ira na sivia na 50 na yabaki se tauvi mate vakadua me ra gole ki na screening clinic.
target_text: Anyone over 50 or with chronic illness should visit a screening clinic.

source_text: Dementia e vakamacalataka na ivakatakilakila ena veisau e yaco ena ivakarau ni cakacaka ni mona.
target_text: Dementia describes symptoms caused by changes in how the brain works.

source_text: Na mate na Alzheimers e mataqali dementia e dau kunei vakalevu.
target_text: Alzheimer's disease is the most common type of dementia.

source_text: E rawa ni dua ga e tauvi dementia, ia e tubu na kena loloma ni sa qase na tamata.
target_text: Anyone can get dementia, but the chance increases with age.

source_text: E dau dredre me kilai na ivakatakilakila taumada ni dementia.
target_text: Early signs of dementia can be difficult to notice.

source_text: E levu na mate e rawa ni qaravi ka vakavuna na ivakatakilakila e vaka na dementia.
target_text: Many treatable illnesses can cause dementia-like symptoms.

source_text: Raica vakatotolo na nomu vuniwai kevaka o lomaleqataka.
target_text: See your doctor if you are worried.

source_text: Na guiguileca vou e vakaleqa na bula wasoma.
target_text: Recent memory loss that affects daily life.

source_text: Na dredre ni cakava na itavi e kilai tu vakawasoma.
target_text: Difficulty performing familiar tasks.
Problems with language.

source_text: Na lutusobu ni vakatulewa se vakasama cala.
target_text: Poor judgment or decision-making.

source_text: Na vascular dementia e vakavuna na sega ni veirauti vinaka na dra e drodro ki na mona.
target_text: Vascular dementia is caused by poor blood supply to the brain.

source_text: E rauta ni dua mai na lewe tolu vei ira na tauvi Alzheimers e tiko na wekadra voleka e tauvi dementia.
target_text: A third of people with Alzheimer's have a close relative with dementia.

source_text: Na dementia e sega ni dau tubu ga ena kawa.
target_text: Dementia is not always inherited.

source_text: Kevaka o kila ni tauvi iko na dementia, e sa tu na veivuke vei iko.
target_text: If you find out you have dementia, help is available.

source_text: E rawa ni ko rawata na itukutuku, wainimate kei na veitokoni.
target_text: You can get information, medication, and support.

source_text: Na ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19 e oka kina na vuvu, katakata, savu ni ucu, wadadamu na mata, kei na sega ni vakila na ikanakana se boica.
target_text: COVID-19 symptoms include cough, fever, runny nose, red eyes, and loss of taste or smell.

source_text: Kevaka o vakila ni leka nomu icegu, gole vakatotolo ki na vale ni bula voleka duadua.
target_text: If you have difficulty breathing, go immediately to a health facility.

source_text: E levu na tamata ena rawa ni bula vinaka ga e vale ka sega ni gadreva na qaravi vakavuniwai.
target_text: Most people will recover at home without medical intervention.

source_text: O ira na tamata cakacaka e vakila na ivakatakilakila era rawa ni taura na ivola ni 14 na siga ni tiko vakatikitiki e vale.
target_text: Workers with symptoms can get a medical certificate for 14 days of self-isolation.

source_text: Na veivakatovotovo e vukea na kena kilai o ira era beci vakalevu ni rawa ni tauvi mate bibi.
target_text: Testing helps identify people at risk of severe illness.

source_text: Na screening clinic e vakatabakidua vei ira era tiko ena iwasewase ni rerevaki vakalevu.
target_text: Screening clinics focus on high-risk groups.

source_text: Na tiko vakatikitiki e vale e tarova na kena vakatetei na COVID-19 vei ira na tani.
target_text: Self-isolation helps prevent the spread of COVID-19 to others.

source_text: O Mika e imatai ni tauvimate ni COVID-19 ena nona matavuvale.
target_text: Mika is the first case of COVID-19 in this household.

source_text: Na siga e laurai kina vei Mika na ivakatakilakila era sa tekivu tiko vakatikitiki kina na lewe ni matavuvale taucoko.
target_text: Everyone in the household starts self-isolating on the day Mika's symptoms start.

source_text: O ira na lewe ni matavuvale e tiko ena iwasewase ni rerevaki vakalevu me ra gole ki na screening clinic mera qai vakatovotovotaki kina.
target_text: High-risk family members should visit a screening clinic and get tested.

source_text: Cava na tiko vakatikitiki kevaka sa oti na 14 na siga ka sega ni laurai e dua na ivakatakilakila me 3 na siga sa sivi.
target_text: Stop isolating if you have completed 14 days and had no symptoms for at least 3 days.

source_text: E duidui na kena vakilai na dementia vei ira na tamata yadua.
target_text: Dementia is different for everyone.

source_text: Na ivakatakilakila e qai ca vakamalua ni sa levu na veisau ena mona.
target_text: Symptoms get worse as brain changes increase.

source_text: Na nomu kila taumada ni tauvi iko na dementia e kena ibalebale ni rawa ni vukei iko vakatotolo na kenadau.
target_text: Finding out early that you have dementia means you can get help sooner.

source_text: Na guiguileca duadua e sega ni kena ibalebale ni sa tauvi iko na dementia.
target_text: Memory lapses alone do not mean you have dementia.

source_text: Na veisau ena ivakarau ni yalo kei na itovo e rawa ni ivakatakilakila ni dementia.
target_text: Changes in mood and behaviour can be a sign of dementia.

source_text: E tubucake na protein vakatubu mate ena mona ena mate na Alzheimers.
target_text: Abnormal proteins build up in the brain in Alzheimer's disease.

source_text: Na ivakatakilakila ni vascular dementia e rawa ni tekivu vakasauri ni oti e dua na stroke.
target_text: The symptoms of vascular dementia can start suddenly after a stroke.

source_text: Kevaka ko leqataka na isema ni vuvale kei na dementia, vosa vua na nomu vuniwai.
target_text: For concerns about a family history of dementia, talk to your doctor.

source_text: Na veika e rawa ni qaravi e rawa ni vakavuna na sega ni nanuma, veilecayaki kei na guiguileca.
target_text: Treatable conditions can cause memory lapses, confusion, and forgetfulness.

source_text: Kevaka ko leqataka ni rawa ni tauvi iko se dua ko kila na dementia, vosa vua na nomu vuniwai se vakailesilesi ni tabana ni bula.
target_text: If you are worried that you or someone you know may have dementia, talk to your healthcare provider.

source_text: E tu e Alzheimers New Zealand e vuqa na itukutuku me baleta na dementia.
target_text: Alzheimers New Zealand has many resources about dementia.

source_text: Na itukutuku oqori e rawa ni sauma e vuqa na taro e tiko vei iko.
target_text: These resources can answer many questions you may have.

source_text: Na ivola About Dementia e dua na idusidusi vei ira era sa kilai ni tauvi ira na dementia.
target_text: The booklet About Dementia is a guide for people diagnosed with dementia.

source_text: Na ivola e vakamacalataka na ivakatakilakila taumada kei na kena vakadeitaki na dementia.
target_text: The booklet explains early warning signs and diagnosis of dementia.

source_text: E vakamacalataki talega ena ivola na bulabula ni mona kei na kena vakalailaitaki na vakatarausui ni mate.
target_text: The booklet covers brain health and risk reduction.

source_text: Na ivola e vakaraitaka na mataqali veitokoni e sa tu.
target_text: The booklet explains what support is available.

source_text: Na ivola e uqeta na kena caka na ituvatuva me baleta na veigauna mai muri.
target_text: The booklet encourages future planning.

source_text: Na veivakatovotovo ni COVID-19 e vakatabakidua vei ira era tiko ena iwasewase ni rawa ni tauvi mate bibi.
target_text: COVID-19 testing is targeted to people at high risk of severe illness.

source_text: Na veivakatovotovo e vukea na kena kilai ka qaravi o ira era beci vakalevu ni rawa ni tauvi COVID-19 bibi.
target_text: Testing helps identify and treat people at risk of severe COVID-19.

source_text: Kevaka o sivia na 50 na yabaki ka vakila na ivakatakilakila lailai ni COVID-19, o dodonu mo gole ki na screening clinic.
target_text: If you have mild COVID-19 symptoms and are over 50, you should visit a screening clinic.

target_text: If you have diabetes, heart disease, kidney disease, asthma, or are obese, you are at higher risk.

source_text: O ira na bukete tiko ka vakila na ivakatakilakila ni COVID-19 me ra vakatovotovotaki.
target_text: Pregnant people with COVID-19 symptoms should be tested.

target_text: If you test positive, health teams will provide immediate care.

target_text: If your symptoms become severe, go immediately to a dedicated health facility.

source_text: O ira na tamata cakacaka e vakila na ivakatakilakila era rawa ni gole ki na screening clinic mera taura kina na ivola ni tauvimate.
